mples of ________ energy resources.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"renewable\",\n        \"sustainable\",\n        \"non-renewable\",\n        \"eco-friendly\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Mining of minerals can lead to ________, damaging soil and water quality.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"pollution\",\n        \"reforestation\",\n        \"conservation\",\n        \"farming\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Excessive farming can lead to a loss of ________ in the soil.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"fertility\",\n        \"pollution\",\n        \"oxygen\",\n        \"water\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"Gold and silver are mainly used for making ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"furniture\",\n        \"jewelry\",\n        \"paper\",\n        \"cement\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"Bauxite is the primary mineral used to produce ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"steel\",\n        \"copper\",\n        \"aluminum\",\n        \"iron\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Soil erosion occurs when topsoil is removed due to ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"excessive rainfall\",\n        \"deforestation\",\n        \"urbanization\",\n        \"all of the above\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Recycling helps in reducing the excessive use of ________ resources.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"water\",\n        \"natural\",\n        \"pollution\",\n        \"oxygen\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"The Sundarbans forest is famous for its ________ trees.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"mangrove\",\n        \"oak\",\n        \"pine\",\n        \"teak\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Natural resources are materials obtained from nature that help humans survive and develop.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Renewable resources cannot be naturally replaced over time.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Non-renewable resources take millions of years to form and can be exhausted if overused.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Forests do not contribute to oxygen production.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"The Amazon Rainforest is the largest tropical rainforest in the world.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Deforestation is a process that increases the number of trees in a forest.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Water covers about 71% of the Earth\'s surface.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"All the water on Earth is drinkable and can be consumed directly.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Rivers, lakes, and groundwater are major sources of freshwater.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Hydropower is generated using coal as the primary source of energy.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"Solar energy is an example of a renewable energy resource.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"Wind energy is produced by burning fossil fuels.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Petroleum is a renewable source of energy.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Land is an essential natural resource used for agriculture, housing, and industries.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Soil erosion is beneficial for agriculture and helps plants grow faster.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"Gold and silver are classified as mineral resources.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"Bauxite is used to manufacture aluminum.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Coal and petroleum are the primary sources of renewable energy.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Iron is commonly used in construction and manufacturing.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"Excessive mining can lead to deforestation and land degradation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"Deforestation helps prevent soil erosion and maintains land fertility.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"Recycling can help conserve natural resources and reduce waste.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"The Sundarbans forest is well-known for its mangrove trees and Royal Bengal Tigers.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"The Black Forest in Germany is named because of its dark soil and desert-like conditions.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"Water pollution is mainly caused by dumping chemicals and waste into water bodies.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"Urbanization has no impact on land resources.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"Excessive use of fertilizers in farming can lead to soil degradation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"Renewable resources such as solar and wind energy can never run out.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"Geothermal energy is generated from the heat inside the Earth\'s surface.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"Land pollution occurs when excessive waste and chemicals accumulate on land.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"Groundwater is the water that is found deep under the Earth\'s surface.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"Mining activities have no impact on the environment.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"Fossil fuels are an unlimited source of energy and will never run out.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"Agricultural land is mainly used for farming and growing crops.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"Planting more trees can help reduce the effects of deforestation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"Plastic waste is biodegradable and does not harm the environment.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"Climate change is caused by excessive use of fossil fuels and pollution.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"Oceans and seas contain the majority of Earth\'s freshwater supply.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"Using energy-efficient appliances can help conserve energy resources.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"Reusing and recycling materials can help reduce environmental pollution.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"Iron ore is commonly found in Jharkhand and Odisha in India.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"Forest fires can occur naturally or due to human activities.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"Overuse of groundwater can lead to water scarcity and depletion.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"Hydropower plants generate electricity using sunlight.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"Reforestation involves planting trees in areas where forests have been destroyed.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"The Three Gorges Dam in China is a major producer of wind energy.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"Urbanization often leads to loss of agricultural land and deforestation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"Soil pollution is caused by excessive use of chemicals, fertilizers, and pesticides.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"Climate change has no effect on natural resources.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"The conservation of natural resources is important for sustainable development.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n  ]\n  ',12,5),(15,'2.2-Renewable, Non-Renewable, and Cyclic Resources','<div class=\"container\">\n    <h2>2.2 Renewable, Non-Renewable, and Cyclic Resources</h2>\n    <p>\n      Resources are things we get from nature to help us survive and improve our lives. They are classified into three types: Renewable, Non-Renewable, and Cyclic Resources.\n    </p>\n    \n    <h3>1. Renewable Resources</h3>\n    <p>These resources can be replenished naturally over time.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Solar Energy</strong> – Unlimited energy from the sun for electricity and heating.</li>\n      <li><strong>Wind Energy</strong> – Wind turbines generate power.</li>\n      <li><strong>Water (Hydropower)</strong> – Flowing water generates electricity in dams.</li>\n      <li><strong>Forests</strong> – Trees regrow if planted properly.</li>\n      <li><strong>Wildlife</strong> – Animals and fish populations recover if managed well.</li>\n      <li><strong>Agricultural Crops</strong> – Crops like wheat and rice can be replanted.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p><strong>Key Point:</strong> Renewable resources remain sustainable if used wisely.</p>\n  \n    <h3>2. Non-Renewable Resources</h3>\n    <p>These resources take millions of years to form and cannot be replenished quickly.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Fossil Fuels:</strong> Coal (electricity), Petroleum (fuel, plastic), Natural Gas (cooking, heating).</li>\n      <li><strong>Metals and Minerals:</strong> Gold, Silver, Copper (jewelry, electronics), Iron, Aluminum (buildings, vehicles).</li>\n      <li><strong>Uranium:</strong> Used in nuclear power plants.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p><strong>Key Point:</strong> Once used, non-renewable resources are gone forever.</p>\n  \n    <h3>3. Cyclic Resources</h3>\n    <p>These resources can be reused after undergoing natural or artificial processes.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Water:</strong> Reused through the water cycle, wastewater purification.</li>\n      <li><strong>Oxygen & CO₂:</strong> Maintained through photosynthesis and respiration.</li>\n      <li><strong>Metals:</strong> Iron, Aluminum, and Copper can be recycled.</li>\n      <li><strong>Paper & Plastic:</strong> Can be processed and reused.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p><strong>Key Point:</strong> Cyclic resources reduce waste and conserve materials.</p>\n    \n    <h3>Comparison of Resources</h3>\n    <table class=\"table table-bordered\">\n      <thead>\n        <tr>\n          <th>Type of Resource</th>\n          <th>Can it be Replenished?</th>\n          <th>Examples</th>\n          <th>Important Fact</th>\n        </tr>\n      </thead>\n      <tbody>\n        <tr>\n          <td>Renewable</td>\n          <td>Yes</td>\n          <td>Sunlight, Wind, Water, Forests</td>\n          <td>Needs proper management.</td>\n        </tr>\n        <tr>\n          <td>Non-Renewable</td>\n          <td>No</td>\n          <td>Coal, Oil, Natural Gas, Gold</td>\n          <td>Cannot be replaced in our lifetime.</td>\n        </tr>\n        <tr>\n          <td>Cyclic</td>\n          <td>Can be reused</td>\n          <td>Water, Oxygen, Metals</td>\n          <td>Helps in conservation.</td>\n        </tr>\n      </tbody>\n    </table>\n  \n    <h3>Why is This Important?</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Wise use of resources prevents wastage.</li>\n      <li>Focusing on renewable and cyclic resources protects the environment.</li>\n      <li>Reducing dependence on non-renewable resources avoids depletion.</li>\n      <li>Recycling and sustainable practices ensure resources for future generations.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>Conclusion</h3>\n    <p>\n      Resources are essential for life. We must use them responsibly: renewable resources should be managed well, non-renewable resources should be conserved, and cyclic resources should be reused efficiently. This helps protect our planet. ??\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a renewable resource?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Coal\",\n        \"Petroleum\",\n        \"Solar Energy\",\n        \"Natural Gas\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Which resource takes millions of years to form and cannot be replenished?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Wind Energy\",\n        \"Forests\",\n        \"Coal\",\n        \"Hydropower\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"What type of resource is water when used in the hydrological cycle?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Renewable\",\n        \"Non-Renewable\",\n        \"Cyclic\",\n        \"None of the above\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an example of a cyclic resource?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Gold\",\n        \"Water\",\n        \"Coal\",\n        \"Natural Gas\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Which renewable resource is generated using wind turbines?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Solar Energy\",\n        \"Hydropower\",\n        \"Geothermal Energy\",\n        \"Wind Energy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which non-renewable resource is used in nuclear power plants?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Coal\",\n        \"Uranium\",\n        \"Natural Gas\",\n        \"Iron\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Why are non-renewable resources considered unsustainable?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"They are expensive to use\",\n        \"They take millions of years to form and cannot be replenished\",\n        \"They are not used by industries\",\n        \"They cannot be extracted\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is NOT an example of a non-renewable resource?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Coal\",\n        \"Petroleum\",\n        \"Wind Energy\",\n        \"Natural Gas\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following metals can be recycled and reused?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Aluminum\",\n        \"Coal\",\n        \"Natural Gas\",\n        \"Petroleum\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"How can we conserve non-renewable resources?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"By using them excessively\",\n        \"By replacing them with renewable resources\",\n        \"By ignoring recycling techniques\",\n        \"By using more fossil fuels\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"_______ resources are those that can be naturally replenished over time.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Non-renewable\",\n        \"Renewable\",\n        \"Cyclic\",\n        \"Fossil\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Non-renewable resources take _______ of years to form and cannot be replaced quickly.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Hundreds\",\n        \"Thousands\",\n        \"Millions\",\n        \"Dozens\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Cyclic resources can be _______ and used again.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Destroyed\",\n        \"Reused\",\n        \"Burned\",\n        \"Discarded\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Solar energy is a type of _______ resource.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Renewable\",\n        \"Non-renewable\",\n        \"Cyclic\",\n        \"Fossil\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Coal and petroleum are examples of _______ resources.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Renewable\",\n        \"Cyclic\",\n        \"Non-renewable\",\n        \"Unlimited\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"The continuous movement of water through evaporation, condensation, and precipitation makes it a _______ resource.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Non-renewable\",\n        \"Cyclic\",\n        \"Exhaustible\",\n        \"Fossil\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Wind turbines generate electricity using _______ energy.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Solar\",\n        \"Wind\",\n        \"Geothermal\",\n        \"Nuclear\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Gold and silver are examples of _______ resources.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Renewable\",\n        \"Non-renewable\",\n        \"Cyclic\",\n        \"Recyclable\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Water is considered a cyclic resource because it undergoes a natural process known as the _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Rock cycle\",\n        \"Carbon cycle\",\n        \"Water cycle\",\n        \"Photosynthesis\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Iron and aluminum can be classified as both _______ and recyclable resources.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Renewable\",\n        \"Cyclic\",\n        \"Non-renewable\",\n        \"Infinite\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    }\n]\n  ','\n[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Renewable resources can be naturally replenished over time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Non-renewable resources can be replaced quickly after they are used.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Solar energy is a non-renewable resource.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Wind energy is considered a renewable resource.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Coal is a non-renewable resource because it takes millions of years to form.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Water is an example of a cyclic resource because it can be reused through the water cycle.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Gold and silver are renewable resources.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Forests can be classified as renewable resources if they are replanted after cutting trees.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Petroleum is a cyclic resource.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Oxygen and carbon dioxide are cyclic resources because they are continuously exchanged between plants and animals.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"Fossil fuels, such as coal and oil, are formed in a short period of time.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"Hydropower is generated using renewable water resources.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Plastic is a renewable resource because it can be recycled.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Non-renewable resources can be exhausted if overused.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Geothermal energy is a type of renewable resource.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"Cyclic resources can be reused after going through natural or artificial processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"Metal ores such as iron and aluminum can be classified as cyclic resources when they are recycled.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Agricultural crops are non-renewable resources.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Uranium is used in nuclear power plants and is a renewable resource.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"Deforestation affects the availability of renewable resources like forests and wildlife.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"Recycling helps conserve non-renewable resources by reducing waste.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"Once metals are extracted from the Earth, they can never be reused.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"Water can be classified as both a renewable and cyclic resource.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"Natural gas is a renewable resource because it is found in nature.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"Cyclic resources help in reducing waste and conserving natural resources.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"Wind turbines use fossil fuels to generate electricity.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"Hydropower plants use the movement of water to generate electricity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"Petroleum and coal are formed from dead plants and animals over millions of years.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"Paper made from trees is a non-renewable resource.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"Overuse of fossil fuels contributes to environmental pollution.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"Non-renewable resources can be renewed by planting more trees.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"Coal mining can cause deforestation and habitat destruction.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"Solar panels convert sunlight into electrical energy.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"Wind power is generated using non-renewable resources.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"Natural resources are important for human survival and industrial growth.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"Cyclic resources can never be reused or recycled.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"Iron and aluminum can be recycled multiple times without losing their properties.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"Water pollution affects the usability of water as a cyclic resource.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"Sustainable use of natural resources means using them in a way that preserves them for future generations.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"Overconsumption of non-renewable resources will not have any negative impact on the environment.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"The burning of fossil fuels releases greenhouse gases into the atmosphere.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"Recycling paper helps in reducing deforestation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"Plastic is a cyclic resource because it can be completely broken down naturally.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"Forest conservation helps maintain renewable resources like trees and wildlife.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"Fossil fuels such as coal and oil are renewable because they are naturally formed underground.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"Recycling aluminum cans saves energy and reduces the need for mining.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"The use of renewable energy sources helps reduce dependency on fossil fuels.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"Sustainable farming ensures that agricultural land remains fertile for future generations.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"Deforestation does not affect the water cycle.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"Using public transportation can help conserve non-renewable resources like petroleum.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  \n',12,5),(16,'2.3-Causes and Effects of Depletion of Resources','<div>\n    <h2>2.3 Causes and Effects of Depletion of Resources</h2>\n    <p>Natural resources are the things we get from nature, such as water, forests, minerals, fossil fuels, and land. These resources are essential for our survival and economic growth. However, many of these resources are being used up at a very fast rate, leading to a serious problem called resource depletion.</p>\n    \n    <h3>1. What is Resource Depletion?</h3>\n    <p>Resource depletion means that natural resources are being used up faster than they can be replaced. Some resources, like trees, can be replenished if we plant new ones, but others, like coal and petroleum, take millions of years to form.</p>\n    <p>Imagine you have a piggy bank with ₹1000, but you keep withdrawing money every day without adding anything back. Eventually, you will run out of money. This is exactly what happens with natural resources if we do not use them wisely.</p>\n    \n    <h3>2. Causes of Resource Depletion</h3>\n    <ul>\n        <li><strong>Overpopulation:</strong> More people mean more demand for food, water, energy, and land.</li>\n        <li><strong>Overconsumption and Wastage:</strong> Many people waste resources by using more than they need.</li>\n        <li><strong>Deforestation:</strong> Cutting down trees for wood, paper, and agriculture reduces forest resources.</li>\n        <li><strong>Industrialization and Urbanization:</strong> Factories use large amounts of raw materials like coal, iron, and oil.</li>\n        <li><strong>Mining and Extraction of Fossil Fuels:</strong> Resources like coal, oil, and natural gas are extracted for energy.</li>\n        <li><strong>Pollution and Environmental Damage:</strong> Pollution contaminates resources, making them unusable.</li>\n        <li><strong>Climate Change:</strong> Global warming leads to droughts, affecting freshwater supply.</li>\n        <li><strong>Poor Agricultural Practices:</strong> Overuse of soil for farming without proper care makes the land infertile.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>3. Effects of Resource Depletion</h3>\n    <ul>\n        <li><strong>Water Scarcity:</strong> Shortage of clean water for drinking, farming, and industries.</li>\n        <li><strong>Loss of Biodiversity:</strong> Animals and plants lose their habitats due to deforestation and pollution.</li>\n        <li><strong>Energy Crisis:</strong> As oil, coal, and gas run out, energy costs increase.</li>\n        <li><strong>Food Shortages:</strong> Poor soil and lack of water reduce food production.</li>\n        <li><strong>Global Warming and Climate Change:</strong> More carbon dioxide emissions due to deforestation and fossil fuel use.</li>\n        <li><strong>Economic Problems:</strong> When resources are scarce, industries shut down, leading to job losses.</li>\n        <li><strong>Conflict and Wars:</strong> Countries may fight over resources like water and oil.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>4. Examples of Resource Depletion in Real Life</h3>\n    <ul>\n        <li><strong>Deforestation in the Amazon Rainforest:</strong> Trees are cut down for farming and wood.</li>\n        <li><strong>Water Crisis in Cape Town, South Africa (2018):</strong> Severe drought led to water shortages.</li>\n        <li><strong>Overfishing in the Oceans:</strong> Too many fish are caught, reducing fish populations.</li>\n        <li><strong>Oil Crisis in the Middle East:</strong> High demand for oil and limited supply.</li>\n        <li><strong>Soil Degradation in India:</strong> Overuse of fertilizers reduced soil fertility.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>Conclusion</h3>\n    <p>Resource depletion is a serious issue caused by human activities like overpopulation, deforestation, and pollution. It leads to many problems, such as water shortages, loss of biodiversity, climate change, and economic crises.</p>\n    <p>To solve this issue, we must use resources wisely by practicing conservation, recycling, and sustainable living. Simple actions like turning off lights when not needed, planting trees, and reducing plastic use can help protect natural resources for future generations.</p>\n    <p><strong>? \"Save resources today for a better tomorrow!\" ?</strong></p>\n</div>','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is resource depletion?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"The increase in natural resources over time\",\n        \"The overuse of natural resources faster than they can be replaced\",\n        \"The conservation of natural resources\",\n        \"The process of recycling resources\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a cause of resource depletion?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Overpopulation\",\n        \"Conservation efforts\",\n        \"Sustainable practices\",\n        \"Using renewable energy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a non-renewable resource?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Solar energy\",\n        \"Wind energy\",\n        \"Coal\",\n        \"Forests\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"How does deforestation contribute to resource depletion?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"By increasing soil fertility\",\n        \"By reducing oxygen production and destroying habitats\",\n        \"By promoting sustainable agriculture\",\n        \"By increasing biodiversity\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is NOT a cause of resource depletion?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Overconsumption\",\n        \"Mining and extraction\",\n        \"Pollution\",\n        \"Recycling\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which human activity is a major cause of soil degradation?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Overuse of chemical fertilizers\",\n        \"Reforestation\",\n        \"Water conservation\",\n        \"Sustainable farming\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"How does overfishing affect the environment?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"It increases fish populations\",\n        \"It disrupts the marine ecosystem\",\n        \"It reduces water pollution\",\n        \"It increases ocean biodiversity\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Which country faced a major water crisis in 2018?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"India\",\n        \"Brazil\",\n        \"South Africa\",\n        \"Canada\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"What happens when fossil fuel reserves run low?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Energy prices increase\",\n        \"Air pollution decreases\",\n        \"Greenhouse gas emissions drop\",\n        \"Energy becomes more sustainable\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an example of sustainable resource use?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Cutting down trees without replanting\",\n        \"Using solar energy instead of coal\",\n        \"Drilling for more oil\",\n        \"Increasing fossil fuel consumption\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Resource depletion occurs when natural resources are used up _______ than they can be replaced.\",\n      \"options\": [\"slower\", \"faster\", \"equally\", \"randomly\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Overpopulation increases the demand for food, water, energy, and _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"gold\", \"land\", \"oxygen\", \"plastic\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Leaving the tap open while brushing your teeth is an example of _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"conservation\", \"overconsumption\", \"recycling\", \"sustainability\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Deforestation leads to reduced _______ production.\",\n      \"options\": [\"hydrogen\", \"carbon dioxide\", \"oxygen\", \"helium\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Industrialization increases the demand for raw materials like coal, iron, and _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"silver\", \"wood\", \"oil\", \"copper\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Oil drilling in oceans can damage marine life and lead to _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"floods\", \"oil spills\", \"earthquakes\", \"volcanic eruptions\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Pollution contaminates resources, making them _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"cheaper\", \"valuable\", \"unusable\", \"renewable\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Melting glaciers reduce the amount of _______ available.\",\n      \"options\": [\"fossil fuels\", \"freshwater\", \"air\", \"solar energy\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Excessive use of chemical fertilizers can destroy _______ quality.\",\n      \"options\": [\"air\", \"soil\", \"water\", \"metal\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Shortage of clean water affects drinking, farming, and _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"industries\", \"entertainment\", \"forests\", \"mining\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"Loss of forests leads to the loss of animal _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"colors\", \"habitats\", \"sounds\", \"sizes\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"Energy crisis occurs due to the depletion of _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"fossil fuels\", \"plants\", \"wind\", \"rainwater\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Droughts in India lead to lower crop production and increased _______ prices.\",\n      \"options\": [\"gold\", \"food\", \"oil\", \"diamond\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Deforestation and burning fossil fuels increase _______ emissions.\",\n      \"options\": [\"oxygen\", \"carbon dioxide\", \"hydrogen\", \"helium\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Shortage of resources can lead to job losses and economic _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"growth\", \"problems\", \"stability\", \"increase\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Resource depletion occurs when natural resources are used up faster than they can be replaced.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Overpopulation decreases the demand for food, water, energy, and land.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Leaving the tap open while brushing your teeth is an example of resource conservation.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Deforestation leads to a decrease in oxygen production.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Industrialization increases the consumption of raw materials like coal, iron, and oil.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Oil drilling in oceans has no impact on marine life.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Pollution can make natural resources unusable.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Melting glaciers increase the amount of freshwater available.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Excessive use of chemical fertilizers improves soil quality permanently.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Water scarcity affects industries as well as farming and drinking water supply.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"Loss of forests does not affect animal habitats.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"An energy crisis can occur due to the depletion of fossil fuels.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Droughts in India have no impact on food prices.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Burning fossil fuels does not contribute to climate change.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Shortage of natural resources can lead to job losses and economic issues.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  ',12,5),(17,'2.4-Energy Forms Conventional and Non-Conventional Energy Sources','<div class=\"energy-section\">\n    <h1>2.4 Energy Forms: Conventional and Non-Conventional Energy Sources</h1>\n    <p>Energy is essential for everything we do in our daily lives. From switching on a light bulb to driving a car, energy is needed everywhere. However, energy can come from different sources, which are broadly classified into Conventional Energy Sources and Non-Conventional Energy Sources.</p>\n    \n    <h2>1. Conventional Energy Sources</h2>\n    <p>Conventional energy sources are those that have been used for a long time and are commonly found in nature. These sources are mostly non-renewable, meaning they take millions of years to form and cannot be replenished once used.</p>\n    \n    <h3>Examples of Conventional Energy Sources</h3>\n    <ul>\n        <li><strong>Coal</strong>\n            <ul>\n                <li>Coal is a black or brownish rock that contains carbon.</li>\n                <li>It is burned in power plants to generate electricity.</li>\n                <li>Used in industries for heating and producing steel.</li>\n                <li><strong>Example:</strong> Coal-fired power plants produce electricity for cities.</li>\n            </ul>\n        </li>\n        <li><strong>Petroleum (Oil)</strong>\n            <ul>\n                <li>Found deep underground in the form of crude oil.</li>\n                <li>Refined into petrol, diesel, and kerosene.</li>\n                <li>Used in cars, airplanes, and industries.</li>\n                <li><strong>Example:</strong> Petrol is used in cars and bikes for transportation.</li>\n            </ul>\n        </li>\n        <li><strong>Natural Gas</strong>\n            <ul>\n                <li>A cleaner fuel compared to coal and oil.</li>\n                <li>Used for cooking in homes (LPG), generating electricity, and in industries.</li>\n                <li><strong>Example:</strong> LPG cylinders used in kitchens contain natural gas.</li>\n            </ul>\n        </li>\n        <li><strong>Hydropower (Dams)</strong>\n            <ul>\n                <li>Electricity generated from flowing water.</li>\n                <li>Dams store water and release it through turbines to generate power.</li>\n                <li><strong>Example:</strong> The Bhakra Nangal Dam in India generates hydroelectricity.</li>\n            </ul>\n        </li>\n        <li><strong>Nuclear Energy</strong>\n            <ul>\n                <li>Energy produced from splitting atoms (nuclear fission).</li>\n                <li>Highly powerful and used for large-scale electricity production.</li>\n                <li><strong>Example:</strong> The Tarapur Nuclear Power Plant in India produces nuclear energy.</li>\n            </ul>\n        </li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>2. Non-Conventional Energy Sources</h2>\n    <p>Non-conventional energy sources are also called renewable energy sources because they are naturally replenished and never run out. These are considered environment-friendly as they do not cause pollution.</p>\n    \n    <h3>Examples of Non-Conventional Energy Sources</h3>\n    <ul>\n        <li><strong>Solar Energy</strong>\n            <ul>\n                <li>The sun’s rays are converted into electricity using solar panels.</li>\n                <li>Used in homes, industries, and even to power satellites.</li>\n                <li><strong>Example:</strong> Solar water heaters and solar street lights work using sunlight.</li>\n            </ul>\n        </li>\n        <li><strong>Wind Energy</strong>\n            <ul>\n                <li>Large windmills (or wind turbines) convert wind into electricity.</li>\n                <li>Requires strong winds to generate power.</li>\n                <li><strong>Example:</strong> Wind farms in Tamil Nadu and Gujarat produce electricity for nearby cities.</li>\n            </ul>\n        </li>\n        <li><strong>Geothermal Energy</strong>\n            <ul>\n                <li>The heat from deep inside the Earth is used to produce electricity.</li>\n                <li>Used in areas with volcanic activity or hot springs.</li>\n                <li><strong>Example:</strong> The United States and Iceland use geothermal power to generate electricity.</li>\n            </ul>\n        </li>\n        <li><strong>Tidal Energy</strong>\n            <ul>\n                <li>The rise and fall of ocean water (tides) are used to generate electricity.</li>\n                <li>Special dams (barrages) are built to trap water during high tides and release it during low tides.</li>\n                <li><strong>Example:</strong> The Kislaya Guba Tidal Power Station in Russia generates tidal energy.</li>\n            </ul>\n        </li>\n        <li><strong>Biomass Energy</strong>\n            <ul>\n                <li>Uses plant and animal waste to generate energy.</li>\n                <li>Biogas plants convert cow dung and kitchen waste into gas for cooking.</li>\n                <li><strong>Example:</strong> Many villages in India use gobar gas plants to produce energy.</li>\n            </ul>\n        </li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>Comparison Between Conventional and Non-Conventional Energy Sources</h2>\n    <table border=\"1\">\n        <tr>\n            <th>Feature</th>\n            <th>Conventional Energy</th>\n            <th>Non-Conventional Energy</th>\n        </tr>\n        <tr>\n            <td>Availability</td>\n            <td>Limited (Non-renewable)</td>\n            <td>Unlimited (Renewable)</td>\n        </tr>\n        <tr>\n            <td>Pollution</td>\n            <td>Causes pollution (CO₂ emissions)</td>\n            <td>Environment-friendly</td>\n        </tr>\n        <tr>\n            <td>Cost</td>\n            <td>High cost due to extraction and processing</td>\n            <td>Lower cost after initial setup</td>\n        </tr>\n        <tr>\n            <td>Examples</td>\n            <td>Coal, Petroleum, Natural Gas</td>\n            <td>Solar, Wind, Biomass, Geothermal</td>\n        </tr>\n    </table>\n    \n    <h2>Conclusion</h2>\n    <p>To meet our energy needs, we have depended on conventional energy sources for a long time. However, these sources are limited and cause pollution. This is why the world is shifting towards non-conventional energy sources, which are cleaner, renewable, and sustainable for the future. By using solar panels, windmills, and biogas plants, we can reduce our dependence on fossil fuels and help protect our environment.</p>\n</div>','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a conventional energy source?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Solar Energy\",\n        \"Wind Energy\",\n        \"Coal\",\n        \"Geothermal Energy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"What is the main disadvantage of conventional energy sources?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"They are renewable\",\n        \"They cause pollution and are limited\",\n        \"They are cost-effective\",\n        \"They do not produce carbon emissions\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Which energy source is obtained by burning fossil fuels?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Solar Energy\",\n        \"Nuclear Energy\",\n        \"Wind Energy\",\n        \"Petroleum\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is NOT a non-conventional energy source?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Wind Energy\",\n        \"Geothermal Energy\",\n        \"Coal\",\n        \"Biomass Energy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"What is the primary fuel used in coal-fired power plants?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Natural Gas\",\n        \"Coal\",\n        \"Solar Energy\",\n        \"Wind Energy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which energy source is derived from the Sun?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Nuclear Energy\",\n        \"Tidal Energy\",\n        \"Solar Energy\",\n        \"Geothermal Energy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"What is the main benefit of non-conventional energy sources?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"They are cheaper to install\",\n        \"They are renewable and environment-friendly\",\n        \"They generate more power than coal\",\n        \"They are easy to transport\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an example of a biomass energy source?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Nuclear Power\",\n        \"Biogas\",\n        \"Natural Gas\",\n        \"Petroleum\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Which energy source relies on the movement of water?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Wind Energy\",\n        \"Hydropower\",\n        \"Solar Energy\",\n        \"Geothermal Energy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Which of these energy sources is NOT affected by weather conditions?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Wind Energy\",\n        \"Solar Energy\",\n        \"Geothermal Energy\",\n        \"Hydropower\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Conventional energy sources are mostly ________ in nature.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"renewable\",\n        \"non-renewable\",\n        \"unlimited\",\n        \"sustainable\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"The main disadvantage of conventional energy sources is that they cause ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"pollution\",\n        \"more energy generation\",\n        \"low costs\",\n        \"less demand\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Coal is an example of a ________ energy source.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"renewable\",\n        \"non-conventional\",\n        \"non-renewable\",\n        \"tidal\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Solar energy is a form of ________ energy source.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"conventional\",\n        \"non-conventional\",\n        \"fossil fuel\",\n        \"nuclear\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Petroleum is refined to produce fuels such as ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"coal and biomass\",\n        \"diesel and petrol\",\n        \"solar and wind\",\n        \"water and air\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"The energy generated from the movement of wind is called ________ energy.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"solar\",\n        \"hydropower\",\n        \"wind\",\n        \"tidal\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Hydropower is generated using the force of ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sunlight\",\n        \"wind\",\n        \"water\",\n        \"biomass\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Nuclear energy is produced through a process called nuclear ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"fusion\",\n        \"fission\",\n        \"conduction\",\n        \"convection\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Energy obtained from organic waste materials is known as ________ energy.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"solar\",\n        \"biomass\",\n        \"wind\",\n        \"geothermal\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"The energy derived from the Earth\'s internal heat is called ________ energy.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"solar\",\n        \"wind\",\n        \"geothermal\",\n        \"tidal\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that conventional energy sources are mostly non-renewable.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that solar energy is a type of conventional energy source.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Coal is a renewable energy source.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Hydropower is generated using the force of moving water.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Petroleum is refined to produce fuels such as diesel and petrol.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Wind energy is generated using wind turbines.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Biomass energy is derived from non-organic materials.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Nuclear energy is produced through the process of nuclear fission.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Tidal energy is produced using the movement of ocean tides.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Geothermal energy is generated from the heat inside the Earth.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  ',12,5),(18,'2.5-Present Global Energy Use and Future Demands','<div class=\"energy-content\">\n    <h2>2.5 Present Global Energy Use and Future Demands</h2>\n    <p>\n      Energy is essential for everything we do, from cooking food to running industries, powering homes, and transportation. As the world\'s population grows and technology advances, the demand for energy increases. In this topic, we will explore how energy is currently used worldwide, what types of energy sources we rely on, and how future demands will shape the way we produce and consume energy.\n    </p>\n  \n    <h3>1. Present Global Energy Use</h3>\n    \n    <h4>A. Sources of Energy</h4>\n    <p>Today, the world depends on different types of energy sources, which can be broadly classified into renewable and non-renewable energy sources.</p>\n    \n    <h5>1. Non-Renewable Energy Sources (Fossil Fuels)</h5>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Coal:</strong> Used for electricity generation in power plants.</li>\n      <li><strong>Oil (Petroleum):</strong> Used for transportation (cars, airplanes), and manufacturing products like plastics.</li>\n      <li><strong>Natural Gas:</strong> Used for heating homes and generating electricity.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Many countries, including the USA, China, and India, rely heavily on coal to generate electricity. In 2023, about 60% of global electricity came from fossil fuels.</p>\n    \n    <h5>2. Renewable Energy Sources</h5>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Solar Energy:</strong> Energy from the sun, used in solar panels.</li>\n      <li><strong>Wind Energy:</strong> Energy from the wind, used in wind turbines.</li>\n      <li><strong>Hydropower:</strong> Energy from flowing water, used in dams.</li>\n      <li><strong>Geothermal Energy:</strong> Energy from the Earth\'s heat, used in power plants.</li>\n      <li><strong>Biomass Energy:</strong> Energy from organic materials like wood, agricultural waste, and animal manure.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Countries like Norway and Brazil generate a large portion of their electricity using hydropower, reducing dependence on fossil fuels.</p>\n  \n    <h4>B. Sectors that Use Energy</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Industrial Sector:</strong> Factories use energy to manufacture goods like steel, cement, and chemicals.</li>\n      <li><strong>Transportation Sector:</strong> Vehicles, airplanes, ships, and trains use energy.</li>\n      <li><strong>Residential Sector:</strong> Homes use energy for lighting, cooking, heating, and cooling.</li>\n      <li><strong>Commercial Sector:</strong> Offices, malls, hospitals, and schools require energy.</li>\n      <li><strong>Agricultural Sector:</strong> Energy is needed for irrigation, tractors, and crop processing.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>2. Future Energy Demand</h3>\n    \n    <h4>A. Reasons for Increasing Energy Demand</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Population Growth:</strong> More people means more energy needed for homes, transportation, and industries.</li>\n      <li><strong>Urbanization:</strong> More people moving to cities increases electricity demand.</li>\n      <li><strong>Technological Advancements:</strong> Industries and digital technology require additional power.</li>\n      <li><strong>Increase in Living Standards:</strong> More people use modern appliances and cars.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>3. Challenges in Meeting Future Energy Demand</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Depletion of Fossil Fuels:</strong> Oil, coal, and gas reserves will eventually run out.</li>\n      <li><strong>Environmental Impact:</strong> Burning fossil fuels causes pollution and climate change.</li>\n      <li><strong>Energy Inequality:</strong> Some regions have energy shortages.</li>\n      <li><strong>Infrastructure Limitations:</strong> Some countries lack technology for energy production.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>4. Solutions for Sustainable Energy Future</h3>\n  \n    <h4>A. Transition to Renewable Energy</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Solar & Wind Farms:</strong> Expanding these can provide clean electricity.</li>\n      <li><strong>Hydropower Projects:</strong> Dams can generate electricity without pollution.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>B. Energy Efficiency</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Smart Homes & Buildings:</strong> Using LED lights and energy-efficient appliances reduces consumption.</li>\n      <li><strong>Electric Vehicles (EVs):</strong> Switching from petrol to electric cars reduces fuel consumption.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>C. Energy Conservation</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Public Transport:</strong> Encouraging buses, trains, and metros reduces energy use.</li>\n      <li><strong>Recycling & Reducing Waste:</strong> Recycling materials saves energy.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>Conclusion</h3>\n    <p>\n      The world’s energy demand is rising, and we need to transition towards clean and renewable energy sources to sustain future generations. Governments, businesses, and individuals must work together to develop innovative solutions, improve efficiency, and reduce energy waste.\n    </p>\n    <p>\n      <strong>Final Thought:</strong> If we don’t shift towards cleaner energy, future generations might face energy shortages and severe climate changes. The choices we make today will determine the future of our planet!\n    </p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a non-renewable energy source?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Solar Energy\",\n        \"Wind Energy\",\n        \"Coal\",\n        \"Hydropower\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"What percentage of global electricity came from fossil fuels in 2023?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"40%\",\n        \"50%\",\n        \"60%\",\n        \"70%\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Which country relies heavily on hydropower for electricity?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"India\",\n        \"Brazil\",\n        \"USA\",\n        \"Germany\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Which sector consumes the most energy globally?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Agricultural Sector\",\n        \"Residential Sector\",\n        \"Industrial Sector\",\n        \"Commercial Sector\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"What is the main reason for increasing global energy demand?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Population growth\",\n        \"Decline in coal reserves\",\n        \"Increased use of bicycles\",\n        \"Less urbanization\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which energy source is harnessed using wind turbines?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Solar Energy\",\n        \"Geothermal Energy\",\n        \"Tidal Energy\",\n        \"Wind Energy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is NOT a renewable energy source?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Geothermal Energy\",\n        \"Nuclear Energy\",\n        \"Solar Energy\",\n        \"Wind Energy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"What is one of the major challenges in meeting future energy demands?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Abundant fossil fuel reserves\",\n        \"Unlimited renewable resources\",\n        \"Depletion of fossil fuels\",\n        \"Low energy consumption\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Which energy source is generated using the Earth\'s heat?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Solar Energy\",\n        \"Tidal Energy\",\n        \"Geothermal Energy\",\n        \"Hydropower\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"What is a major disadvantage of using fossil fuels?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"They cause pollution\",\n        \"They are renewable\",\n        \"They do not produce CO₂\",\n        \"They are free of cost\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"The world’s energy sources are broadly classified into ________ and ________ energy sources.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"renewable, non-renewable\",\n        \"fossil, non-fossil\",\n        \"solar, wind\",\n        \"coal, oil\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"________ is a fossil fuel widely used in power plants for electricity generation.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Solar\",\n        \"Coal\",\n        \"Wind\",\n        \"Geothermal\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Oil, also known as ________, is refined into petrol, diesel, and kerosene.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"natural gas\",\n        \"biogas\",\n        \"crude oil\",\n        \"solar energy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Countries like Norway and Brazil generate a large portion of their electricity using ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"solar energy\",\n        \"hydropower\",\n        \"wind energy\",\n        \"biomass energy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Fossil fuels take ________ of years to form and cannot be replaced easily.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"millions\",\n        \"hundreds\",\n        \"tens\",\n        \"a few\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Natural gas is used for cooking in homes in the form of ________ gas.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"LPG\",\n        \"CNG\",\n        \"kerosene\",\n        \"diesel\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"________ is a cleaner fuel compared to coal and oil.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Petroleum\",\n        \"Natural gas\",\n        \"Nuclear energy\",\n        \"Hydropower\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Electricity produced from the heat inside the Earth is called ________ energy.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"solar\",\n        \"wind\",\n        \"geothermal\",\n        \"biomass\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"The rise and fall of ocean water is used to generate electricity in ________ energy.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"tidal\",\n        \"wind\",\n        \"solar\",\n        \"geothermal\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Energy from organic materials such as wood and agricultural waste is called ________ energy.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"solar\",\n        \"wind\",\n        \"nuclear\",\n        \"biomass\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"One of the biggest sources of renewable energy worldwide is ________ power.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"nuclear\",\n        \"solar\",\n        \"hydropower\",\n        \"coal\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"The two main sectors that consume energy the most are the ________ and ________ sectors.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"residential, agricultural\",\n        \"commercial, industrial\",\n        \"transportation, industrial\",\n        \"agricultural, commercial\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and gas contribute to ________ emissions, causing global warming.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"oxygen\",\n        \"carbon dioxide\",\n        \"nitrogen\",\n        \"helium\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Solar energy is captured using ________ panels.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"wind\",\n        \"hydro\",\n        \"solar\",\n        \"nuclear\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"One major challenge in meeting future energy demand is the ________ of fossil fuels.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"abundance\",\n        \"overuse\",\n        \"depletion\",\n        \"increase\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"Smart meters and LED lighting are examples of ________ energy use.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"wasteful\",\n        \"efficient\",\n        \"costly\",\n        \"temporary\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ is the world\'s largest solar farm, built in the UAE.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Tarbela Dam\",\n        \"Burj Khalifa Solar Plant\",\n        \"Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum Solar Park\",\n        \"Three Gorges Dam\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"________ energy sources do not cause air pollution.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Renewable\",\n        \"Non-renewable\",\n        \"Fossil fuel-based\",\n        \"All of the above\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Public transport systems like buses and trains help in ________ energy consumption.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"reducing\",\n        \"increasing\",\n        \"wasting\",\n        \"doubling\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"Nuclear power plants use the process of nuclear ________ to generate energy.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"fusion\",\n        \"fission\",\n        \"combustion\",\n        \"absorption\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that energy is essential for running industries, homes, and transportation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that fossil fuels are classified as renewable energy sources.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Coal is a non-renewable energy source used primarily for generating electricity in power plants.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Solar energy is a non-renewable energy source that takes millions of years to replenish.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Natural gas is primarily used for heating homes and generating electricity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Countries like Norway and Brazil generate most of their electricity using wind power.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Fossil fuels, such as coal and oil, contribute significantly to global warming.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Hydropower relies on flowing water to generate electricity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Geothermal energy is produced using wind turbines.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Wind energy is generated using solar panels.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"The industrial sector consumes energy to manufacture goods like steel and chemicals.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"Air conditioners and heaters used in homes contribute to high residential energy consumption.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Electric water pumps used in irrigation are an example of energy consumption in the agricultural sector.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Urbanization reduces electricity demand in cities.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"An increase in living standards leads to higher energy consumption.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"Depletion of fossil fuel reserves is a major concern for future energy demands.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"Nuclear energy is a renewable source of energy.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Wind energy contributes to air pollution and carbon emissions.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Many rural areas in Africa still lack access to electricity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"Renewable energy sources are naturally replenished over time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"Infrastructure limitations can prevent some countries from generating enough electricity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"The Three Gorges Dam in China is the largest hydroelectric power plant in the world.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"Recycling materials helps to conserve energy and reduce waste.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"Public transport systems like buses and trains consume more energy than individual cars.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"Electric vehicles (EVs) do not contribute to energy consumption.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"Energy efficiency improvements in homes and buildings can help reduce electricity consumption.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"Fossil fuels will last forever and will never run out.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"Many countries are transitioning to clean and sustainable energy sources to meet future demands.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"The burning of fossil fuels releases carbon dioxide (CO₂), contributing to climate change.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"Using smart meters and LED lights can help in energy conservation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"Solar panels generate electricity even at night.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"The aviation industry is a major consumer of energy in the transportation sector.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"Fossil fuels are a clean source of energy with no environmental impact.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"The UAE has built one of the world\'s largest solar farms, known as the Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum Solar Park.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"Hydropower projects do not produce any electricity.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"Burning biomass energy produces emissions that can impact air quality.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"Energy shortages are a global issue, affecting both developed and developing nations.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"Using electric vehicles reduces the demand for gasoline and diesel.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"Technological advancements have no impact on future energy demand.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"More people moving to cities leads to a decrease in electricity demand.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"The commercial sector does not require energy for lighting, elevators, or air conditioning.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"Energy conservation can help reduce overall energy consumption and costs.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"If we continue using fossil fuels at the current rate, oil reserves may run out by 2050-2070.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"A sustainable energy future depends on the use of only fossil fuels.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"Solar panels convert wind energy into electricity.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"Singapore has an advanced public transport system that helps reduce energy consumption.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"Nuclear power plants generate energy by burning coal.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"The choices we make today regarding energy use will impact future generations.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"Coal is considered a clean and renewable energy source.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"Reducing energy waste and investing in renewables can create a cleaner and more sustainable future.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  ',12,5),(19,'2.6-Energy Conservation – Detailed Explanation with Examples','<div class=\"energy-conservation\">\n    <h2>2.6 Energy Conservation – Detailed Explanation with Examples</h2>\n    \n    <h3>What is Energy Conservation?</h3>\n    <p>Energy conservation means using energy wisely and reducing unnecessary energy use. It involves making efforts to save energy so that we do not waste natural resources like coal, oil, gas, and electricity.</p>\n    <p>Energy is essential for everything we do—turning on lights, cooking food, running machines, and driving vehicles. However, many energy sources, like fossil fuels (coal, petrol, and natural gas), are limited. If we waste them, they will run out, and future generations may not have enough. That’s why conserving energy is important.</p>\n  \n    <h3>Why is Energy Conservation Important?</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Saves Natural Resources:</strong> Non-renewable energy sources like coal and oil take millions of years to form. If we use them carelessly, they may get exhausted.</li>\n      <li><strong>Reduces Electricity Bills:</strong> When we use less energy, we pay lower electricity bills.</li>\n      <li><strong>Protects the Environment:</strong> Burning fossil fuels releases carbon dioxide (CO₂), which causes air pollution and global warming. Energy conservation helps reduce pollution.</li>\n      <li><strong>Ensures Energy Availability for the Future:</strong> If we conserve energy today, future generations will have enough energy to use.</li>\n      <li><strong>Improves Energy Efficiency:</strong> Using energy-saving technologies, like LED bulbs and fuel-efficient vehicles, helps in effective energy utilization.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>Ways to Conserve Energy</h3>\n    \n    <h4>1. At Home</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Switch off lights and fans when not needed.</strong> Example: If you leave a room, turn off the lights and fan to save electricity.</li>\n      <li><strong>Use LED bulbs instead of traditional bulbs.</strong> Example: LED bulbs consume less electricity than old incandescent bulbs.</li>\n      <li><strong>Use energy-efficient appliances.</strong> Example: Refrigerators, air conditioners, and washing machines with a 5-star energy rating consume less power.</li>\n      <li><strong>Reduce water heating costs.</strong> Example: Use solar water heaters instead of electric geysers.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>2. In Transportation</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Use public transport or carpooling instead of personal vehicles.</strong> Example: If five people travel in one car instead of using five separate cars, fuel is saved.</li>\n      <li><strong>Prefer walking or cycling for short distances.</strong> Example: Instead of using a bike for a 1-km distance, walk or cycle to save fuel.</li>\n      <li><strong>Maintain vehicles properly.</strong> Example: Regular servicing of vehicles improves fuel efficiency and reduces fuel consumption.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>3. In Industries</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Use energy-efficient machinery.</strong> Example: Factories should use modern machines that consume less power.</li>\n      <li><strong>Recycle materials.</strong> Example: Recycling paper and plastic reduces energy needed to produce new materials.</li>\n      <li><strong>Optimize production processes.</strong> Example: Running machines only when required can help conserve electricity.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>4. In Offices and Schools</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Use natural light whenever possible.</strong> Example: Open windows and curtains instead of using artificial lights during the daytime.</li>\n      <li><strong>Turn off computers when not in use.</strong> Example: Shutting down computers at the end of the day saves electricity.</li>\n      <li><strong>Use energy-efficient air conditioners and fans.</strong> Example: Keeping ACs at 24°C instead of 18°C saves a lot of energy.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>Examples of Energy Conservation in Real Life</h3>\n    \n    <h4>Smart Homes with Energy Saving Features</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Some modern homes have automatic lights that turn off when no one is in the room.</li>\n      <li>Solar panels are used to generate electricity, reducing dependence on non-renewable energy.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>Eco-friendly Vehicles</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Electric vehicles (EVs) consume less energy and do not cause pollution.</li>\n      <li>Hybrid cars use both fuel and electricity, saving fuel costs.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>Energy-Saving Campaigns</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Governments and organizations run campaigns like \"Earth Hour,\" where people switch off lights for one hour to promote energy conservation.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>Conclusion</h3>\n    <p>Energy conservation is not just about saving electricity; it is about using all forms of energy efficiently. By making small changes in our daily habits—like switching off unnecessary lights, using public transport, and choosing energy-efficient appliances—we can save energy, reduce costs, and protect the environment.</p>\n    <p><strong>Remember:</strong> Every small effort counts! If everyone takes responsibility for saving energy, we can ensure a better future for the next generations. ???</p>\n</div>','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What does energy conservation mean?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using energy wisely and reducing waste\",\n        \"Using as much energy as possible\",\n        \"Only using renewable energy sources\",\n        \"Stopping energy use completely\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Why is energy conservation important?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"It helps waste natural resources\",\n        \"It reduces electricity bills and pollution\",\n        \"It makes people spend more money\",\n        \"It increases fossil fuel consumption\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a non-renewable energy source?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Solar energy\",\n        \"Wind energy\",\n        \"Coal\",\n        \"Hydropower\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a renewable energy source?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Natural gas\",\n        \"Oil\",\n        \"Coal\",\n        \"Solar energy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Which household appliance can help save electricity?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Incandescent bulbs\",\n        \"LED bulbs\",\n        \"Old tube lights\",\n        \"High-energy consuming appliances\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which action can help save electricity at home?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Leaving lights on all day\",\n        \"Using energy-efficient appliances\",\n        \"Keeping fans running in empty rooms\",\n        \"Using electric geysers frequently\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"What is an example of energy conservation in industries?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using outdated machinery\",\n        \"Using energy-efficient machines\",\n        \"Running machines continuously\",\n        \"Using more fossil fuels\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"How can vehicles help conserve energy?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using public transport or carpooling\",\n        \"Driving alone in large vehicles\",\n        \"Keeping engines running unnecessarily\",\n        \"Ignoring vehicle maintenance\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"What is one of the environmental benefits of energy conservation?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Increases air pollution\",\n        \"Reduces carbon dioxide emissions\",\n        \"Makes fossil fuels last longer\",\n        \"Stops climate change\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Which sector consumes energy for lighting, heating, and cooling?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Residential sector\",\n        \"Agricultural sector\",\n        \"Transportation sector\",\n        \"Mining sector\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Energy conservation means using energy ________ and reducing waste.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"carelessly\",\n        \"wisely\",\n        \"recklessly\",\n        \"excessively\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Natural resources like coal, oil, and gas are ________ in supply.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"unlimited\",\n        \"renewable\",\n        \"limited\",\n        \"everlasting\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Burning fossil fuels releases ________ into the atmosphere, causing pollution.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"carbon dioxide\",\n        \"oxygen\",\n        \"nitrogen\",\n        \"hydrogen\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Using LED bulbs instead of traditional bulbs helps in ________ energy consumption.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"increasing\",\n        \"wasting\",\n        \"reducing\",\n        \"ignoring\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Public transport and carpooling help conserve ________ resources.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"water\",\n        \"fuel\",\n        \"electricity\",\n        \"sunlight\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Energy conservation helps in reducing ________ bills.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"electricity\",\n        \"water\",\n        \"food\",\n        \"gas\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Using energy-efficient appliances like refrigerators with a 5-star rating helps in ________ energy.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"saving\",\n        \"wasting\",\n        \"producing\",\n        \"ignoring\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Keeping an air conditioner at ________ instead of 18°C helps save energy.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"15°C\",\n        \"30°C\",\n        \"24°C\",\n        \"10°C\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Solar panels are used to generate ________, reducing the use of fossil fuels.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"coal\",\n        \"electricity\",\n        \"gas\",\n        \"petrol\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Smart homes use ________ lights that turn off when no one is in the room.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"manual\",\n        \"automatic\",\n        \"incandescent\",\n        \"non-functional\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Energy conservation means using energy wisely and reducing unnecessary energy use.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Fossil fuels like coal and oil are renewable sources of energy.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Using LED bulbs instead of traditional bulbs helps reduce energy consumption.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Burning fossil fuels does not contribute to air pollution and global warming.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"If we waste natural resources today, future generations may suffer from energy shortages.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Leaving lights and fans on when not in use helps in energy conservation.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Energy conservation can help reduce electricity bills.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Using public transportation instead of personal vehicles can help save fuel.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Solar water heaters consume more electricity than electric geysers.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Carpooling is an effective way to conserve fuel.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"Switching off computers when not in use does not contribute to energy savings.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"Maintaining vehicles properly improves fuel efficiency and reduces fuel consumption.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Recycling materials like paper and plastic reduces the energy needed to produce new materials.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Energy-efficient appliances, such as refrigerators and air conditioners, consume more electricity than regular appliances.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Hybrid cars use both fuel and electricity, making them more energy efficient.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"Opening windows for natural light during the daytime can reduce the need for artificial lighting.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"Energy conservation has no impact on protecting the environment.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Using electric vehicles (EVs) instead of petrol or diesel cars helps in reducing pollution.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Factories should use modern, energy-efficient machinery to reduce power consumption.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"The use of solar panels helps in reducing dependence on non-renewable energy sources.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"Air conditioners set at 18°C consume less electricity than those set at 24°C.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"Using more energy-efficient technologies improves overall energy utilization.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"Earth Hour is a campaign where people switch off lights for one hour to promote energy conservation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"Electric vehicles consume more fuel than petrol or diesel vehicles.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"Energy conservation means producing more energy to meet demands.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"Turning off electrical devices when not in use can help in saving energy.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"Leaving devices on standby mode does not consume electricity.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"Using energy-efficient appliances reduces overall energy costs.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"Conserving energy today ensures that future generations will have enough energy.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"Using a bike or walking for short distances helps in reducing fuel consumption.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"Incandescent bulbs use less energy compared to LED bulbs.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"Factories should operate machines continuously to maximize energy usage.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"Using less water also helps in saving energy, as water purification requires electricity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"Replacing old electrical appliances with new energy-efficient models is a good way to conserve energy.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"Unplugging chargers and electronic devices when not in use can prevent energy wastage.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"Solar-powered streetlights help in conserving electricity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"Energy-efficient buildings are designed to consume more power than traditional buildings.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"Using curtains and blinds to block heat during summer helps in reducing air conditioning costs.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"Setting computers to \'sleep mode\' when idle helps in saving electricity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"Using too many electrical appliances at once increases energy efficiency.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"Using rechargeable batteries instead of disposable ones helps in conserving energy.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"Government campaigns promote awareness about the importance of energy conservation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"Using fans instead of air conditioners can help in reducing energy consumption.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"Power-saving modes in appliances help in reducing unnecessary energy use.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"Smart thermostats can automatically adjust temperature settings to save energy.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"Regular maintenance of electrical appliances can improve their energy efficiency.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"Insulating houses properly can reduce the need for excessive heating and cooling.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"Using more energy-efficient appliances can help reduce the overall carbon footprint.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"Leaving taps running while brushing teeth saves energy.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"Energy conservation plays a major role in sustainable development.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  ',12,5),(20,'2.7-Overuse of Natural Resources and Its Impacts on the Environment','<div>\n    <h2>2.7 Overuse of Natural Resources and Its Impacts on the Environment</h2>\n  \n    <h3>What Are Natural Resources?</h3>\n    <p>Natural resources are materials and substances found in nature that humans use for survival and development. These include:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Renewable resources</strong> – resources that can be replaced naturally over time (e.g., sunlight, wind, water, forests).</li>\n      <li><strong>Non-renewable resources</strong> – resources that take millions of years to form and cannot be replenished once used (e.g., coal, petroleum, minerals).</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>What Is Overuse of Natural Resources?</h3>\n    <p>Overuse of natural resources happens when humans consume these resources faster than they can be replenished. This excessive use leads to depletion, meaning the resources may run out or become too scarce to be useful.</p>\n  \n    <h3>Causes of Overuse of Natural Resources</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Population Growth</strong> – More people require more food, water, and energy.</li>\n      <li><strong>Industrialization</strong> – Factories need raw materials, leading to excessive mining and deforestation.</li>\n      <li><strong>Deforestation</strong> – Cutting down trees faster than they can grow back.</li>\n      <li><strong>Overfishing</strong> – Catching too many fish reduces their population.</li>\n      <li><strong>Excessive Water Usage</strong> – Using groundwater at a higher rate than it is replenished.</li>\n      <li><strong>Dependence on Fossil Fuels</strong> – Using coal, oil, and gas for energy at an unsustainable rate.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>Impacts of Overuse of Natural Resources</h3>\n    \n    <h4>1. Environmental Degradation</h4>\n    <p>When resources are overused, nature struggles to recover, leading to environmental damage.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Example: Cutting down forests for wood and farming leads to soil erosion, loss of biodiversity, and climate change.</li>\n      <li>Example: Excessive groundwater use leads to drying rivers and lakes.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>2. Climate Change</h4>\n    <p>Burning fossil fuels (coal, oil, gas) releases carbon dioxide (CO₂), which traps heat in the atmosphere. This causes global warming.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Example: Melting glaciers lead to rising sea levels, flooding coastal cities.</li>\n      <li>Example: Extreme weather patterns like hurricanes, droughts, and heatwaves become more frequent.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>3. Loss of Biodiversity</h4>\n    <p>When humans overuse forests, water, and land, animals and plants lose their habitats and may go extinct.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Example: Clearing rainforests in the Amazon threatens species like jaguars, sloths, and parrots.</li>\n      <li>Example: Overfishing has led to the near-extinction of species like the Atlantic bluefin tuna.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>4. Soil Erosion and Desertification</h4>\n    <p>Over-farming and deforestation remove the protective cover of trees and plants, causing soil to erode.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Example: The Sahara Desert is expanding due to excessive land use and climate change.</li>\n      <li>Example: In India, overuse of farmland in Punjab has led to declining soil fertility.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>5. Water Scarcity</h4>\n    <p>When too much water is used for industries, farming, and daily life, it reduces the availability of fresh water.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Example: Many cities, like Cape Town (South Africa), have faced severe water shortages.</li>\n      <li>Example: In India, excessive groundwater use has caused wells to dry up in states like Maharashtra and Rajasthan.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>6. Air and Water Pollution</h4>\n    <p>Overusing fossil fuels and industrial processes release harmful pollutants into the air and water, leading to health issues.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Example: Burning coal in China and India causes severe air pollution, leading to diseases like asthma.</li>\n      <li>Example: Dumping industrial waste into rivers like the Ganges has made the water unsafe for drinking.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>7. Food Shortage</h4>\n    <p>Overuse of land and water resources reduces soil fertility and freshwater supply, leading to food shortages.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Example: Overuse of fertilizers has degraded farmland in states like Punjab and Haryana in India.</li>\n      <li>Example: Excessive fishing has reduced seafood availability, increasing prices.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>Solutions to Reduce Overuse of Natural Resources</h3>\n    \n    <h4>1. Conservation</h4>\n    <p>Use resources wisely and avoid waste.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Example: Turn off lights and fans when not needed to save electricity.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>2. Afforestation</h4>\n    <p>Plant more trees to balance deforestation.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Example: Government programs like \"One Tree per Child\" encourage tree planting.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>3. Renewable Energy</h4>\n    <p>Shift to solar, wind, and hydropower instead of fossil fuels.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Example: Countries like Germany and Denmark are using solar and wind energy for electricity.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>4. Water Management</h4>\n    <p>Reduce wastage and promote rainwater harvesting.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Example: In Rajasthan, traditional rainwater harvesting (baoris and johads) has helped store water.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>5. Sustainable Farming</h4>\n    <p>Use organic farming and crop rotation to maintain soil fertility.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Example: Using compost and natural fertilizers instead of chemicals.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>6. Reduce, Reuse, Recycle</h4>\n    <p>Minimize waste and reuse materials.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Example: Recycling plastic, paper, and metals reduces the need for new raw materials.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>7. Stronger Laws and Policies</h4>\n    <p>Governments should enforce regulations to protect resources.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Example: Banning single-use plastics to reduce pollution.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>Conclusion</h3>\n    <p>Overusing natural resources harms the environment and future generations. If we continue at the current rate, many resources may become unavailable, leading to major crises like food and water shortages, loss of biodiversity, and climate disasters.</p>\n    <p>However, by adopting sustainable practices, using renewable energy, and conserving resources, we can protect the environment and ensure a better future for everyone.</p>\n    <p>? Let’s act responsibly today to save resources for tomorrow!</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What are renewable natural resources?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Resources that cannot be replaced\",\n        \"Resources that take millions of years to form\",\n        \"Resources that can be naturally replenished\",\n        \"Resources that do not exist in nature\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an example of a non-renewable resource?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Sunlight\",\n        \"Wind\",\n        \"Coal\",\n        \"Water\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"What is meant by the overuse of natural resources?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using resources faster than they can be replenished\",\n        \"Using resources at a sustainable rate\",\n        \"Not using natural resources at all\",\n        \"Using only renewable resources\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Which human activity contributes the most to deforestation?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Fishing\",\n        \"Mining\",\n        \"Logging and agriculture\",\n        \"Urban gardening\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"What is a major cause of overuse of natural resources?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Population growth\",\n        \"Reduction in industrialization\",\n        \"Use of renewable energy\",\n        \"Water conservation\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a major consequence of deforestation?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Improved soil fertility\",\n        \"Loss of biodiversity\",\n        \"Increase in freshwater resources\",\n        \"Stabilization of climate\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"What is one of the main environmental impacts of burning fossil fuels?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Reduction in air pollution\",\n        \"Increase in biodiversity\",\n        \"Global warming\",\n        \"Soil conservation\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"How does overfishing impact marine ecosystems?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Increases fish population\",\n        \"Leads to the extinction of fish species\",\n        \"Reduces water pollution\",\n        \"Creates more habitat for fish\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a renewable source of energy?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Petroleum\",\n        \"Solar energy\",\n        \"Coal\",\n        \"Natural gas\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a sustainable solution to prevent desertification?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Overgrazing\",\n        \"Afforestation\",\n        \"Excessive water usage\",\n        \"Deforestation\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"What is a consequence of groundwater depletion?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Increase in freshwater supply\",\n        \"Drying up of rivers and lakes\",\n        \"Improvement in biodiversity\",\n        \"Increased fish population\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"What does sustainable farming help with?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Overuse of fertilizers\",\n        \"Soil conservation\",\n        \"Soil erosion\",\n        \"Reduction in crop yield\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Which of these contributes to climate change?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Use of wind energy\",\n        \"Burning fossil fuels\",\n        \"Afforestation\",\n        \"Sustainable farming\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"What is a negative effect of industrialization?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Increased biodiversity\",\n        \"Reduced soil erosion\",\n        \"Overexploitation of resources\",\n        \"Sustainable energy production\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"What is an example of a sustainable practice?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using solar panels\",\n        \"Overgrazing\",\n        \"Overfishing\",\n        \"Burning fossil fuels\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Natural resources are materials and substances found in ________ that humans use for survival and development.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"factories\",\n        \"nature\",\n        \"laboratories\",\n        \"industries\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Renewable resources are those that can be replaced ________ over time.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"artificially\",\n        \"naturally\",\n        \"chemically\",\n        \"mechanically\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Coal, petroleum, and minerals are examples of ________ resources.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"renewable\",\n        \"non-renewable\",\n        \"unlimited\",\n        \"synthetic\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"The excessive use of natural resources leads to their ________, making them scarce or unavailable.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"renewal\",\n        \"depletion\",\n        \"abundance\",\n        \"formation\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"A major cause of overuse of natural resources is rapid ________ growth.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"technological\",\n        \"population\",\n        \"industrial\",\n        \"economic\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Cutting down trees at a faster rate than they can regrow is known as ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"deforestation\",\n        \"afforestation\",\n        \"conservation\",\n        \"reforestation\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Overfishing results in a significant reduction in ________ population.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"forest\",\n        \"fish\",\n        \"bird\",\n        \"mammal\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Burning fossil fuels releases ________, which contributes to climate change.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"oxygen\",\n        \"carbon dioxide\",\n        \"nitrogen\",\n        \"hydrogen\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Excessive groundwater usage can cause ________ and lakes to dry up.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"oceans\",\n        \"rivers\",\n        \"hills\",\n        \"mountains\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"The melting of glaciers due to climate change leads to rising ________ levels.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sea\",\n        \"air\",\n        \"land\",\n        \"temperature\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"Overuse of natural resources leads to ________, which results in the loss of plant and animal species.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"urbanization\",\n        \"biodiversity loss\",\n        \"industrialization\",\n        \"agriculture\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"The Sahara Desert is expanding due to excessive land use and ________ change.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"cultural\",\n        \"climate\",\n        \"economic\",\n        \"political\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"One of the major reasons for water scarcity is excessive use of ________ water.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"surface\",\n        \"ground\",\n        \"rain\",\n        \"seawater\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Dumping industrial waste into rivers leads to ________ pollution.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"air\",\n        \"soil\",\n        \"water\",\n        \"noise\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Overuse of fertilizers can degrade farmland and reduce soil ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"productivity\",\n        \"fertility\",\n        \"pollution\",\n        \"hardness\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"Using solar and wind energy instead of fossil fuels helps in reducing ________ emissions.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"oxygen\",\n        \"carbon dioxide\",\n        \"hydrogen\",\n        \"methane\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"A sustainable way to conserve water is through ________ harvesting.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"rainwater\",\n        \"groundwater\",\n        \"river\",\n        \"seawater\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Planting more trees to restore forests is called ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"deforestation\",\n        \"afforestation\",\n        \"industrialization\",\n        \"urbanization\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Banning ________ plastics can help in reducing pollution.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"biodegradable\",\n        \"single-use\",\n        \"recyclable\",\n        \"natural\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"Extreme weather patterns like hurricanes and droughts are becoming more frequent due to ________ change.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"economic\",\n        \"cultural\",\n        \"climate\",\n        \"technological\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Natural resources are materials found in nature that humans use for survival and development.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Renewable resources cannot be replaced naturally over time.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Coal and petroleum are examples of renewable resources.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Overuse of natural resources occurs when humans consume them faster than they can be replenished.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Deforestation is the process of planting more trees to increase forest cover.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Industrialization increases the demand for raw materials, leading to excessive mining and deforestation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Overfishing does not impact marine biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Burning fossil fuels releases carbon dioxide, which contributes to climate change.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Excessive groundwater usage can lead to the drying up of rivers and lakes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Melting glaciers due to climate change do not affect sea levels.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"Loss of biodiversity occurs when natural habitats are destroyed by human activities.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"The Amazon rainforest is unaffected by deforestation.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Overuse of farmland can lead to soil erosion and declining soil fertility.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Climate change has no impact on extreme weather events like hurricanes and droughts.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Water scarcity can be caused by excessive water usage in agriculture and industries.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"Burning coal and oil improves air quality and reduces pollution.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"Food shortages can result from the overuse of land and water resources.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Excessive use of fertilizers improves soil quality permanently.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Using renewable energy sources like solar and wind power helps reduce dependence on fossil fuels.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"Recycling materials can help reduce the demand for new raw materials.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"Governments have no role in regulating the use of natural resources.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"Afforestation means planting more trees to compensate for deforestation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"The expansion of the Sahara Desert is caused by excessive land use and climate change.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"Overuse of resources has no impact on future generations.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"Air pollution caused by burning fossil fuels can lead to respiratory diseases.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"Single-use plastics help in reducing environmental pollution.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"Rainwater harvesting is an effective way to conserve water resources.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"Soil erosion occurs when the land is overused for agriculture without sustainable practices.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"Overfishing has led to a decrease in the population of species like the Atlantic bluefin tuna.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"Reducing, reusing, and recycling waste helps conserve natural resources.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"Sustainable farming involves using excessive chemical fertilizers to increase production.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"Climate change has no impact on agricultural production.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"Dumping industrial waste into rivers has no negative effect on water quality.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"Deforestation can contribute to an increase in carbon dioxide levels in the atmosphere.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"Food shortages are not linked to environmental degradation.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"Governments worldwide are banning single-use plastics to reduce environmental pollution.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"Water management is crucial in preventing water scarcity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"Burning fossil fuels does not contribute to global warming.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"Rainforests act as the lungs of the Earth by absorbing carbon dioxide.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"Desertification happens when land becomes fertile due to excess water.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"Renewable energy sources like wind and solar power help reduce environmental pollution.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"The depletion of natural resources has no economic impact.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"Sustainable development ensures that resources are used wisely to benefit future generations.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"Excessive mining activities can lead to land degradation and habitat destruction.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"The main cause of deforestation is natural disasters.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"Recycling reduces the need for excessive extraction of raw materials.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"Global warming has no impact on rising sea levels.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"Switching to public transportation helps reduce fossil fuel consumption.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"Sustainable water use can help prevent future water shortages.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"Protecting biodiversity is not necessary for a balanced ecosystem.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    }\n]\n  ',12,5),(21,'3.1-Ecosystem','<div>\n    <h2>3.1 Ecosystem</h2>\n  \n    <h3>Definition of Ecosystem</h3>\n    <p>An ecosystem is a system where living organisms (plants, animals, and microorganisms) interact with non-living components (air, water, soil, sunlight, temperature) in a specific environment. It is a natural unit that functions as a whole, supporting life.</p>\n    <p><strong>? Example:</strong> A forest is an ecosystem where trees, animals, birds, soil, water, and sunlight interact with each other. Similarly, a pond is an ecosystem where fish, algae, insects, and water exist together.</p>\n  \n    <h3>Aspects of an Ecosystem</h3>\n  \n    <h4>Biotic Components (Living things)</h4>\n    <p>These are all the living organisms in an ecosystem.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Trees, flowers, grass, deer, tiger, birds, bacteria, insects.</p>\n  \n    <h4>Abiotic Components (Non-living things)</h4>\n    <p>These are the physical and chemical elements in the ecosystem that support life.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Air, water, sunlight, temperature, soil, minerals, and nutrients.</p>\n    <p><strong>? Example:</strong> In a pond ecosystem, fish (biotic) live in water (abiotic), and they depend on oxygen, temperature, and sunlight for survival.</p>\n  \n    <h3>Division of Ecosystem</h3>\n    <p>Ecosystems can be divided into different types based on their location and characteristics:</p>\n  \n    <h4>1. Natural Ecosystems</h4>\n    <p>These exist in nature without human interference.</p>\n    <p><strong>✅ Examples:</strong></p>\n  \n    <h5>Terrestrial Ecosystems (Land-based)</h5>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Forest Ecosystem (Trees, deer, tigers, monkeys, soil, sunlight)</li>\n      <li>Grassland Ecosystem (Grass, cows, rabbits, insects, birds)</li>\n      <li>Desert Ecosystem (Cactus, camels, snakes, sand, high temperature)</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h5>Aquatic Ecosystems (Water-based)</h5>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Freshwater Ecosystem (Ponds, lakes, rivers – fish, frogs, lotus)</li>\n      <li>Marine Ecosystem (Oceans, seas – whales, sharks, corals)</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>2. Artificial Ecosystems</h4>\n    <p>These are man-made ecosystems where humans control the environment.</p>\n    <p><strong>✅ Examples:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Crop fields (Agricultural land) – Farmers grow wheat, rice, or vegetables.</li>\n      <li>Aquariums – Artificially created environments for fish with plants and oxygen pumps.</li>\n      <li>Zoos – Animals are kept in a controlled environment for conservation or public display.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>General Characteristics of Ecosystem</h3>\n  \n    <h4>Self-Sustaining</h4>\n    <p>Ecosystems can maintain themselves naturally.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> A forest can grow, provide food, and support animals without human help.</p>\n  \n    <h4>Energy Flow</h4>\n    <p>Sunlight is the main source of energy, and it flows through plants, animals, and decomposers.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Sun → Plants (photosynthesis) → Deer (eats plants) → Tiger (eats deer).</p>\n  \n    <h4>Food Chains and Food Webs</h4>\n    <p>Organisms are linked through feeding relationships.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Grass → Grasshopper → Frog → Snake → Eagle.</p>\n  \n    <h4>Recycling of Nutrients</h4>\n    <p>Elements like carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen cycle through the ecosystem.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Trees absorb carbon dioxide, give out oxygen, and when they decay, the nutrients go back into the soil.</p>\n  \n    <h4>Interdependence</h4>\n    <p>All living and non-living things are connected and affect each other.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> If bees disappear, plants won’t get pollinated, and food production will decrease.</p>\n  \n    <h3>Functions of Ecosystem</h3>\n  \n    <h4>Energy Flow</h4>\n    <p>The Sun provides energy to plants (producers), which is passed on to herbivores (plant-eaters) and then to carnivores (meat-eaters).</p>\n  \n    <h4>Nutrient Cycling</h4>\n    <p>Essential elements like carbon, oxygen, nitrogen, and water keep moving between living and non-living things.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> When leaves fall, they decompose and provide nutrients to the soil, helping new plants grow.</p>\n  \n    <h4>Balance of Gases</h4>\n    <p>Plants absorb carbon dioxide and release oxygen, which animals need for breathing.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> The Amazon rainforest is called the \"lungs of the Earth\" because it produces a lot of oxygen.</p>\n  \n    <h4>Waste Decomposition</h4>\n    <p>Microorganisms like bacteria and fungi break down dead plants and animals, cleaning the environment.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> If a tree falls in a forest, decomposers turn it into nutrients for the soil.</p>\n  \n    <h4>Climate Regulation</h4>\n    <p>Ecosystems help in maintaining temperature and controlling the climate.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Forests absorb carbon dioxide and prevent global warming.</p>\n  \n    <h4>Water Cycle</h4>\n    <p>Ecosystems help in rain formation and maintain water balance.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Trees release water vapor, which forms clouds and brings rain.</p>\n  \n    <h3>Conclusion</h3>\n    <p>An ecosystem is a dynamic system where living beings and non-living components interact with each other. It maintains the balance of nature through energy flow, food chains, and recycling of nutrients. Whether natural (like forests and oceans) or artificial (like farms and aquariums), ecosystems are essential for life on Earth.</p>\n    <p><strong>? Key takeaway:</strong> We must protect ecosystems by avoiding pollution, deforestation, and overuse of natural resources to keep our environment healthy! ?✨</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is an ecosystem?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"A system where living organisms interact with non-living components\",\n        \"A place where only animals live\",\n        \"A human-made environment\",\n        \"A location with only plants and trees\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a biotic component of an ecosystem?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Sunlight\",\n        \"Water\",\n        \"Soil\",\n        \"Trees\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an abiotic component?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Animals\",\n        \"Microorganisms\",\n        \"Air\",\n        \"Plants\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"What is an example of a terrestrial ecosystem?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Ocean\",\n        \"Lake\",\n        \"Desert\",\n        \"River\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Which of these is a natural ecosystem?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Aquarium\",\n        \"Zoo\",\n        \"Forest\",\n        \"Crop field\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"What is an example of an artificial ecosystem?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Rainforest\",\n        \"Desert\",\n        \"Lake\",\n        \"Aquarium\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a freshwater ecosystem?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Ocean\",\n        \"River\",\n        \"Coral reef\",\n        \"Seashore\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Which ecosystem has organisms like whales, sharks, and corals?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Forest\",\n        \"Freshwater\",\n        \"Marine\",\n        \"Desert\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an example of energy flow in an ecosystem?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Sun → Plants → Deer → Tiger\",\n        \"Tiger → Deer → Sun → Plants\",\n        \"Plants → Sun → Soil → Water\",\n        \"Sun → Soil → Rocks → Air\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"What do decomposers do in an ecosystem?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Produce food\",\n        \"Break down dead organisms\",\n        \"Hunt for food\",\n        \"Store energy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a producer in an ecosystem?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Lion\",\n        \"Fungi\",\n        \"Grass\",\n        \"Tiger\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"Which of these is a function of an ecosystem?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Balancing gases\",\n        \"Stopping rain\",\n        \"Eliminating decomposers\",\n        \"Preventing food chains\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an example of a food chain?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Plants → Deer → Tiger\",\n        \"Water → Fish → Soil\",\n        \"Plants → Soil → Air\",\n        \"Rocks → Trees → Animals\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Which process helps recycle nutrients in an ecosystem?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Water cycle\",\n        \"Nutrient cycling\",\n        \"Rock formation\",\n        \"Sunlight absorption\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an example of interdependence in an ecosystem?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Birds needing trees for nesting\",\n        \"Fish creating their own water\",\n        \"Sunlight producing food\",\n        \"Rocks growing into trees\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"What helps maintain the balance of gases in an ecosystem?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Trees absorbing carbon dioxide\",\n        \"Animals breathing nitrogen\",\n        \"Oceans eliminating oxygen\",\n        \"Rocks producing gases\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"Which ecosystem is called the \'lungs of the Earth\'?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Desert\",\n        \"Amazon Rainforest\",\n        \"Tundra\",\n        \"Coral reefs\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Which process helps in climate regulation?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Burning fossil fuels\",\n        \"Deforestation\",\n        \"Absorbing carbon dioxide\",\n        \"Polluting rivers\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Which type of ecosystem is a grassland?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Artificial\",\n        \"Aquatic\",\n        \"Terrestrial\",\n        \"Marine\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"What is the role of decomposers in the ecosystem?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Producing food\",\n        \"Breaking down dead matter\",\n        \"Hunting prey\",\n        \"Storing energy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"An ecosystem consists of both ________ and ________ components.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"biotic, abiotic\",\n        \"plants, animals\",\n        \"air, water\",\n        \"producers, consumers\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"A ________ is a system where living organisms interact with non-living components in an environment.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"community\",\n        \"biosphere\",\n        \"habitat\",\n        \"ecosystem\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"The two major aspects of an ecosystem are ________ and ________ components.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"natural, artificial\",\n        \"freshwater, marine\",\n        \"biotic, abiotic\",\n        \"plants, animals\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Air, water, sunlight, and soil are examples of ________ components in an ecosystem.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"biotic\",\n        \"artificial\",\n        \"abiotic\",\n        \"natural\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Plants, animals, and microorganisms form the ________ components of an ecosystem.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"biotic\",\n        \"abiotic\",\n        \"artificial\",\n        \"chemical\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"A pond is an example of a ________ ecosystem.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"terrestrial\",\n        \"marine\",\n        \"freshwater\",\n        \"desert\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"A desert ecosystem includes ________, camels, and high temperatures.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"fish\",\n        \"cactus\",\n        \"frogs\",\n        \"corals\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"An example of an artificial ecosystem is ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"forest\",\n        \"ocean\",\n        \"aquarium\",\n        \"grassland\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"A marine ecosystem includes ________, sharks, and corals.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"whales\",\n        \"tigers\",\n        \"frogs\",\n        \"snakes\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ is the main source of energy in an ecosystem.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"plants\",\n        \"sun\",\n        \"soil\",\n        \"water\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"A food chain always starts with a ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"carnivore\",\n        \"producer\",\n        \"decomposer\",\n        \"herbivore\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"Grass → Grasshopper → Frog → Snake → Eagle is an example of a ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"food chain\",\n        \"nutrient cycle\",\n        \"water cycle\",\n        \"energy flow\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Nutrient cycling involves the continuous movement of elements like ________ and ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"oxygen, carbon\",\n        \"gold, silver\",\n        \"helium, hydrogen\",\n        \"copper, iron\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Decomposers like bacteria and fungi help in ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"energy flow\",\n        \"waste decomposition\",\n        \"photosynthesis\",\n        \"gas exchange\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Forests help regulate climate by absorbing ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"oxygen\",\n        \"nitrogen\",\n        \"carbon dioxide\",\n        \"helium\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"The Amazon rainforest is often called the ________ of the Earth.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"backbone\",\n        \"lungs\",\n        \"heart\",\n        \"brain\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"Interdependence in an ecosystem means that all living and non-living things are ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"separate\",\n        \"connected\",\n        \"useless\",\n        \"static\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"If bees disappear, plants won’t get ________, leading to food production problems.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"watered\",\n        \"pollinated\",\n        \"pruned\",\n        \"harvested\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Humans must protect ecosystems by avoiding ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"deforestation\",\n        \"oxygen production\",\n        \"nutrient cycling\",\n        \"photosynthesis\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"The water cycle helps maintain the Earth\'s ________ balance.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"oxygen\",\n        \"carbon\",\n        \"water\",\n        \"nitrogen\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that an ecosystem consists of both living and non-living components interacting in a specific environment.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that biotic components of an ecosystem include air, water, and sunlight.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that a pond is considered an ecosystem because it supports interactions between fish, algae, and water.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that an ecosystem only includes living organisms and does not involve any physical environment.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that ecosystems can be divided into natural and artificial types.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that forests, grasslands, and deserts are examples of artificial ecosystems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that an aquarium is a type of artificial ecosystem.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that energy flow in an ecosystem begins with animals.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the Sun is the primary source of energy in an ecosystem.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that food chains and food webs do not exist in an ecosystem.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that a food chain represents the flow of energy from one organism to another.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that deserts are not considered ecosystems because they lack water.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that decomposers help in breaking down dead plants and animals in an ecosystem.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that nutrient cycling does not occur in an ecosystem.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that forests help regulate the climate by absorbing carbon dioxide.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that human activities do not affect ecosystems in any way.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that artificial ecosystems require human management to function properly.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that marine ecosystems only include fish and do not have any plants or microorganisms.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that oxygen is an essential abiotic component in an ecosystem.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the balance of gases in an ecosystem is not important for survival.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that forests are self-sustaining ecosystems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that a desert ecosystem does not have any living organisms.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the water cycle plays a significant role in ecosystems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that food chains always remain the same and do not change over time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that interdependence is a key characteristic of ecosystems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the loss of bees would not affect plant pollination in an ecosystem.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that terrestrial and aquatic ecosystems are two broad divisions of natural ecosystems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that climate change has no effect on ecosystems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that ecosystems maintain the balance of nature by cycling nutrients and energy.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that all ecosystems have the same climate and biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  ',12,6),(22,'3.2-Biodiversity – Definition, Levels, Value, and Loss of Biodiversity','<div>\n    <h2>3.2 Biodiversity – Definition, Levels, Value, and Loss of Biodiversity</h2>\n    \n    <h3>1. Definition of Biodiversity</h3>\n    <p>Biodiversity (short for biological diversity) refers to the variety of life on Earth. It includes all living organisms, such as plants, animals, fungi, and microorganisms, as well as the ecosystems they form.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>A rainforest has a high biodiversity because it contains thousands of different species of trees, birds, insects, and mammals.</li>\n      <li>A desert has lower biodiversity because fewer species can survive in the extreme conditions.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>2. Levels of Biodiversity</h3>\n    <p>Biodiversity exists at three main levels:</p>\n    \n    <h4>A. Genetic Biodiversity (Diversity within a species)</h4>\n    <p>Refers to differences in genes within the same species.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Different breeds of dogs (Labrador, German Shepherd, Pug) all belong to the same species but have different genetic traits.</li>\n      <li>Different varieties of rice or wheat that farmers grow for different climates and soil types.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>B. Species Biodiversity (Diversity among species)</h4>\n    <p>Refers to the variety of different species in a particular region or ecosystem.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>A coral reef contains hundreds of fish species, sea turtles, crabs, and corals.</li>\n      <li>A city park may have fewer species, such as pigeons, squirrels, and a few trees.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>C. Ecosystem Biodiversity (Diversity of ecosystems)</h4>\n    <p>Refers to the variety of different ecosystems or habitats found on Earth.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>The Amazon rainforest, Sahara Desert, and Arctic tundra all have different types of biodiversity.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>3. Value of Biodiversity</h3>\n    <p>Biodiversity is important for many reasons.</p>\n    \n    <h4>A. Ecological Value</h4>\n    <p>Each species plays a role in maintaining a healthy ecosystem.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Bees help in pollinating plants.</li>\n      <li>Forests absorb carbon dioxide and produce oxygen.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>B. Economic Value</h4>\n    <p>Many industries depend on biodiversity.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Fishermen rely on fish for their livelihood.</li>\n      <li>Many medicines come from plants.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>C. Aesthetic and Recreational Value</h4>\n    <p>Nature’s beauty provides pleasure and tourism opportunities.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>National parks attract tourists.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>D. Ethical and Cultural Value</h4>\n    <p>We must protect biodiversity because all species have the right to exist.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>In Hinduism, the cow is considered sacred.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>4. Loss of Biodiversity</h3>\n    <p>Biodiversity is decreasing rapidly due to human activities.</p>\n    \n    <h4>A. Habitat Destruction</h4>\n    <p>Deforestation and urbanization destroy natural habitats.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Amazon Rainforest destruction due to logging.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>B. Pollution</h4>\n    <p>Water pollution, air pollution, and soil pollution harm biodiversity.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Oil spills kill marine life.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>C. Climate Change</h4>\n    <p>Global warming affects biodiversity.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Coral reefs are dying due to rising sea temperatures.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>D. Overexploitation</h4>\n    <p>Hunting, fishing, and mining are done at unsustainable levels.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Overfishing has led to the decline of fish populations.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>E. Invasive Species</h4>\n    <p>When new species are introduced to an ecosystem, they can outcompete native species.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>The water hyacinth is choking water bodies.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>Conclusion</h3>\n    <p>Biodiversity is essential for a healthy planet. It supports life, provides food, medicine, and clean air.</p>\n    <p><strong>Ways to Protect Biodiversity:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Plant more trees</li>\n      <li>Reduce pollution</li>\n      <li>Protect wildlife</li>\n      <li>Sustainable farming and fishing</li>\n      <li>Support conservation programs</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p>By taking these steps, we can ensure that future generations enjoy the benefits of a diverse and thriving natural world.</p>\n</div>','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What does biodiversity refer to?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Variety of living organisms on Earth\",\n        \"Number of plants in a garden\",\n        \"Types of weather conditions\",\n        \"Different languages spoken in a region\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is NOT a level of biodiversity?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Genetic Biodiversity\",\n        \"Species Biodiversity\",\n        \"Ecosystem Biodiversity\",\n        \"Chemical Biodiversity\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Which ecosystem has the highest biodiversity?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Desert\",\n        \"Rainforest\",\n        \"Arctic tundra\",\n        \"Grassland\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an example of genetic biodiversity?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Different species of birds in a forest\",\n        \"Different breeds of dogs\",\n        \"Variety of fish in the ocean\",\n        \"Different types of forests on Earth\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"What is an example of species biodiversity?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Different varieties of rice\",\n        \"A coral reef with hundreds of fish species\",\n        \"A rainforest with diverse tree heights\",\n        \"Different climates across the world\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which factor contributes to ecosystem biodiversity?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Genetic mutations\",\n        \"Presence of different species\",\n        \"Variety of ecosystems like forests and deserts\",\n        \"Weather patterns\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Why is biodiversity important for ecological balance?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"It provides oxygen, food, and maintains ecosystems\",\n        \"It increases pollution levels\",\n        \"It causes deforestation\",\n        \"It leads to habitat destruction\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following industries depends on biodiversity?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Agriculture\",\n        \"Medicine\",\n        \"Fishing\",\n        \"All of the above\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an economic benefit of biodiversity?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Provides oxygen\",\n        \"Supports tourism and agriculture\",\n        \"Regulates climate\",\n        \"Recycles nutrients\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"What is an example of aesthetic and recreational value of biodiversity?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"National parks and wildlife sanctuaries\",\n        \"Deforestation\",\n        \"Plastic pollution\",\n        \"Mining and construction\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"Which human activity is the biggest cause of biodiversity loss?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Pollution\",\n        \"Deforestation\",\n        \"Overfishing\",\n        \"All of the above\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"How does climate change affect biodiversity?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Causes habitat destruction and species extinction\",\n        \"Increases oxygen levels\",\n        \"Reduces pollution\",\n        \"Increases biodiversity in deserts\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an invasive species?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Water hyacinth\",\n        \"Oak tree\",\n        \"Mango tree\",\n        \"Bamboo plant\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Why is overfishing harmful to biodiversity?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"It maintains fish populations\",\n        \"It causes the decline of marine species\",\n        \"It reduces water pollution\",\n        \"It increases coral reef growth\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a way to protect biodiversity?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Deforestation\",\n        \"Overhunting\",\n        \"Conservation programs\",\n        \"Increasing plastic use\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Biodiversity refers to the variety of ________ on Earth.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ecosystems\",\n        \"species\",\n        \"life\",\n        \"genes\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"The three levels of biodiversity are genetic, ________, and ecosystem biodiversity.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"species\",\n        \"population\",\n        \"habitat\",\n        \"community\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Genetic biodiversity refers to variations within a ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"species\",\n        \"community\",\n        \"population\",\n        \"habitat\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"A region with a high number of different species has high ________ biodiversity.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"genetic\",\n        \"species\",\n        \"ecosystem\",\n        \"functional\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"The Amazon rainforest is an example of an ecosystem with ________ biodiversity.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"low\",\n        \"moderate\",\n        \"high\",\n        \"no\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"The Sahara Desert has relatively ________ biodiversity due to its extreme conditions.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"high\",\n        \"low\",\n        \"moderate\",\n        \"infinite\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Biodiversity provides economic value through industries such as ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"fishing and agriculture\",\n        \"mining and logging\",\n        \"construction and manufacturing\",\n        \"tourism and transportation\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"The ethical value of biodiversity suggests that all species have the ________ to exist.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"opportunity\",\n        \"ability\",\n        \"right\",\n        \"necessity\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Habitat destruction is a major cause of biodiversity ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"increase\",\n        \"stability\",\n        \"growth\",\n        \"loss\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"The introduction of non-native species can lead to biodiversity ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"growth\",\n        \"protection\",\n        \"loss\",\n        \"expansion\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that biodiversity refers to the variety of life on Earth, including plants, animals, fungi, and microorganisms.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that biodiversity includes only animals and plants, excluding microorganisms.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that genetic biodiversity refers to differences in genes within the same species.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that species biodiversity refers to the genetic variations within a single species.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that ecosystem biodiversity refers to the variety of different ecosystems found on Earth.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that biodiversity only exists at one level, which is genetic diversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the Amazon rainforest has high biodiversity due to the large number of species it supports.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that deserts have higher biodiversity than rainforests.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that bees play an important role in biodiversity by helping in pollination.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that biodiversity has no economic value.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that biodiversity loss is mainly caused by habitat destruction, pollution, climate change, overexploitation, and invasive species.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that climate change has no impact on biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that overfishing has caused the decline of species like tuna and cod.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the introduction of invasive species does not affect native species in an ecosystem.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that ecosystem biodiversity includes various habitats such as rainforests, deserts, and oceans.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that genetic biodiversity only applies to plants and not animals.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that forests play a major role in absorbing carbon dioxide and producing oxygen.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that humans do not benefit from biodiversity in any way.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that national parks and wildlife sanctuaries help in conserving biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that biodiversity is only important for scientific research and has no impact on human life.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that habitat destruction leads to the loss of biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that pollution does not harm biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that sustainable farming and fishing can help protect biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that biodiversity is decreasing at a slow rate due to human activities.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that ethical and cultural values influence biodiversity conservation efforts.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that biodiversity loss has no effect on the ecosystem’s balance.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that forests act as the lungs of the Earth by producing oxygen.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that poaching and hunting do not affect biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that ecotourism promotes the conservation of biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that planting trees does not contribute to biodiversity protection.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that certain plants and animals are considered sacred in different cultures.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that all species in an ecosystem are independent of each other.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that biodiversity ensures food security by providing diverse crops and livestock.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that invasive species always benefit the ecosystem.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that coral reefs are highly biodiverse marine ecosystems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that all species contribute equally to ecosystem stability.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that conservation programs like wildlife reserves help in protecting endangered species.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that biodiversity loss does not affect climate regulation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that biodiversity loss can lead to food shortages and economic instability.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that biodiversity has no impact on medicine and healthcare.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that protecting biodiversity helps maintain healthy ecosystems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that economic activities like deforestation do not contribute to biodiversity loss.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that governments and organizations play a key role in biodiversity conservation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that biodiversity loss has no impact on human well-being.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that humans rely on biodiversity for food, water, and medicine.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  ',12,6),(23,'3.3-Biodiversity Assessment Initiatives in India','<div>\n    <h2>3.3 Biodiversity Assessment Initiatives in India</h2>\n  \n    <p>Biodiversity refers to the variety of life on Earth, including plants, animals, and microorganisms, as well as the ecosystems they form. Assessing biodiversity means identifying and recording different species, understanding their distribution, and evaluating the health of ecosystems. In India, several initiatives have been taken to study and protect biodiversity.</p>\n  \n    <h3>Why is Biodiversity Assessment Important?</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Conservation Planning</strong> – Helps in protecting endangered species.</li>\n      <li><strong>Sustainable Development</strong> – Ensures that natural resources are used wisely.</li>\n      <li><strong>Climate Change Mitigation</strong> – Helps in understanding how species react to environmental changes.</li>\n      <li><strong>Economic Benefits</strong> – Many industries like medicine, agriculture, and tourism depend on biodiversity.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>Major Biodiversity Assessment Initiatives in India</h3>\n  \n    <h4>1. Indian Biodiversity Information System (IBIS)</h4>\n    <p>A digital platform that collects and shares biodiversity data.</p>\n    <p>Scientists and researchers use it to track species and ecosystems.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> A scientist in Kerala can use IBIS to check records of rare bird sightings across India.</p>\n  \n    <h4>2. Biological Diversity Act (2002)</h4>\n    <p>A legal framework for conserving biodiversity and ensuring fair use of biological resources.</p>\n    <p>Establishes National Biodiversity Authority (NBA) to oversee biodiversity conservation.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> If a pharmaceutical company wants to use a rare Himalayan herb, they need permission from the NBA to ensure sustainable use.</p>\n  \n    <h4>3. National Biodiversity Action Plan (NBAP)</h4>\n    <p>A government policy that outlines steps to protect biodiversity.</p>\n    <p>Focuses on habitat conservation, species protection, and sustainable resource use.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Under NBAP, India has developed plans to protect the Great Indian Bustard, one of the world’s most endangered birds.</p>\n  \n    <h4>4. Biodiversity Hotspot Identification</h4>\n    <p>India has four biodiversity hotspots:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Himalayas</strong> (Snow leopards, Red pandas)</li>\n      <li><strong>Indo-Burma region</strong> (Hoolock Gibbons, Assam roofed turtles)</li>\n      <li><strong>Western Ghats</strong> (Lion-tailed macaques, Malabar civets)</li>\n      <li><strong>Sundaland (Andaman & Nicobar Islands)</strong> (Nicobar megapodes, Dugongs)</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> The Western Ghats are studied to monitor the health of frog populations, as they indicate climate change effects.</p>\n  \n    <h4>5. All India Coordinated Project on Taxonomy (AICOPTAX)</h4>\n    <p>A government project that classifies and records plant and animal species.</p>\n    <p>Helps scientists identify new species and update old classifications.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> In 2021, a new species of snake called Trimeresurus salazar was discovered in Arunachal Pradesh under this initiative.</p>\n  \n    <h4>6. Indian State of Forest Report (ISFR)</h4>\n    <p>A biennial (every two years) report that assesses forest cover and biodiversity.</p>\n    <p>Provides data on tree species, wildlife corridors, and deforestation rates.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> The 2023 ISFR reported an increase in mangrove forests along India’s coastline, which is good news for marine biodiversity.</p>\n  \n    <h4>7. National Mission for Green India (GIM)</h4>\n    <p>A government program to increase forest and tree cover.</p>\n    <p>Focuses on restoring degraded ecosystems.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> In Rajasthan, the GIM has helped plant native trees to restore desert ecosystems.</p>\n  \n    <h4>8. People’s Biodiversity Registers (PBRs)</h4>\n    <p>Community-based documentation of local biodiversity.</p>\n    <p>Villagers and tribal communities help record plant and animal species in their area.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> In Karnataka, villagers documented over 300 medicinal plants used in traditional healing practices.</p>\n  \n    <h4>9. Zoological Survey of India (ZSI) & Botanical Survey of India (BSI)</h4>\n    <p>ZSI studies animal species; BSI studies plant species.</p>\n    <p>These organizations help in discovering and documenting new species.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> In 2020, ZSI identified a new species of freshwater fish in Meghalaya.</p>\n  \n    <h4>10. Wildlife Protection Act (1972)</h4>\n    <p>Protects endangered animals and their habitats.</p>\n    <p>Helps in setting up National Parks and Wildlife Sanctuaries.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> The Act played a major role in saving the Royal Bengal Tiger through Project Tiger.</p>\n  \n    <h3>Conclusion</h3>\n    <p>Biodiversity assessment initiatives in India play a crucial role in understanding and protecting the country’s rich natural heritage. With projects like IBIS, PBRs, and AICOPTAX, India continues to identify, document, and conserve its vast biodiversity. These initiatives not only help in conservation but also ensure sustainable development for future generations.</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What does biodiversity refer to?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Variety of life on Earth\",\n        \"Variety of human cultures\",\n        \"Different climatic conditions\",\n        \"Types of soil found in an area\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Which digital platform collects and shares biodiversity data in India?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Wildlife Census Portal\",\n        \"Indian Biodiversity Information System (IBIS)\",\n        \"National Ecology Database\",\n        \"Flora and Fauna Repository\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"When was the Biological Diversity Act passed in India?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"1995\",\n        \"2000\",\n        \"2002\",\n        \"2010\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"What is the role of the National Biodiversity Authority (NBA)?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Overseeing biodiversity conservation\",\n        \"Regulating air pollution levels\",\n        \"Monitoring human population growth\",\n        \"Enforcing industrial safety laws\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Which biodiversity hotspot in India is home to the Snow Leopard?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Indo-Burma\",\n        \"Western Ghats\",\n        \"Sundaland\",\n        \"Himalayas\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which report assesses India’s forest cover every two years?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"National Biodiversity Action Plan\",\n        \"Indian State of Forest Report (ISFR)\",\n        \"Wildlife Protection Survey\",\n        \"Flora and Fauna Census\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Which initiative documents biodiversity at the community level?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"All India Coordinated Project on Taxonomy (AICOPTAX)\",\n        \"People’s Biodiversity Registers (PBRs)\",\n        \"Indian Biodiversity Information System (IBIS)\",\n        \"National Biodiversity Action Plan (NBAP)\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Which act was responsible for the creation of National Parks and Wildlife Sanctuaries in India?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Environmental Protection Act (1986)\",\n        \"Wildlife Protection Act (1972)\",\n        \"Biological Diversity Act (2002)\",\n        \"National Forest Conservation Act (1980)\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"What is the primary goal of the National Mission for Green India (GIM)?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To promote urban development\",\n        \"To increase forest and tree cover\",\n        \"To improve air quality in cities\",\n        \"To conserve river ecosystems\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Which Indian biodiversity hotspot includes the Nicobar megapode and Dugongs?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Western Ghats\",\n        \"Sundaland\",\n        \"Indo-Burma\",\n        \"Himalayas\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Biodiversity refers to the variety of _______ on Earth, including plants, animals, and microorganisms.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"climates\",\n        \"life\",\n        \"rocks\",\n        \"oceans\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"The assessment of biodiversity helps in _______ planning by protecting endangered species.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"urban\",\n        \"conservation\",\n        \"economic\",\n        \"industrial\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"The _______ is a digital platform that collects and shares biodiversity data in India.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"National Forest Database\",\n        \"Indian Biodiversity Information System (IBIS)\",\n        \"Wildlife Census Report\",\n        \"Species Identification System\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"The _______ Act (2002) provides a legal framework for biodiversity conservation in India.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Wildlife Protection\",\n        \"Forest Conservation\",\n        \"Biological Diversity\",\n        \"Environmental Protection\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"The National Biodiversity Authority (NBA) was established to regulate and oversee the use of _______ resources.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"biological\",\n        \"mineral\",\n        \"water\",\n        \"solar\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"India has identified _______ biodiversity hotspots.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"two\",\n        \"three\",\n        \"four\",\n        \"five\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"The Himalayan biodiversity hotspot is home to species such as _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Red pandas\",\n        \"Kangaroos\",\n        \"Penguins\",\n        \"Crocodiles\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"The National Biodiversity Action Plan (NBAP) focuses on _______ conservation and sustainable resource use.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"climate\",\n        \"genetic\",\n        \"habitat\",\n        \"mineral\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"The Indo-Burma biodiversity hotspot includes species such as the _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Hoolock Gibbons\",\n        \"Polar Bear\",\n        \"Koala\",\n        \"Emperor Penguin\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"The Indian State of Forest Report (ISFR) is published every _______ years.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"one\",\n        \"two\",\n        \"five\",\n        \"ten\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"The _______ program aims to increase forest and tree cover in India.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Project Elephant\",\n        \"National Green Mission\",\n        \"National Mission for Green India\",\n        \"Wildlife Conservation Mission\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"The People\'s Biodiversity Registers (PBRs) involve local communities in documenting _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"weather conditions\",\n        \"plant and animal species\",\n        \"mineral deposits\",\n        \"ocean currents\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"The Zoological Survey of India (ZSI) primarily studies _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"plants\",\n        \"animals\",\n        \"minerals\",\n        \"rivers\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"The _______ was launched in 1972 to protect endangered species and their habitats.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Forest Act\",\n        \"Wildlife Protection Act\",\n        \"National Park Act\",\n        \"Conservation Act\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Project Tiger was initiated under the _______ Act.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Biological Diversity\",\n        \"Wildlife Protection\",\n        \"Forest Conservation\",\n        \"Environmental Protection\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"The Western Ghats are home to the endangered _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Lion-tailed macaque\",\n        \"Bengal tiger\",\n        \"Snow leopard\",\n        \"One-horned rhinoceros\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"The Great Indian Bustard is one of the most _______ birds in India.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"common\",\n        \"colorful\",\n        \"endangered\",\n        \"aggressive\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Overexploitation of resources, habitat destruction, and pollution contribute to biodiversity _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"increase\",\n        \"loss\",\n        \"stability\",\n        \"growth\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Invasive species can negatively impact biodiversity by _______ native species.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"helping\",\n        \"competing with\",\n        \"ignoring\",\n        \"saving\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"Climate change can lead to _______ of certain species.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"extinction\",\n        \"growth\",\n        \"expansion\",\n        \"increase\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Biodiversity refers to the variety of life on Earth, including plants, animals, and microorganisms.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"The Biological Diversity Act (2002) does not require companies to seek permission before using biological resources.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"The Indian Biodiversity Information System (IBIS) is a digital platform that collects and shares biodiversity data.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"The National Biodiversity Action Plan (NBAP) focuses only on protecting endangered animals.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"The Himalayas are one of India\'s four biodiversity hotspots.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Biodiversity assessment is important for conservation planning and sustainable development.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"The Indo-Burma region is not considered a biodiversity hotspot in India.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"The Western Ghats contain species like the Lion-tailed macaque and Malabar civet.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"The Zoological Survey of India (ZSI) is responsible for studying plant species in India.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"The Botanical Survey of India (BSI) documents and classifies plant species.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"The Wildlife Protection Act (1972) played a key role in saving the Royal Bengal Tiger.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"The Indian State of Forest Report (ISFR) is published every year.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"The People’s Biodiversity Registers (PBRs) involve local communities in documenting biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Biodiversity assessment does not contribute to climate change mitigation.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Overexploitation of natural resources does not affect biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"The National Mission for Green India (GIM) aims to increase forest and tree cover.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"The All India Coordinated Project on Taxonomy (AICOPTAX) focuses on classifying and recording species.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Biodiversity loss is mainly caused by natural disasters, not human activities.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Mangrove forests are important for marine biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"Habitat destruction has no impact on biodiversity conservation.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"Climate change does not affect biodiversity hotspots.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"Invasive species can outcompete native species and reduce biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"India is home to the Great Indian Bustard, one of the world’s most endangered birds.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"Coral reefs are dying due to rising sea temperatures, a phenomenon called coral bleaching.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"Plastic waste in the ocean has no effect on marine biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"The Dugong is a species found in India’s Sundaland region.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"ZSI and BSI help in discovering new species in India.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"The water hyacinth is a native species that helps improve water quality.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"The Amazon Rainforest is a biodiversity hotspot located in India.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"Overfishing can lead to a decline in fish populations such as tuna and cod.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"The Indian State of Forest Report provides data on deforestation rates.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"National parks and wildlife sanctuaries are established under the Wildlife Protection Act.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"Biodiversity has no impact on agriculture or medicine.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"The Great Indian Bustard is found in dense forests.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"Restoring degraded ecosystems is a goal of the National Mission for Green India.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"The Biological Diversity Act (2002) was passed to regulate and protect biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"Climate change can cause droughts, floods, and extreme temperatures, impacting biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"The National Biodiversity Authority (NBA) does not regulate the use of biological resources.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"Tourism does not benefit from biodiversity conservation.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"The Sundaland biodiversity hotspot includes the Andaman and Nicobar Islands.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"Oil spills do not affect marine biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"Local communities play no role in biodiversity conservation.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"Biodiversity helps in nutrient recycling and climate regulation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"Biodiversity hotspots are regions with low species diversity.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"Poaching of elephants for ivory has made them endangered.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"Sustainable farming and fishing can help protect biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"The Biological Diversity Act promotes the unrestricted use of biological resources.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"Deforestation leads to habitat destruction and loss of biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"The People’s Biodiversity Registers help record local plant and animal species.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"Biodiversity assessment is essential for sustainable development and conservation efforts.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  ',12,6),(24,'3.4-Threats to Biodiversity','<div>\n    <h2>3.4 Threats to Biodiversity</h2>\n    <p>There are several factors that pose a danger to biodiversity. These threats can lead to species extinction, habitat loss, and ecosystem destruction. Some of the major threats include:</p>\n    \n    <h3>1. Habitat Destruction</h3>\n    <p>The most significant threat to biodiversity is the destruction of natural habitats. Forests, wetlands, coral reefs, and grasslands are being cleared for agriculture, urbanization, and industrialization.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> The Amazon Rainforest is being cut down at an alarming rate to make space for cattle ranching and farming.</p>\n    \n    <h3>2. Pollution</h3>\n    <p>Pollution from industries, agriculture, and households affects air, water, and soil quality, harming plants and animals.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Plastic pollution in oceans kills marine animals like turtles, dolphins, and fish.</p>\n    \n    <h3>3. Climate Change</h3>\n    <p>Global warming and unpredictable weather patterns affect ecosystems and species\' survival. Rising temperatures cause ice caps to melt, endangering polar bears and penguins.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Coral bleaching occurs when corals lose their color and die due to warmer ocean temperatures.</p>\n    \n    <h3>4. Overexploitation of Resources</h3>\n    <p>Excessive hunting, fishing, and logging can lead to species decline.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> The overhunting of the dodo bird led to its extinction. Overfishing in oceans is reducing fish populations, impacting marine food chains.</p>\n    \n    <h3>5. Invasive Species</h3>\n    <p>When non-native species are introduced to a new environment, they may outcompete native species and disrupt ecosystems.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> The introduction of water hyacinth in Indian lakes and rivers has led to water pollution and the suffocation of aquatic life.</p>\n    \n    <h3>6. Deforestation</h3>\n    <p>Large-scale clearing of forests for timber, agriculture, and settlements leads to habitat loss and global warming.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> The Sundarbans mangrove forests in India and Bangladesh are shrinking due to excessive tree cutting.</p>\n    \n    <h3>7. Industrial and Agricultural Expansion</h3>\n    <p>Chemical fertilizers and pesticides used in farming harm soil, water, and wildlife.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Pesticides like DDT once harmed bird populations, including eagles and falcons, by weakening their eggshells.</p>\n    \n    <h2>Hotspots of Biodiversity</h2>\n    <p>A biodiversity hotspot is a region that is rich in species diversity but is under severe threat due to human activities. To qualify as a biodiversity hotspot, a region must meet two criteria:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>It must have at least 1,500 species of vascular plants as endemic species (species found nowhere else in the world).</li>\n      <li>It must have lost at least 70% of its original natural vegetation due to human activities.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>Examples of Biodiversity Hotspots in the World</h3>\n    <p>There are 36 biodiversity hotspots globally. Some important ones include:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Amazon Rainforest (South America)</strong> – The world’s largest tropical rainforest, home to jaguars, macaws, and thousands of plant species.</li>\n      <li><strong>The Congo Basin (Africa)</strong> – A dense rainforest home to gorillas, chimpanzees, and rare plant species.</li>\n      <li><strong>Sundaland (Southeast Asia)</strong> – Includes Indonesia, Malaysia, and surrounding areas with species like orangutans and tigers.</li>\n      <li><strong>Madagascar (Africa)</strong> – An island with unique species such as lemurs found nowhere else.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>Biodiversity Hotspots in India</h3>\n    <p>India has four major biodiversity hotspots:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>The Himalayas</strong> – Includes the entire Indian Himalayan region and parts of neighboring countries. It is home to snow leopards, red pandas, and rhododendrons.</li>\n      <li><strong>The Indo-Burma Region</strong> – Covers northeastern India, Myanmar, and surrounding countries. It has many endangered species like the one-horned rhinoceros.</li>\n      <li><strong>The Western Ghats</strong> – A mountain range along the west coast of India, home to species like the Malabar civet and Nilgiri tahr.</li>\n      <li><strong>The Sundaland (Including the Nicobar Islands)</strong> – Home to exotic species like the Nicobar pigeon and saltwater crocodiles.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>Why Should We Protect Biodiversity?</h2>\n    <p>Biodiversity is crucial because it:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>✔️ Provides food, medicine, and resources for survival.</li>\n      <li>✔️ Maintains ecological balance and supports all life forms.</li>\n      <li>✔️ Helps in climate regulation and disaster prevention.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>How Can We Protect Biodiversity?</h2>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Reduce deforestation and plant more trees.</li>\n      <li>Avoid plastic and reduce pollution.</li>\n      <li>Implement laws to protect endangered species.</li>\n      <li>Promote sustainable farming and fishing practices.</li>\n      <li>Raise awareness about the importance of biodiversity.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>Conclusion</h2>\n    <p>Biodiversity is essential for maintaining life on Earth, but it is under severe threat due to human activities. Protecting biodiversity hotspots and reducing environmental damage is necessary for a sustainable future. Through conservation efforts and responsible human actions, we can save our planet’s rich biodiversity.</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is biodiversity?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Variety of life on Earth\",\n        \"Only plant species on Earth\",\n        \"Only animal species on Earth\",\n        \"The number of human populations\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a major threat to biodiversity?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Planting trees\",\n        \"Deforestation\",\n        \"Organic farming\",\n        \"Wildlife conservation\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"What is the most significant threat to biodiversity?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Air pollution\",\n        \"Climate change\",\n        \"Habitat destruction\",\n        \"Sustainable agriculture\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"What is an example of habitat destruction?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Planting forests\",\n        \"Clearing wetlands for urbanization\",\n        \"Setting up wildlife sanctuaries\",\n        \"Reducing air pollution\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Which human activity has led to deforestation in the Amazon Rainforest?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Fishing\",\n        \"Cattle ranching\",\n        \"Solar power generation\",\n        \"Eco-tourism\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"What is a major effect of plastic pollution?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Improved soil fertility\",\n        \"Increased oxygen levels in water\",\n        \"Death of marine animals\",\n        \"Better plant growth\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a result of climate change?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Coral bleaching\",\n        \"More stable weather patterns\",\n        \"Growth of new forests\",\n        \"Increase in biodiversity\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"What led to the extinction of the dodo bird?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Pollution\",\n        \"Overhunting\",\n        \"Climate change\",\n        \"Invasive species\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an example of an invasive species?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Snow leopard\",\n        \"Water hyacinth\",\n        \"Bengal tiger\",\n        \"Indian elephant\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Which species is at risk due to melting ice caps?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Lions\",\n        \"Polar bears\",\n        \"Elephants\",\n        \"Peacocks\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"What percentage of original vegetation must be lost for a region to qualify as a biodiversity hotspot?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"30%\",\n        \"50%\",\n        \"70%\",\n        \"90%\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"How many biodiversity hotspots exist globally?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"12\",\n        \"24\",\n        \"36\",\n        \"50\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Which is the world’s largest tropical rainforest?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Amazon Rainforest\",\n        \"Congo Basin\",\n        \"Sundaland\",\n        \"Himalayas\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Which biodiversity hotspot in Africa is known for its unique species such as lemurs?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Sundaland\",\n        \"Amazon Rainforest\",\n        \"Madagascar\",\n        \"Western Ghats\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"How many biodiversity hotspots are present in India?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Two\",\n        \"Four\",\n        \"Six\",\n        \"Eight\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"Which Indian biodiversity hotspot is home to the snow leopard?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Western Ghats\",\n        \"Sundaland\",\n        \"The Himalayas\",\n        \"Indo-Burma region\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"What species is native to the Indo-Burma biodiversity hotspot?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Malabar civet\",\n        \"One-horned rhinoceros\",\n        \"Royal Bengal Tiger\",\n        \"Red panda\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Which Indian biodiversity hotspot includes the Nicobar Islands?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Western Ghats\",\n        \"Sundaland\",\n        \"Himalayas\",\n        \"Indo-Burma region\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following helps in protecting biodiversity?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Deforestation\",\n        \"Illegal poaching\",\n        \"Wildlife conservation\",\n        \"Overfishing\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"Why is biodiversity important for humans?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"It provides resources for food, medicine, and economy\",\n        \"It increases desertification\",\n        \"It reduces ecosystem stability\",\n        \"It has no impact on human life\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"The most significant threat to biodiversity is ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"pollution\", \"habitat destruction\", \"overfishing\", \"climate change\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Excessive hunting and fishing are examples of ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"habitat destruction\", \"overexploitation\", \"deforestation\", \"invasive species\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"A species that is found only in a particular region and nowhere else is called ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"native species\", \"invasive species\", \"endemic species\", \"migratory species\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"The introduction of non-native species into an ecosystem can lead to ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"pollution\", \"invasive species\", \"climate change\", \"deforestation\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Global warming is primarily caused by increased levels of ________ in the atmosphere.\",\n      \"options\": [\"oxygen\", \"nitrogen\", \"carbon dioxide\", \"hydrogen\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"The Western Ghats is one of the four ________ in India.\",\n      \"options\": [\"national parks\", \"biodiversity hotspots\", \"wildlife sanctuaries\", \"biosphere reserves\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"The Great Indian Bustard is an endangered species protected under ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"National Biodiversity Action Plan\", \"Wildlife Protection Act\", \"Forest Conservation Act\", \"Indian Biodiversity Information System\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"The Amazon Rainforest is being cleared mainly for ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"tourism\", \"cattle ranching and farming\", \"urbanization\", \"fishing\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Coral bleaching occurs due to ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"water pollution\", \"rising ocean temperatures\", \"oil spills\", \"deforestation\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"India has ________ major biodiversity hotspots.\",\n      \"options\": [\"two\", \"four\", \"six\", \"eight\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"The Himalayan biodiversity hotspot is home to ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Royal Bengal Tiger\", \"Snow Leopard\", \"Asian Elephant\", \"Indian Peafowl\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"Illegal hunting of animals for their body parts is known as ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"conservation\", \"poaching\", \"breeding\", \"domestication\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Excessive use of chemical fertilizers and pesticides leads to ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"pollution\", \"biodiversity conservation\", \"wildlife protection\", \"species diversity\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"The Indian State of Forest Report (ISFR) is published every ________ years.\",\n      \"options\": [\"one\", \"two\", \"three\", \"five\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"The Biological Diversity Act was enacted in the year ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"1992\", \"2002\", \"2010\", \"2015\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"People’s Biodiversity Registers (PBRs) document ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"climate data\", \"local biodiversity\", \"economic growth\", \"scientific research\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"The National Mission for Green India aims to increase ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"water conservation\", \"pollution\", \"forest and tree cover\", \"industrial growth\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"A region must have at least ________ species of vascular plants to qualify as a biodiversity hotspot.\",\n      \"options\": [\"500\", \"1,500\", \"5,000\", \"10,000\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"The Sundarbans are known for the conservation of ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Asiatic Lion\", \"Royal Bengal Tiger\", \"Indian Cobra\", \"Black Panther\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"Overfishing has led to a decline in ________ populations.\",\n      \"options\": [\"pandas\", \"dolphins\", \"tuna and cod\", \"kangaroos\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that biodiversity includes plants, animals, microorganisms, and ecosystems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that biodiversity only refers to the variety of animal species on Earth.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that habitat destruction is the most significant threat to biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that pollution has no effect on biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that climate change affects ecosystems and species\' survival.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that global warming has no impact on coral reefs.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that overexploitation of resources like excessive hunting and fishing can lead to species decline.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that deforestation only affects animals and has no impact on global warming.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that invasive species can disrupt ecosystems by outcompeting native species.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that industrial and agricultural expansion has no effect on biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that biodiversity hotspots contain a high number of endemic species.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that a region must have only 500 endemic plant species to qualify as a biodiversity hotspot.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that at least 70% of a region\'s original natural vegetation must be lost for it to be considered a biodiversity hotspot.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that there are only 10 biodiversity hotspots in the world.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the Amazon Rainforest is the world\'s largest tropical rainforest.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the Congo Basin is located in South America.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the Sundaland biodiversity hotspot includes Indonesia and Malaysia.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Madagascar is not a biodiversity hotspot.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that India has four major biodiversity hotspots.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the Himalayas are not a biodiversity hotspot in India.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the Indo-Burma region includes northeastern India.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the Western Ghats are located in northern India.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the Sundaland biodiversity hotspot includes the Nicobar Islands.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that biodiversity does not help in climate regulation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that deforestation can be reduced by planting more trees.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that plastic pollution has no effect on marine life.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that overfishing reduces fish populations and disrupts marine food chains.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that conservation laws are unnecessary for protecting endangered species.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that sustainable farming can help protect biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that biodiversity loss does not impact human life.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that coral bleaching occurs due to warmer ocean temperatures.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that industrial pollution only affects humans and not biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that raising awareness is an important step in protecting biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  ',12,6),(25,'3.5-Conservation of Biodiversity','<div>\n    <h2>3.5 Conservation of Biodiversity</h2>\n    <h3>What is Biodiversity?</h3>\n    <p>Biodiversity means the variety of life on Earth. It includes different types of plants, animals, microorganisms, and ecosystems like forests, rivers, oceans, and deserts.</p>\n    <p>Biodiversity is essential because:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>✅ It keeps nature balanced.</li>\n      <li>✅ It provides food, medicine, and raw materials.</li>\n      <li>✅ It helps in controlling climate and diseases.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>What is Conservation of Biodiversity?</h3>\n    <p>Conservation of biodiversity means protecting and preserving plants, animals, and natural habitats. It ensures that future generations can enjoy and benefit from nature.</p>\n    \n    <h3>Objectives of Biodiversity Conservation</h3>\n    <p>The main goal of conservation is to protect species and ecosystems while allowing sustainable use of natural resources. The objectives can be divided into three main types:</p>\n    \n    <h4>1. Preservation of Species</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>✔ Saving endangered species from extinction.</li>\n      <li>✔ Protecting species that are on the verge of disappearing.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p>Example:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>The Bengal tiger in India is endangered, so the government has created reserves like Sundarbans Tiger Reserve to protect them.</li>\n      <li>The Great Indian Bustard, a rare bird, is being protected in Rajasthan.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>2. Protection of Natural Habitats</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>✔ Safeguarding forests, wetlands, and other ecosystems where wildlife lives.</li>\n      <li>✔ Preventing activities like deforestation, pollution, and land conversion.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p>Example:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>The Amazon Rainforest, known as the “lungs of the Earth,” is protected in many areas to prevent excessive deforestation.</li>\n      <li>Kaziranga National Park in India protects one-horned rhinoceroses from poaching and habitat destruction.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>3. Sustainable Use of Resources</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>✔ Using natural resources wisely so they don’t get exhausted.</li>\n      <li>✔ Encouraging eco-friendly practices like organic farming, renewable energy, and reforestation.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p>Example:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Sustainable fishing helps prevent overfishing in oceans.</li>\n      <li>Agroforestry (growing trees along with crops) conserves soil and biodiversity.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>Various Laws for Biodiversity Conservation</h3>\n    <p>Different countries have made laws to protect biodiversity. In India, several laws and international agreements help in conservation.</p>\n    \n    <h4>1. Wildlife Protection Act, 1972 (India)</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>✔ This law protects wild animals and plants from hunting and trade.</li>\n      <li>✔ It creates national parks, wildlife sanctuaries, and reserves.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p>Example:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Hunting tigers is illegal under this law.</li>\n      <li>Poachers caught smuggling elephant tusks can be jailed.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>2. Forest Conservation Act, 1980 (India)</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>✔ Prevents deforestation and ensures forests are not destroyed for commercial use.</li>\n      <li>✔ Requires special permission for cutting down forests.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p>Example:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>If a company wants to build a factory in a forest, it needs government approval.</li>\n      <li>Many forest areas are re-planted after cutting down trees.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>3. Biological Diversity Act, 2002 (India)</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>✔ Protects Indian biological resources and prevents their misuse by foreign companies.</li>\n      <li>✔ Encourages local communities to conserve biodiversity.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p>Example:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Foreign companies cannot patent Indian traditional medicinal plants like Neem, Turmeric, and Basmati rice.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>4. Environment Protection Act, 1986 (India)</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>✔ Gives the government the power to take action against pollution and environmental damage.</li>\n      <li>✔ Helps in protecting air, water, and land biodiversity.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p>Example:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Industries dumping waste in rivers can be fined or shut down.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>5. International Laws and Agreements</h4>\n    <p>Several global agreements help in biodiversity conservation.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>(a) Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) – 1992</strong>\n        <ul>\n          <li>✔ Signed by 196 countries to protect biodiversity worldwide.</li>\n          <li>✔ Encourages sustainable use of natural resources.</li>\n        </ul>\n      </li>\n      <li><strong>(b) Ramsar Convention on Wetlands – 1971</strong>\n        <ul>\n          <li>✔ Protects important wetland areas that provide homes for birds, fish, and plants.</li>\n        </ul>\n        <p>Example: Chilika Lake in India is a Ramsar site that protects migratory birds.</p>\n      </li>\n      <li><strong>(c) CITES (Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species) – 1973</strong>\n        <ul>\n          <li>✔ Bans the trade of endangered animals and plants.</li>\n        </ul>\n        <p>Example: Buying and selling ivory from elephants is illegal worldwide.</p>\n      </li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>Ways We Can Help in Biodiversity Conservation</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>? Plant more trees – Prevents deforestation and provides homes for animals.</li>\n      <li>? Avoid plastic waste – Reduces pollution in oceans and rivers.</li>\n      <li>? Support wildlife protection – Avoid products made from animal parts.</li>\n      <li>? Use less energy – Saves natural resources like coal and oil.</li>\n      <li>? Eat sustainable food – Choose organic and local food.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>Conclusion</h3>\n    <p>Biodiversity is essential for a healthy planet. Conservation efforts include protecting species, preserving natural habitats, and using resources wisely. By taking small steps, everyone can contribute to preserving biodiversity for future generations.</p>\n</div>','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What does biodiversity refer to?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Only plant species on Earth\",\n        \"Variety of life on Earth\",\n        \"Only animal species on Earth\",\n        \"The number of human populations\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"What is the main goal of biodiversity conservation?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To prevent plant growth\",\n        \"To protect species and ecosystems\",\n        \"To increase hunting\",\n        \"To promote deforestation\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an objective of biodiversity conservation?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Increasing industrial expansion\",\n        \"Preservation of species\",\n        \"Destroying natural habitats\",\n        \"Encouraging pollution\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"What is an example of preserving endangered species?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Hunting tigers for fur\",\n        \"Creating reserves like Sundarbans Tiger Reserve\",\n        \"Converting forests into urban areas\",\n        \"Polluting water bodies\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a method to protect natural habitats?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Safeguarding forests and wetlands\",\n        \"Expanding mining activities\",\n        \"Encouraging poaching\",\n        \"Cutting down trees for timber\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which is an example of sustainable use of natural resources?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Overfishing in oceans\",\n        \"Using renewable energy sources\",\n        \"Destroying forests for farming\",\n        \"Excessive use of pesticides\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Which Indian law was enacted to protect wild animals and plants?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Forest Conservation Act, 1980\",\n        \"Wildlife Protection Act, 1972\",\n        \"Biological Diversity Act, 2002\",\n        \"Environment Protection Act, 1986\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"What does the Wildlife Protection Act, 1972 prohibit?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Poaching and illegal wildlife trade\",\n        \"Planting trees\",\n        \"Water conservation\",\n        \"Creating nature reserves\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Which act prevents deforestation in India?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Wildlife Protection Act, 1972\",\n        \"Forest Conservation Act, 1980\",\n        \"Biological Diversity Act, 2002\",\n        \"Ramsar Convention\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Under the Forest Conservation Act, 1980, what is required before cutting down forests?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Public approval\",\n        \"No permission needed\",\n        \"Special government permission\",\n        \"Farmer\'s consent\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"What is the purpose of the Biological Diversity Act, 2002?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To prevent the misuse of Indian biological resources\",\n        \"To promote deforestation\",\n        \"To allow foreign companies to exploit Indian resources\",\n        \"To increase pollution\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"Which act gives the Indian government the power to control pollution and environmental damage?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Biological Diversity Act, 2002\",\n        \"Environment Protection Act, 1986\",\n        \"Wildlife Protection Act, 1972\",\n        \"CITES\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Which international agreement aims to protect biodiversity worldwide?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"CITES\",\n        \"Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD)\",\n        \"Wildlife Protection Act\",\n        \"Environment Protection Act\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Which international convention protects wetlands?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"CITES\",\n        \"Ramsar Convention\",\n        \"CBD\",\n        \"Biological Diversity Act\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Which site in India is protected under the Ramsar Convention?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Kaziranga National Park\",\n        \"Chilika Lake\",\n        \"Sundarbans\",\n        \"Western Ghats\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"Which law bans the trade of endangered species worldwide?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"CBD\",\n        \"Wildlife Protection Act\",\n        \"CITES\",\n        \"Ramsar Convention\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an illegal trade item under CITES?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Elephant ivory\",\n        \"Timber\",\n        \"Organic vegetables\",\n        \"Solar panels\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Why is biodiversity conservation important?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"It helps maintain ecological balance\",\n        \"It leads to species extinction\",\n        \"It reduces forest cover\",\n        \"It encourages industrial expansion\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Which activity promotes biodiversity conservation?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Overfishing\",\n        \"Hunting endangered species\",\n        \"Reforestation\",\n        \"Pollution\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"Which practice reduces deforestation?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Planting more trees\",\n        \"Using fossil fuels\",\n        \"Burning forests for agriculture\",\n        \"Urbanization\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Biodiversity refers to the variety of ________ on Earth.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ecosystems\",\n        \"species\",\n        \"natural resources\",\n        \"living organisms\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"The primary goal of biodiversity conservation is to protect species and ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ecosystems\",\n        \"rivers\",\n        \"land\",\n        \"industries\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"The Bengal tiger is protected under the ________ Tiger Reserve.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Sundarbans\",\n        \"Kaziranga\",\n        \"Jim Corbett\",\n        \"Gir\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"The Great Indian Bustard is a rare bird found in ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Karnataka\",\n        \"Maharashtra\",\n        \"Rajasthan\",\n        \"Tamil Nadu\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Deforestation leads to habitat loss and contributes to ________ change.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"economic\",\n        \"cultural\",\n        \"climate\",\n        \"political\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"________ National Park in India protects the one-horned rhinoceros.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Jim Corbett\",\n        \"Kaziranga\",\n        \"Sundarbans\",\n        \"Gir\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Sustainable use of resources ensures they do not get ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"wasted\",\n        \"exhausted\",\n        \"damaged\",\n        \"destroyed\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ Act, 1972, protects wild animals and plants from hunting and trade in India.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Biological Diversity\",\n        \"Environment Protection\",\n        \"Wildlife Protection\",\n        \"Forest Conservation\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"The Forest Conservation Act, ________, prevents deforestation.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"1972\",\n        \"1980\",\n        \"1992\",\n        \"2002\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"The Environment Protection Act, ________, helps in protecting air, water, and land biodiversity.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"1972\",\n        \"1980\",\n        \"1986\",\n        \"2002\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"The Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) was signed in ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"1972\",\n        \"1980\",\n        \"1992\",\n        \"2002\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"The Ramsar Convention aims to protect important ________ areas.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"desert\",\n        \"wetland\",\n        \"forest\",\n        \"mountain\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"CITES bans the trade of ________ animals and plants.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"medicinal\",\n        \"endangered\",\n        \"agricultural\",\n        \"aquatic\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"The Amazon Rainforest is often called the \'________ of the Earth\'.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Heart\",\n        \"Lungs\",\n        \"Brain\",\n        \"Kidney\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Agroforestry helps conserve biodiversity by growing ________ along with crops.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"grasses\",\n        \"weeds\",\n        \"trees\",\n        \"fungi\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"The Himalayas, Indo-Burma, Western Ghats, and Sundaland are India\'s four major ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"national parks\",\n        \"biodiversity hotspots\",\n        \"forests\",\n        \"rivers\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"The illegal hunting of animals is known as ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"poaching\",\n        \"conservation\",\n        \"pollution\",\n        \"urbanization\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"________ forests are home to the endangered snow leopard.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Amazon\",\n        \"Himalayan\",\n        \"Sundarbans\",\n        \"Western Ghats\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Using natural resources responsibly to meet present and future needs is called ________ development.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"industrial\",\n        \"sustainable\",\n        \"technological\",\n        \"mechanized\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"The introduction of non-native species that harm local ecosystems is called an ________ species.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"endemic\",\n        \"invasive\",\n        \"native\",\n        \"migratory\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that biodiversity includes only animals and plants.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that biodiversity helps in controlling climate and diseases.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that conservation of biodiversity only focuses on protecting animals.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that preserving species is one of the main objectives of biodiversity conservation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the Bengal tiger is a species that does not require any conservation efforts.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the Great Indian Bustard is protected in Rajasthan.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that protecting natural habitats is not necessary for biodiversity conservation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that deforestation can harm biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that sustainable use of resources is not an objective of biodiversity conservation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that overfishing can harm ocean biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the Wildlife Protection Act, 1972, allows hunting of endangered species.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the Forest Conservation Act, 1980, prevents deforestation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the Biological Diversity Act, 2002, allows foreign companies to patent Indian medicinal plants.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the Environment Protection Act, 1986, helps prevent pollution and environmental damage.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that industries dumping waste into rivers cannot be penalized under the Environment Protection Act.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) was signed in 1992.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the Ramsar Convention protects desert ecosystems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that Chilika Lake in India is a Ramsar site.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that CITES allows the trade of ivory from elephants.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that planting more trees helps in biodiversity conservation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that plastic waste does not affect ocean biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that agroforestry helps in conserving soil and biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that only governments are responsible for biodiversity conservation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that biodiversity conservation benefits future generations.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that eating sustainable food has no impact on biodiversity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  ',12,6),(26,'1.1-Operating System (OS)','<div>\n    <h1>1.1 Operating System (OS)</h1>\n    <h2>What is an Operating System (OS)?</h2>\n    <p>An Operating System (OS) is a software that acts as an interface between the user and the computer hardware. It helps users perform tasks like running applications, managing files, and using computer resources efficiently.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Think of an OS like a manager in a company. The manager ensures that employees (applications) get the right resources (CPU, memory, etc.) to work efficiently without conflicts.</p>\n    <h3>Some common operating systems:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Windows (Used in most personal computers)</li>\n      <li>macOS (Used in Apple computers)</li>\n      <li>Linux (Used in servers and programming)</li>\n      <li>Android (Used in mobile phones)</li>\n      <li>iOS (Used in Apple mobile devices)</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>Components of an Operating System</h2>\n    <h3>1. Kernel</h3>\n    <p>The kernel is the core part of the OS. It directly interacts with the hardware and manages system resources.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Think of the kernel as a chef in a restaurant. It takes orders from customers (users) and prepares food (processes tasks) using kitchen tools (hardware).</p>\n    \n    <h3>2. Process Management</h3>\n    <p>It manages running applications (called processes) and ensures that CPU time is given to different tasks efficiently.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> If you open multiple apps on your phone (like WhatsApp and YouTube), the OS decides which app runs in the background and which one is active.</p>\n    \n    <h3>3. Memory Management</h3>\n    <p>It allocates and deallocates memory (RAM) to programs so they can run efficiently.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> If you have 4GB RAM and you open Chrome, Word, and Spotify, the OS decides how much memory each application gets.</p>\n    \n    <h3>4. File System Management</h3>\n    <p>It helps in storing, retrieving, and organizing files on storage devices like Hard Drives or SSDs.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> When you save a document in C:\\Documents\\file.docx, the OS keeps track of where it is stored so you can access it later.</p>\n    \n    <h3>5. Device Management</h3>\n    <p>It controls hardware devices like keyboards, printers, and USB drives. The OS ensures these devices work properly.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> When you plug in a pen drive, the OS detects it and allows you to transfer files.</p>\n    \n    <h3>6. User Interface</h3>\n    <p>It provides a way for users to interact with the computer, such as Graphical User Interface (GUI) and Command Line Interface (CLI).</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> GUI: Windows with icons and buttons (like in Windows 10). CLI: Commands typed in a terminal (like in Linux).</p>\n    \n    <h2>Operations of an Operating System</h2>\n    <h3>1. Program Management</h3>\n    <p>OS loads, runs, and closes programs. It manages multiple programs using multitasking.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> When you open a web browser and a video editor at the same time, the OS ensures both run without crashing.</p>\n    \n    <h3>2. Resource Management</h3>\n    <p>The OS distributes CPU time, memory, and disk space efficiently among processes.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> In a bank, multiple employees (processes) need computers (resources). The OS ensures every process gets its share.</p>\n    \n    <h3>3. Security and Protection</h3>\n    <p>OS protects the system from viruses, hackers, and unauthorized access. It provides password protection, firewalls, and encryption.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Your phone has a password or fingerprint lock—this is the OS ensuring security.</p>\n    \n    <h2>Views of an Operating System</h2>\n    <h3>1. User View</h3>\n    <p>Focuses on how users interact with the OS. Users care about ease of use, speed, and efficiency.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> When you use Windows, you see icons, folders, and a Start menu, making it easy to use.</p>\n    \n    <h3>2. System View</h3>\n    <p>Focuses on how the OS manages hardware and resources internally. The OS ensures that hardware components work efficiently together.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Inside your laptop, the OS manages RAM, CPU, and storage to ensure smooth performance.</p>\n    \n    <h2>Conclusion</h2>\n    <p>An Operating System (OS) is like the brain of a computer. It manages everything, from running programs to ensuring security. Without an OS, using a computer would be very difficult.</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is an Operating System (OS)?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"A type of hardware\",\n        \"A software that acts as an interface between user and hardware\",\n        \"A programming language\",\n        \"A type of network protocol\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is NOT an example of an Operating System?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Windows\",\n        \"Linux\",\n        \"Google Chrome\",\n        \"macOS\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"What is the core component of an Operating System?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"File System\",\n        \"Kernel\",\n        \"User Interface\",\n        \"Device Manager\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Which component of an OS is responsible for process management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Memory Management\",\n        \"Process Management\",\n        \"Device Management\",\n        \"Security Management\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"What is the function of Memory Management in an OS?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Managing running applications\",\n        \"Allocating and deallocating RAM\",\n        \"Controlling file system operations\",\n        \"Handling input/output devices\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which OS component manages hardware devices like printers and keyboards?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Device Management\",\n        \"Process Management\",\n        \"Memory Management\",\n        \"User Interface\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an example of a mobile operating system?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Windows\",\n        \"Linux\",\n        \"Android\",\n        \"macOS\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Which operation of an OS involves multitasking?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Security Management\",\n        \"Program Management\",\n        \"User Interface\",\n        \"File System Management\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Which OS operation is responsible for protecting data from hackers?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Security and Protection\",\n        \"Resource Management\",\n        \"Process Management\",\n        \"User Interface\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"How does the OS manage running applications?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"By allocating CPU time efficiently\",\n        \"By removing applications automatically\",\n        \"By upgrading them\",\n        \"By duplicating them\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"What is the main function of the User Interface in an OS?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Managing memory\",\n        \"Providing interaction between user and system\",\n        \"Controlling CPU scheduling\",\n        \"Managing security settings\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"What is the difference between GUI and CLI?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"GUI uses a command-line interface, CLI uses a graphical interface\",\n        \"GUI is text-based, CLI is icon-based\",\n        \"GUI uses icons and buttons, CLI uses text commands\",\n        \"There is no difference\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Which type of OS allows multiple users to access a system at the same time?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Single-user OS\",\n        \"Real-time OS\",\n        \"Time-Shared OS\",\n        \"Batch OS\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Which OS is designed to handle real-time tasks with strict timing constraints?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Batch OS\",\n        \"Real-Time OS\",\n        \"Time-Shared OS\",\n        \"Multi-User OS\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Which OS component organizes and stores files on a computer?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Memory Management\",\n        \"Process Management\",\n        \"File System Management\",\n        \"User Interface\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"An Operating System (OS) acts as an interface between the user and the _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"applications\", \"hardware\", \"software\", \"internet\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"The core component of an OS that interacts directly with hardware is called the _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Shell\", \"Kernel\", \"BIOS\", \"Driver\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"The OS ensures multiple applications run smoothly using _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"monotasking\", \"single-threading\", \"multitasking\", \"one-time execution\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"The component of the OS responsible for managing CPU execution time is _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Process Management\", \"Memory Management\", \"File System Management\", \"User Interface\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"To protect a computer from unauthorized access, the OS provides features like _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"encryption\", \"open access\", \"auto-login\", \"unprotected networks\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"An example of a mobile operating system is _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Windows\", \"Linux\", \"Android\", \"macOS\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"The OS function responsible for allocating and deallocating RAM is called _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Process Management\", \"Memory Management\", \"File System Management\", \"Security Management\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"A _______ operating system processes jobs in groups without direct user interaction.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Real-time\", \"Batch\", \"Time-shared\", \"Distributed\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"A distributed operating system allows multiple computers to function as a _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"single system\", \"separate units\", \"independent networks\", \"isolated devices\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"The component of the OS that helps users interact with the system is the _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Kernel\", \"File System\", \"User Interface\", \"Process Manager\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"Windows and macOS provide a graphical interface, also known as _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"CLI\", \"TUI\", \"GUI\", \"Shell\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"A _______ OS ensures that critical tasks are executed within a fixed time frame.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Batch\", \"Multi-user\", \"Real-time\", \"Time-sharing\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Security measures in an OS include firewalls, encryption, and _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"open-access\", \"authentication\", \"malware\", \"bugs\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"The _______ is responsible for organizing and storing files on a storage device.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Process Manager\", \"File System\", \"User Interface\", \"Shell\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"The primary function of a multiprocessor OS is to manage multiple _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"users\", \"processors\", \"keyboards\", \"storages\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that an Operating System (OS) acts as an interface between the user and the computer hardware.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that an Operating System is a hardware component of a computer.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Windows, macOS, and Linux are examples of operating systems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Android and iOS are types of desktop operating systems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"The kernel is the core component of an operating system that interacts directly with hardware.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the user directly interacts with the kernel in a typical OS setup.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Process Management ensures that multiple processes run efficiently on a system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that memory management only deals with permanent storage like hard drives.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"A file system helps in organizing and retrieving files on storage devices.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the OS has no role in managing input and output devices like keyboards and printers.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"A graphical user interface (GUI) is a visual way for users to interact with an OS.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that a command-line interface (CLI) does not allow users to interact with an OS.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Program management in an OS is responsible for loading, running, and closing programs.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n  \n  \n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that resource management in an OS does not allocate CPU time to different processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Security and protection in an OS help prevent unauthorized access and cyber threats.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that an OS does not provide password protection or encryption mechanisms.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"The user view of an OS focuses on how easy it is for users to interact with the system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the system view of an OS does not consider hardware management.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Batch operating systems execute jobs in groups without user interaction during execution.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that multi-programmed operating systems allow only one program to run at a time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"Time-sharing operating systems allow multiple users to share system resources simultaneously.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that multiprocessor systems use a single CPU to execute tasks.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"Distributed operating systems connect multiple computers to work together as a single system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that real-time operating systems are not used in critical applications like medical devices and flight control.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"Android is an example of a mobile operating system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that iOS is a desktop operating system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"The OS is responsible for process scheduling to ensure smooth execution of multiple tasks.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the file system management component of an OS is only required for cloud storage.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"Security in an OS helps prevent unauthorized access to system resources.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that every OS must have a graphical user interface (GUI).\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"Device management in an OS ensures efficient communication between hardware and software.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that an OS cannot run multiple applications at the same time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  ',13,9),(27,'1.2-Different Types of Operating Systems','<div>\n    <h1>Different Types of Operating Systems</h1>\n    <p>An Operating System (OS) is the main software that controls a computer. It manages hardware (like the keyboard, mouse, and memory), runs programs, and allows users to interact with the computer. Different types of operating systems are used for different purposes. Let\'s explore them one by one with easy examples.</p>\n  \n    <h2>1. Batch Operating System</h2>\n    <p><strong>Definition:</strong> A Batch Operating System processes a group (batch) of similar jobs automatically without user interaction.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> A bank processing cheques in batches.</p>\n    <p><strong>Real-life Example:</strong> IBM mainframe computers used for payroll processing.</p>\n    <p><strong>Key Features:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>No direct user interaction during execution.</li>\n      <li>Jobs are processed in a queue (first-come, first-served).</li>\n      <li>Used for tasks like payroll processing and billing.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h2>2. Multi-Programmed Operating System</h2>\n    <p><strong>Definition:</strong> A Multi-Programmed OS allows multiple programs to run at the same time by managing CPU usage efficiently.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Downloading a movie while listening to music.</p>\n    <p><strong>Real-life Example:</strong> Windows and macOS allowing multiple applications to run.</p>\n    <p><strong>Key Features:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Increases CPU utilization by switching between programs.</li>\n      <li>Multiple users can use the computer at the same time.</li>\n      <li>Reduces CPU idle time.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h2>3. Time-Shared Operating System</h2>\n    <p><strong>Definition:</strong> A Time-Shared OS allows multiple users to share the same computer resources by giving each user a small time slot.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> A teacher allowing students to speak one by one.</p>\n    <p><strong>Real-life Example:</strong> Cloud computing services like Google Drive.</p>\n    <p><strong>Key Features:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Allows multiple users to work simultaneously.</li>\n      <li>CPU switches between users quickly.</li>\n      <li>Reduces waiting time for users.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h2>4. Multiprocessor Operating System</h2>\n    <p><strong>Definition:</strong> A Multiprocessor OS is designed to work with computers that have multiple processors.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> A restaurant with multiple chefs working together.</p>\n    <p><strong>Real-life Example:</strong> Supercomputers used in weather forecasting.</p>\n    <p><strong>Key Features:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Multiple processors work together for better performance.</li>\n      <li>Increases speed and efficiency.</li>\n      <li>Used in supercomputers and high-performance applications.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h2>5. Distributed Operating System</h2>\n    <p><strong>Definition:</strong> A Distributed OS connects multiple computers over a network to act as a single system.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Food delivery services like Zomato connecting restaurants and customers.</p>\n    <p><strong>Real-life Example:</strong> Google Search running on multiple computers.</p>\n    <p><strong>Key Features:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Multiple computers work together like a single system.</li>\n      <li>Increases speed and fault tolerance.</li>\n      <li>Used in cloud computing and large-scale applications.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h2>6. Real-Time Operating System (RTOS)</h2>\n    <p><strong>Definition:</strong> A Real-Time OS processes data and responds immediately without delays.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Airbag deployment in cars.</p>\n    <p><strong>Real-life Example:</strong> Medical devices and air traffic control systems.</p>\n    <p><strong>Key Features:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Processes data instantly with no delay.</li>\n      <li>Used in critical applications like healthcare and aviation.</li>\n      <li>Two types: Hard Real-Time OS (zero delay) and Soft Real-Time OS (minimal delay).</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h2>7. Mobile Operating Systems (Android & iOS)</h2>\n    <p><strong>Definition:</strong> A Mobile OS is designed for smartphones and tablets.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Running multiple apps on a phone.</p>\n    <p><strong>Types of Mobile OS:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Android OS:</strong> Developed by Google, open-source.</li>\n      <li><strong>iOS:</strong> Developed by Apple, closed-source.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p><strong>Key Features:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>User-friendly and designed for touchscreens.</li>\n      <li>Manages apps, security, and hardware.</li>\n      <li>Used in smartphones, tablets, and smart devices.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h2>Conclusion</h2>\n    <p>Different operating systems are designed for different purposes. Batch OS is used for automated job processing, while Multi-Programmed OS and Time-Shared OS improve efficiency. Multiprocessor OS increases speed using multiple CPUs, and Distributed OS connects multiple systems. Real-Time OS is used in critical applications, while Mobile OS powers our smartphones.</p>\n    <p>Understanding these types helps us appreciate how computers, mobile phones, and large-scale systems work efficiently. ?</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is the primary function of an Operating System (OS)?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To act as an interface between hardware and software\",\n        \"To directly execute user programs\",\n        \"To manufacture computer hardware\",\n        \"To design application software\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Which type of Operating System processes jobs in groups without user interaction?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Multi-Programmed OS\",\n        \"Batch OS\",\n        \"Time-Shared OS\",\n        \"Real-Time OS\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"What is a real-life example of a Batch Operating System?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Online banking transactions\",\n        \"Payroll processing in companies\",\n        \"Live video streaming\",\n        \"Playing an online multiplayer game\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Which OS type allows multiple programs to run by efficiently utilizing CPU time?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Batch OS\",\n        \"Multi-Programmed OS\",\n        \"Time-Shared OS\",\n        \"Mobile OS\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"What is an example of a Multi-Programmed OS in daily life?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"A microwave oven operating system\",\n        \"A computer running a web browser, music player, and document editor simultaneously\",\n        \"A single ATM processing one transaction at a time\",\n        \"A computer booting up\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"What is the key feature of a Time-Shared Operating System?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Processing jobs in batches\",\n        \"Allowing multiple users to interact with the system simultaneously\",\n        \"Using multiple processors to execute tasks\",\n        \"Controlling real-time industrial operations\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Which computing scenario best represents a Time-Shared OS?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"A group of students using a shared university server for coding assignments\",\n        \"A traffic light system responding to real-time sensor data\",\n        \"A supercomputer performing complex calculations for weather forecasting\",\n        \"An iPhone running mobile applications\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"What is a Multiprocessor Operating System designed for?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Managing multiple users on a single computer\",\n        \"Using multiple CPUs to increase computing performance\",\n        \"Allowing multiple tasks to execute on a single CPU\",\n        \"Ensuring critical tasks meet deadlines\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Which device commonly uses a Multiprocessor OS?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"An old typewriter\",\n        \"A modern gaming console like PlayStation\",\n        \"A wristwatch\",\n        \"A basic calculator\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"What is the main advantage of a Distributed OS?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"It works without user input\",\n        \"It connects multiple computers to function as one system\",\n        \"It is only used in mobile devices\",\n        \"It eliminates the need for RAM\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"A Batch Operating System processes a group of similar jobs ________ user interaction.\",\n      \"options\": [\"with\", \"without\", \"by requiring\", \"along with\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"In a Multi-Programmed OS, multiple programs run at the same time by managing ________ usage efficiently.\",\n      \"options\": [\"RAM\", \"CPU\", \"Cache\", \"Hard Disk\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"A Time-Shared OS provides each user with a small ________, making it seem like all users are using the system simultaneously.\",\n      \"options\": [\"window\", \"time slot\", \"space\", \"process\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"A Multiprocessor OS is designed to work with computers that have multiple ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"hard disks\", \"processors\", \"monitors\", \"users\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Google Search is an example of a ________ Operating System.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Batch\", \"Time-Shared\", \"Distributed\", \"Real-Time\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"A Real-Time Operating System (RTOS) is designed to process data and respond ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"whenever needed\", \"immediately\", \"at its convenience\", \"randomly\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"An example of a mobile operating system is ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Windows\", \"Linux\", \"Android\", \"macOS\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"The OS function responsible for managing CPU execution time is ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Process Management\", \"Memory Management\", \"File System Management\", \"User Interface\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"A Distributed OS connects multiple computers over a ________ to act as a single system.\",\n      \"options\": [\"cable\", \"power supply\", \"network\", \"keyboard\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"In a Real-Time OS, even a ________ delay can be critical.\",\n      \"options\": [\"minute\", \"second\", \"hour\", \"week\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"A Batch Operating System processes jobs in real-time with direct user interaction.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"A Multi-Programmed OS increases CPU utilization by switching between programs.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Time-Shared Operating Systems allocate a small time slot to each user to create the illusion of simultaneous execution.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"A Multiprocessor OS is designed to run on a single-core processor only.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Distributed Operating Systems connect multiple computers to work as a single system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"A Real-Time Operating System (RTOS) ensures that critical tasks are executed without any delay.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Mobile Operating Systems are designed specifically for personal computers.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Batch Operating Systems are mainly used in payroll processing and bill generation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Multi-Programmed Operating Systems reduce CPU idle time by managing multiple programs.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Time-Shared Operating Systems are also known as real-time systems.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"Multiprocessor Operating Systems use multiple CPUs to enhance performance.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"Distributed Operating Systems cannot function without an internet connection.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Real-Time Operating Systems are commonly used in life-critical systems like medical devices and air traffic control.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Android and iOS are examples of mobile operating systems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Batch Operating Systems execute jobs one after another without any user intervention.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"A Multi-Programmed OS allows only one process to run at a time.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"Time-Shared Operating Systems improve user experience by providing each user with a dedicated CPU.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Multiprocessor systems can be used in supercomputers for complex calculations.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Google Search and cloud computing services use distributed operating systems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"A Real-Time Operating System cannot be used in robotics and industrial automation.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"Mobile Operating Systems are optimized for touchscreen devices.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"Batch Operating Systems provide immediate responses to user inputs.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"In a Time-Shared Operating System, multiple users share system resources efficiently.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"A Multiprocessor OS decreases processing speed by distributing tasks among multiple processors.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"Distributed OS improves system fault tolerance by distributing tasks among different computers.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"A Soft Real-Time OS allows slight delays in task execution.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"Android OS is an open-source mobile operating system developed by Google.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"iOS is an open-source mobile operating system available for all mobile manufacturers.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"Time-Shared Operating Systems are commonly used in cloud computing environments.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"Real-Time Operating Systems are not used in medical devices like heart monitors.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    }\n]\n  ',13,9),(28,'1.3-Command Line Based OS & GUI Based OS','<div>\n    <h1>1.3 Command Line Based OS & GUI Based OS</h1>\n    <p>Operating Systems (OS) are the software that help users interact with the computer. Based on the interface, they can be categorized into two types:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Command Line Based OS – DOS, UNIX</li>\n      <li>Graphical User Interface (GUI) Based OS – Windows, Linux</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p>Let’s understand both with examples.</p>\n  \n    <h2>1. Command Line Based Operating Systems</h2>\n    <p>A Command Line Interface (CLI) operating system requires users to type text commands to perform tasks. It does not have a mouse or graphical icons.</p>\n    \n    <h3>1.1 DOS (Disk Operating System)</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>DOS was one of the earliest operating systems used on personal computers.</li>\n      <li>It was developed by Microsoft in the 1980s.</li>\n      <li>DOS operates using commands typed in a black screen (Command Prompt).</li>\n      <li>No graphical interface, only text commands.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h4>Examples of DOS Commands</h4>\n    <pre>\n      dir – Displays files and folders in the current directory.\n      C:\\> dir\n  \n      cd – Changes the current directory.\n      C:\\> cd Documents\n  \n      copy – Copies files from one location to another.\n      C:\\> copy file1.txt D:\\\n  \n      del – Deletes a file.\n      C:\\> del file1.txt\n    </pre>\n    <p><strong>? Use Case:</strong> In the early days, users had to type commands to open files, delete files, or move between folders.</p>\n  \n    <h3>1.2 UNIX</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>UNIX is a powerful, multi-user operating system mainly used in servers and mainframe computers.</li>\n      <li>Developed in 1969 at AT&T Bell Labs.</li>\n      <li>Commands are typed in a Terminal (similar to DOS).</li>\n      <li>Used in universities, research centers, and big organizations.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h4>Examples of UNIX Commands</h4>\n    <pre>\n      ls – Lists files in a directory.\n      $ ls\n  \n      pwd – Shows the current working directory.\n      $ pwd\n  \n      mkdir – Creates a new directory.\n      $ mkdir myfolder\n  \n      rm – Deletes a file.\n      $ rm file.txt\n    </pre>\n    <p><strong>? Use Case:</strong> UNIX is still widely used for web servers and databases because it is secure and stable.</p>\n  \n    <h2>2. GUI Based Operating Systems</h2>\n    <p>A Graphical User Interface (GUI) OS allows users to interact using icons, windows, and a mouse instead of typing commands.</p>\n  \n    <h3>2.1 Windows</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Developed by Microsoft in 1985.</li>\n      <li>One of the most popular OS for personal computers.</li>\n      <li>Uses icons, start menu, taskbar, and file explorer.</li>\n      <li>Very easy to use compared to CLI-based OS like DOS or UNIX.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h4>Examples of GUI Features in Windows</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Opening a file – Double-click a file instead of using <code>open filename</code> command.</li>\n      <li>Copying files – Drag and drop files instead of typing <code>copy file1.txt D:\\</code>.</li>\n      <li>Installing software – Click \"Install\" instead of running manual commands.</li>\n      <li>Shutting down – Click \"Start → Shut Down\" instead of typing <code>shutdown -h</code>.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p><strong>? Use Case:</strong> Windows is widely used in homes, offices, and schools because it is user-friendly.</p>\n  \n    <h3>2.2 Linux</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Developed in 1991 by Linus Torvalds.</li>\n      <li>It is open-source, meaning it is free to use and modify.</li>\n      <li>Comes in different versions like Ubuntu, Fedora, Debian.</li>\n      <li>Supports both CLI and GUI.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h4>Examples of GUI Features in Linux</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>File Management – Click folders to open instead of using <code>ls</code> command.</li>\n      <li>Web Browsing – Use Firefox or Chrome instead of typing <code>wget</code> command.</li>\n      <li>Installing Software – Use \"Ubuntu Software Center\" instead of typing <code>sudo apt install</code>.</li>\n      <li>System Settings – Change volume, display, and network settings through a GUI menu.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p><strong>? Use Case:</strong> Linux is widely used by developers, servers, and cybersecurity experts.</p>\n  \n    <h2>Comparison Table: CLI vs GUI OS</h2>\n    <table border=\"1\">\n      <tr>\n        <th>Feature</th>\n        <th>Command Line (CLI) OS (DOS, UNIX)</th>\n        <th>GUI-Based OS (Windows, Linux)</th>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>User Interface</td>\n        <td>Text-based commands</td>\n        <td>Icons, windows, buttons</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Ease of Use</td>\n        <td>Difficult (commands must be memorized)</td>\n        <td>Easy (mouse and menus)</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Speed</td>\n        <td>Faster (low memory usage)</td>\n        <td>Slightly slower (uses more resources)</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Usage</td>\n        <td>Used by IT professionals & servers</td>\n        <td>Used by general users</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Examples</td>\n        <td>DOS, UNIX</td>\n        <td>Windows, Linux</td>\n      </tr>\n    </table>\n  \n    <h2>Conclusion</h2>\n    <p>CLI-based OS (DOS, UNIX) is fast but requires users to remember commands.</p>\n    <p>GUI-based OS (Windows, Linux) is easier to use with a graphical interface.</p>\n    <p>Windows is more user-friendly, while Linux is used for security and development.</p>\n    \n    <h3>Simple Analogy</h3>\n    <p>? Imagine you want to listen to music:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>CLI OS (DOS, UNIX):</strong> You type a command like <code>play music.mp3</code>.</li>\n      <li><strong>GUI OS (Windows, Linux):</strong> You simply double-click the file, and it plays.</li>\n    </ul>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is an Operating System (OS)?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"A hardware component\",\n        \"A type of software that manages hardware and software resources\",\n        \"A programming language\",\n        \"A database management system\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is NOT an example of an Operating System?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Windows\",\n        \"macOS\",\n        \"Microsoft Office\",\n        \"Linux\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"What is the core component of an Operating System?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Kernel\",\n        \"Desktop\",\n        \"Task Manager\",\n        \"File Explorer\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Which component of an OS is responsible for managing memory allocation?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Process Manager\",\n        \"Memory Manager\",\n        \"Device Manager\",\n        \"File System Manager\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Which OS operation ensures that multiple programs run without interfering with each other?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Security Management\",\n        \"Resource Management\",\n        \"File System Management\",\n        \"User Interface Management\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following OS types is best for real-time applications like medical devices?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Batch OS\",\n        \"Multi-Programmed OS\",\n        \"Time-Shared OS\",\n        \"Real-Time OS\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Which OS is primarily used for smartphones and tablets?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"DOS\",\n        \"macOS\",\n        \"Android\",\n        \"UNIX\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"What is the primary function of a Batch Operating System?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To allow multiple users to work simultaneously\",\n        \"To process a group of jobs automatically without user interaction\",\n        \"To provide real-time responses for critical tasks\",\n        \"To allow distributed computing over a network\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Which type of OS is designed to support multiple processors for improved performance?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Distributed OS\",\n        \"Multiprocessor OS\",\n        \"Batch OS\",\n        \"Time-Shared OS\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Which command in DOS is used to list all files in a directory?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ls\",\n        \"dir\",\n        \"pwd\",\n        \"cd\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"Which OS is known for its strong security and stability, commonly used in web servers?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Windows\",\n        \"macOS\",\n        \"Linux\",\n        \"DOS\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"Which GUI-based OS was developed by Microsoft?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Windows\",\n        \"Linux\",\n        \"UNIX\",\n        \"Android\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Which CLI-based OS was one of the earliest used in personal computers?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Windows\",\n        \"DOS\",\n        \"macOS\",\n        \"iOS\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Which Linux command is used to display the current directory?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"dir\",\n        \"pwd\",\n        \"cd\",\n        \"ls\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Which OS is commonly used in mobile devices manufactured by Apple?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Android\",\n        \"Windows\",\n        \"iOS\",\n        \"Linux\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"A _______ OS requires users to type text commands to perform tasks.\",\n      \"options\": [\"GUI-based\", \"Command Line Based\", \"Cloud-based\", \"Real-time\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"A Command Line Interface (CLI) OS does not have a _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"keyboard\", \"mouse\", \"command prompt\", \"terminal\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"DOS was developed by Microsoft in the _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"1970s\", \"1980s\", \"1990s\", \"2000s\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"In DOS, the command used to display files and folders is _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"cd\", \"ls\", \"dir\", \"pwd\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"The UNIX command used to list files in a directory is _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"ls\", \"dir\", \"cd\", \"pwd\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"A GUI-based OS allows users to interact using _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"text commands\", \"code only\", \"icons and windows\", \"scripts\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"The first version of Windows was released in _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"1980\", \"1985\", \"1990\", \"1995\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Windows OS is known for its _______ interface.\",\n      \"options\": [\"command-line\", \"text-based\", \"graphical\", \"complex\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Linux was developed by _______ in 1991.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Bill Gates\", \"Linus Torvalds\", \"Steve Jobs\", \"Dennis Ritchie\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Linux supports both _______ and GUI-based interaction.\",\n      \"options\": [\"only CLI\", \"only GUI\", \"CLI and GUI\", \"none\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that a Command Line Interface (CLI) OS requires users to type text commands to perform tasks.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that CLI-based operating systems support graphical icons and mouse interaction.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that DOS was one of the earliest operating systems used on personal computers.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that DOS was developed by Apple in the 1990s.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that in DOS, the \'dir\' command is used to display files and folders in the current directory.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that UNIX was developed in the early 2000s.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that UNIX was developed at AT&T Bell Labs in 1969.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that UNIX is mainly used in personal home computers.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the \'ls\' command in UNIX is used to list files in a directory.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the \'rm\' command in UNIX is used to create a new directory.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that GUI-based operating systems allow users to interact with the system using icons, windows, and a mouse.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Windows was developed in 1975.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that Windows was developed by Microsoft in 1985.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Windows uses only command-line interaction without a graphical interface.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that Linux was developed by Linus Torvalds in 1991.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Linux is a closed-source operating system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that Linux is open-source, meaning it is free to use and modify.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Linux does not support any graphical user interface.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that Linux supports both CLI and GUI interfaces.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the main advantage of GUI-based OS is that they are difficult to use.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that GUI-based OS is easier to use compared to CLI-based OS.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that CLI-based OS is slower than GUI-based OS.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that CLI-based OS consumes less memory and is faster than GUI-based OS.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Windows and Linux are examples of CLI-based operating systems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that Windows and Linux are examples of GUI-based operating systems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that UNIX and DOS are examples of GUI-based operating systems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that UNIX and DOS are examples of CLI-based operating systems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Linux does not have different versions.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that Linux comes in different versions like Ubuntu, Fedora, and Debian.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the \'mkdir\' command is used to delete files in UNIX.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the \'mkdir\' command is used to create directories in UNIX.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Windows is an open-source operating system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that Windows is a proprietary operating system developed by Microsoft.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Linux is mainly used for gaming and multimedia only.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that Linux is widely used by developers, servers, and cybersecurity experts.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that CLI-based OS does not require users to remember commands.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that CLI-based OS requires users to remember and type commands manually.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that GUI-based OS lacks any security features.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that GUI-based OS includes security features like user authentication and encryption.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that UNIX is an example of a GUI-based OS.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that UNIX is a CLI-based OS used mainly in servers.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Windows is the only GUI-based OS available.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that both Windows and Linux provide a graphical user interface.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that CLI-based OS is commonly used in personal computers today.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that GUI-based OS is more common in personal computers.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that UNIX was originally designed for home users.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that UNIX was developed for multi-user environments like servers.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Linux does not support software development.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that Linux is widely used for software development and security testing.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the \'copy\' command in DOS is used to delete files.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  ',13,9),(29,'2.1-Different Services of Operating System','<div>\n    <h1>2.1 Different Services of Operating System</h1>\n    <p>An Operating System (OS) is a software that manages the hardware and software of a computer. It acts as a bridge between the user and the computer. The OS provides various services to ensure smooth operation and efficient resource management.</p>\n    <p>Let’s explore the main services of an operating system with simple explanations and examples.</p>\n\n    <h2>1. Process Management</h2>\n    <p>The OS manages processes (running programs) by allocating CPU time and resources. It ensures multiple programs can run efficiently without interfering with each other.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> When you open a web browser and play a song in a music player at the same time, the OS ensures both applications run smoothly without crashing. The OS uses multitasking, which allows multiple applications to run at the same time.</p>\n\n    <h2>2. Memory Management</h2>\n    <p>The OS manages RAM (Random Access Memory) and ensures that each program gets enough memory to run without interfering with others.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Suppose you open MS Word, Google Chrome, and VLC Media Player at the same time. The OS allocates memory to each program so they work without slowing down the system. If there is not enough RAM, the OS uses virtual memory (part of the hard disk) to prevent crashes.</p>\n\n    <h2>3. File Management</h2>\n    <p>The OS organizes and manages files stored on the computer. It provides operations like creating, saving, deleting, renaming, and moving files.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> When you save a Word document, the OS stores it in a specific location (e.g., Documents folder). If you want to copy a file from a USB drive to your computer, the OS handles the process.</p>\n\n    <h2>4. Device Management</h2>\n    <p>The OS manages hardware devices like printers, keyboards, mice, and USB drives. It ensures smooth communication between software and hardware.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> When you connect a printer, the OS detects it and installs the necessary drivers. When you insert a USB drive, the OS recognizes it and allows you to access the files.</p>\n\n    <h2>5. Security and Protection</h2>\n    <p>The OS provides security features to protect data and prevent unauthorized access.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n        <li>User Authentication: You need to enter a password or PIN to log into Windows.</li>\n        <li>Antivirus Support: The OS allows security software to detect and remove viruses.</li>\n        <li>File Permissions: You can restrict access to files so only certain users can open them.</li>\n    </ul>\n\n    <h2>6. User Interface</h2>\n    <p>The OS provides a Graphical User Interface (GUI) or Command Line Interface (CLI) to interact with the system.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n        <li>GUI (Graphical Interface): Windows OS allows you to use a mouse and icons to navigate.</li>\n        <li>CLI (Command Line Interface): In Linux, you can type commands like <code>mkdir NewFolder</code> to create a folder.</li>\n    </ul>\n\n    <h2>7. Networking Services</h2>\n    <p>The OS allows computers to connect to the internet and communicate with other devices.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n        <li>When you connect to Wi-Fi, the OS manages the connection.</li>\n        <li>When you send an email, the OS helps transfer data through the network.</li>\n    </ul>\n\n    <h2>8. Error Detection and Handling</h2>\n    <p>The OS continuously monitors the system for errors and fixes them to prevent crashes.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n        <li>If an application stops responding, the OS shows a message like \"Not Responding\" and allows you to force close it.</li>\n        <li>If there is a hard disk failure, the OS may display an alert and recommend solutions.</li>\n    </ul>\n\n    <h2>Conclusion</h2>\n    <p>The Operating System is like a manager that controls everything in a computer. It ensures smooth operation by managing processes, memory, files, devices, security, user interfaces, networking, and errors. Without an OS, using a computer would be very difficult.</p>\n</div>','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is the primary function of an Operating System?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To run applications only\",\n        \"To manage hardware and software resources\",\n        \"To act as a storage device\",\n        \"To connect computers in a network\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Which OS service is responsible for managing running programs?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Memory Management\",\n        \"Process Management\",\n        \"Device Management\",\n        \"File Management\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following best describes memory management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Managing running programs\",\n        \"Managing computer storage devices\",\n        \"Managing RAM and allocation of memory to processes\",\n        \"Managing user authentication\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"What does the file management service of an OS do?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Controls network connections\",\n        \"Manages files by creating, saving, renaming, and deleting them\",\n        \"Allocates memory to different programs\",\n        \"Provides security features like passwords\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Which OS service allows communication between software and hardware devices?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"File Management\",\n        \"Process Management\",\n        \"Device Management\",\n        \"User Interface\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an example of security and protection service in an OS?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"User authentication using passwords\",\n        \"Opening a web browser\",\n        \"Connecting to a Wi-Fi network\",\n        \"Displaying an error message\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"What is the function of the networking service in an OS?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To provide security against malware\",\n        \"To manage connections between computers and networks\",\n        \"To manage memory allocation\",\n        \"To manage running processes\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Which OS service continuously monitors the system for errors?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Memory Management\",\n        \"Process Management\",\n        \"Error Detection and Handling\",\n        \"File Management\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"What is an example of an error detection service provided by an OS?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Saving a document in a folder\",\n        \"Displaying \'Not Responding\' for a frozen application\",\n        \"Managing CPU processes\",\n        \"Allocating memory to a running application\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an example of process management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Typing a command in the terminal\",\n        \"Running multiple applications simultaneously without crashes\",\n        \"Copying a file from one folder to another\",\n        \"Changing volume settings on the computer\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"The OS acts as a bridge between the user and the _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Internet\", \"Hardware\", \"Software\", \"Applications\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"The OS ensures multiple programs can run efficiently through _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Single-tasking\", \"Multitasking\", \"Manual Switching\", \"Slow Processing\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"When you open multiple applications, the OS manages _______ allocation.\",\n      \"options\": [\"CPU\", \"RAM\", \"Cache\", \"ROM\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"The OS uses _______ memory when there is not enough RAM available.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Virtual\", \"Cache\", \"Flash\", \"Primary\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"The service that organizes and manages files stored on the computer is called _______ management.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Process\", \"Memory\", \"File\", \"Device\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"When you connect a printer, the OS installs necessary _______ to communicate with it.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Applications\", \"Drivers\", \"Extensions\", \"Documents\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"A user needs to enter a password to log into Windows. This is an example of _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Device Management\", \"Process Scheduling\", \"User Authentication\", \"Error Detection\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"The OS allows users to interact with the system using either a GUI or _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"CLI\", \"URL\", \"API\", \"WIFI\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"The OS ensures that computers can connect to the internet using _______ services.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Security\", \"Networking\", \"Process\", \"Storage\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"If an application stops responding, the OS allows users to _______ it.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Delete\", \"Force Close\", \"Uninstall\", \"Rename\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"Managing hardware devices like keyboards and printers is a function of _______ management.\",\n      \"options\": [\"File\", \"Device\", \"Process\", \"Security\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"The OS continuously monitors the system for errors and helps in _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"User Authentication\", \"Error Detection and Handling\", \"Network Configuration\", \"Process Scheduling\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"An OS that allows multiple applications to run at the same time is known as a _______ system.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Single-tasking\", \"Multi-programming\", \"Manual\", \"Static\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"A GUI-based OS allows users to interact with the system using _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Text Commands\", \"Icons and Menus\", \"Scripts\", \"Terminal Only\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"The OS schedules processes based on their priority in _______ management.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Process\", \"Memory\", \"File\", \"Security\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that an operating system acts as a bridge between the user and the computer.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that process management is responsible for managing the hardware devices connected to a computer.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the OS allocates CPU time and resources to multiple programs running simultaneously.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the OS does not manage memory allocation for running applications.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that if there is not enough RAM, the OS uses virtual memory to prevent crashes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that file management is unrelated to the organization of stored data in a computer.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that file management allows users to create, save, rename, and delete files.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that device management only applies to software and has no connection with hardware devices.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the OS detects and installs necessary drivers when a new device is connected.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the OS does not provide any security features to protect user data.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the OS provides user authentication, such as passwords and PINs, for security.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that antivirus software cannot work with the OS to remove malicious files.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that file permissions allow users to restrict access to specific files.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that all operating systems only use a graphical user interface (GUI).\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that some operating systems offer both GUI and Command Line Interface (CLI).\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that networking services in an OS are only used for connecting USB devices.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the OS manages internet connections and data transfer over networks.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that an operating system does not detect and handle system errors.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the OS can detect hardware failures and display error messages.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that an OS is not necessary for running modern computers.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that an OS is responsible for managing both software and hardware.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the OS does not allow multiple applications to run at the same time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that multitasking allows multiple applications to run efficiently.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the OS does not use RAM for storing temporary data while programs run.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that virtual memory helps when RAM is full by using a portion of the hard disk.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that files stored on a computer do not need management by the OS.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that an OS helps users organize files into folders and directories.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the OS has no role in managing printers or external devices.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that device drivers help the OS communicate with external devices.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that passwords and authentication methods are not part of OS security.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the OS provides firewalls and antivirus support to enhance security.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that a computer can function efficiently without an operating system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the OS provides networking services to connect computers to the internet.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the OS does not help detect or handle software errors.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that if a program stops responding, the OS can terminate it.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the OS does not help users interact with the system through GUI or CLI.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that Windows, Linux, and macOS provide GUI interfaces for users.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the OS does not manage file storage on external drives like USBs.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that networking services allow data sharing between multiple computers.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the OS does not handle Wi-Fi and Bluetooth connections.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that file permissions help control who can access or modify a file.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that an OS does not allocate resources to different tasks.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that process management ensures each program gets CPU time efficiently.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that security features in an OS are unnecessary for modern computing.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that OS security prevents unauthorized access and protects sensitive data.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  ',13,10),(30,'2.2-System Calls – Concept, Types of System Calls','<div>\n    <h1>2.2 System Calls – Concept, Types of System Calls</h1>\n    <h2>What is a System Call?</h2>\n    <p>A system call is a way for a program to request a service from the operating system. Think of it as a bridge between the user and the operating system.</p>\n    <p>Imagine you are in a restaurant. You (the user) want food, but you cannot directly enter the kitchen to cook. Instead, you call a waiter (system call) who takes your request to the kitchen (operating system). The kitchen prepares the food and gives it to the waiter, who delivers it back to you.</p>\n    <p>Similarly, when a program needs to perform a task (like reading a file or printing something), it cannot do it directly. It asks the operating system using a system call.</p>\n    \n    <h2>Why Are System Calls Important?</h2>\n    <ul>\n      <li>They allow user programs to interact with hardware (files, memory, network, etc.).</li>\n      <li>They ensure security by controlling access to system resources.</li>\n      <li>They simplify programming since developers don’t need to write code for low-level hardware operations.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h2>Types of System Calls</h2>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Process Control System Calls</li>\n      <li>File Management System Calls</li>\n      <li>Device Management System Calls</li>\n      <li>Information Maintenance System Calls</li>\n      <li>Communication System Calls</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>1. Process Control System Calls</h3>\n    <p>A process is any program that is running on a computer. These system calls help to start, stop, or manage a process.</p>\n    <p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><code>fork()</code> – Creates a new process (like making a photocopy of a document).</li>\n      <li><code>exec()</code> – Runs a new program (like switching from a music app to a video app).</li>\n      <li><code>exit()</code> – Stops a process (like closing an app on your phone).</li>\n      <li><code>wait()</code> – Makes a process wait for another to finish (like waiting for a friend before leaving together).</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>2. File Management System Calls</h3>\n    <p>Computers store data in files. These system calls help in creating, opening, reading, writing, and closing files.</p>\n    <p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><code>open()</code> – Opens a file (like opening a book).</li>\n      <li><code>read()</code> – Reads data from a file (like reading a page).</li>\n      <li><code>write()</code> – Writes data to a file (like writing in a notebook).</li>\n      <li><code>close()</code> – Closes a file (like closing a book after reading).</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>3. Device Management System Calls</h3>\n    <p>Computers use various devices like printers, keyboards, and USB drives. These system calls help in managing hardware devices.</p>\n    <p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><code>ioctl()</code> – Controls a device (like adjusting volume on speakers).</li>\n      <li><code>read()</code> and <code>write()</code> – Transfer data to/from a device (like sending a document to a printer).</li>\n      <li><code>close()</code> – Releases a device (like unplugging a USB drive safely).</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>4. Information Maintenance System Calls</h3>\n    <p>These system calls provide system-related information such as date, time, memory usage, and process details.</p>\n    <p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><code>getpid()</code> – Gets the process ID (like finding your student ID).</li>\n      <li><code>alarm()</code> – Sets a timer (like setting an alarm on your phone).</li>\n      <li><code>gettimeofday()</code> – Gets the current date and time (like checking the time on your phone).</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>5. Communication System Calls</h3>\n    <p>These system calls help programs exchange data with each other or over a network.</p>\n    <p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><code>pipe()</code> – Allows two processes to communicate (like passing a note in class).</li>\n      <li><code>send()</code> and <code>recv()</code> – Send and receive messages (like sending a WhatsApp message).</li>\n      <li><code>connect()</code> – Connects to a server (like opening a website).</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h2>Conclusion</h2>\n    <p>System calls are essential for a computer to function. They allow programs to interact with the operating system securely and efficiently. Without system calls, even simple tasks like opening a file, printing a document, or browsing the internet wouldn’t be possible.</p>\n  \n    <h2>Quick Summary Table:</h2>\n    <table border=\"1\">\n      <tr>\n        <th>Type of System Call</th>\n        <th>Purpose</th>\n        <th>Examples</th>\n        <th>Real-Life Example</th>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Process Control</td>\n        <td>Start, stop, or manage a process</td>\n        <td>fork(), exec(), exit()</td>\n        <td>Opening and closing apps</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>File Management</td>\n        <td>Create, read, write, delete files</td>\n        <td>open(), read(), write()</td>\n        <td>Opening a document</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Device Management</td>\n        <td>Control hardware devices</td>\n        <td>ioctl(), read(), write()</td>\n        <td>Printing a document</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Information Maintenance</td>\n        <td>Get system-related info</td>\n        <td>getpid(), alarm(), gettimeofday()</td>\n        <td>Checking battery percentage</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Communication</td>\n        <td>Exchange data between processes or over a network</td>\n        <td>pipe(), send(), recv()</td>\n        <td>Sending a WhatsApp message</td>\n      </tr>\n    </table>\n    \n    <p>By understanding system calls, you now have a better idea of how computers work behind the scenes! ?</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is a system call?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"A type of hardware device\",\n        \"A request from a program to the operating system\",\n        \"A type of programming language\",\n        \"A type of computer virus\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Which system call is used to create a new process?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"exec()\",\n        \"fork()\",\n        \"exit()\",\n        \"wait()\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"What does the exec() system call do?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Terminates a process\",\n        \"Creates a new process\",\n        \"Runs a new program\",\n        \"Waits for a process to finish\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Which system call is used to read data from a file?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"open()\",\n        \"write()\",\n        \"read()\",\n        \"close()\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"What is the purpose of the close() system call?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To delete a file\",\n        \"To close an open file or device\",\n        \"To save a file\",\n        \"To shut down the computer\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which system call is used to allocate CPU time to processes?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"wait()\",\n        \"exec()\",\n        \"fork()\",\n        \"sched_yield()\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"What is the function of the wait() system call?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To start a new process\",\n        \"To make a process wait until another process finishes\",\n        \"To terminate a process\",\n        \"To retrieve system information\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Which system call is used to send data between processes?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"send()\",\n        \"recv()\",\n        \"pipe()\",\n        \"connect()\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"What does the getpid() system call do?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Gets the parent process ID\",\n        \"Retrieves system uptime\",\n        \"Gets the process ID of the current process\",\n        \"Checks if a process is active\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Which system call is used to retrieve the current time and date?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"gettimeofday()\",\n        \"time()\",\n        \"clock()\",\n        \"sys_time()\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"A system call is a way for a program to request a ________ from the operating system.\",\n      \"options\": [\"service\", \"command\", \"process\", \"file\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"System calls act as a ________ between the user and the operating system.\",\n      \"options\": [\"barrier\", \"bridge\", \"block\", \"wall\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ system call is used to create a new process.\",\n      \"options\": [\"exec()\", \"fork()\", \"exit()\", \"wait()\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"The exec() system call is used to ________ a new program.\",\n      \"options\": [\"stop\", \"run\", \"delete\", \"pause\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"The exit() system call is used to ________ a process.\",\n      \"options\": [\"start\", \"pause\", \"stop\", \"restart\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ system call makes a process wait for another to finish.\",\n      \"options\": [\"exec()\", \"fork()\", \"exit()\", \"wait()\"],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"File management system calls help in ________ files.\",\n      \"options\": [\"creating\", \"reading\", \"writing\", \"all of the above\"],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"The open() system call is used to ________ a file.\",\n      \"options\": [\"create\", \"close\", \"open\", \"delete\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"The read() system call is used to ________ data from a file.\",\n      \"options\": [\"write\", \"read\", \"delete\", \"rename\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"The write() system call is used to ________ data to a file.\",\n      \"options\": [\"read\", \"write\", \"delete\", \"copy\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"Device management system calls help in controlling ________ devices.\",\n      \"options\": [\"software\", \"hardware\", \"applications\", \"websites\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"The ioctl() system call is used to ________ a device.\",\n      \"options\": [\"control\", \"delete\", \"pause\", \"open\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"The getpid() system call is used to get the ________ of a process.\",\n      \"options\": [\"size\", \"ID\", \"priority\", \"status\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"The alarm() system call is used to set a ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"process\", \"file\", \"timer\", \"device\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Communication system calls help programs exchange ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"files\", \"commands\", \"data\", \"users\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"The send() system call is used to ________ messages.\",\n      \"options\": [\"receive\", \"send\", \"delete\", \"store\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"The recv() system call is used to ________ messages.\",\n      \"options\": [\"send\", \"receive\", \"delete\", \"modify\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"The connect() system call is used to establish a ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"file\", \"network connection\", \"process\", \"device\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"System calls allow programs to interact with the ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"user\", \"operating system\", \"database\", \"browser\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"Without system calls, it would be difficult for programs to perform ________ operations.\",\n      \"options\": [\"low-level\", \"high-level\", \"basic\", \"logical\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"A system call is a way for a program to request a service from the operating system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"System calls allow user programs to interact directly with hardware without involving the operating system.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"The fork() system call is used to create a new process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"The exec() system call is used to terminate a process.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"System calls ensure security by controlling access to system resources.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"The exit() system call is used to terminate a process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"The wait() system call allows one process to wait until another process finishes execution.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"System calls make programming more difficult as developers must handle hardware operations manually.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"The open() system call is used to open a file.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"The read() system call is used to delete a file.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"The write() system call is used to write data to a file.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"The close() system call is used to terminate a process.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Device management system calls help in managing hardware devices like printers and USB drives.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"The ioctl() system call is used to control a device.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"The getpid() system call is used to get the process ID of the currently running process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"The gettimeofday() system call retrieves the current date and time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"The alarm() system call is used to shut down the operating system.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Communication system calls help programs exchange data over a network.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"The send() and recv() system calls are used for inter-process communication.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"The pipe() system call allows two processes to communicate by creating a communication channel.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"System calls are necessary for applications to interact with the operating system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"Without system calls, user programs would be able to directly access hardware resources.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"System calls are categorized into four main types.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"The system calls related to file management allow users to create, read, write, and close files.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"The close() system call is responsible for opening a file.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"The process control system calls help in managing processes by creating and terminating them.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"The connect() system call is used to establish a connection between a client and a server.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"Information maintenance system calls provide details such as memory usage and process status.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"System calls operate at the user level without involving the kernel.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"System calls improve security by restricting direct hardware access.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"The getpid() system call returns the process ID of another process chosen randomly.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"A user program can directly perform input/output operations without using system calls.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"System calls work in user mode rather than kernel mode.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"File management system calls include open(), read(), write(), and close().\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"The fork() system call duplicates a process, creating a child process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"The exit() system call is used to send a message over a network.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"System calls act as an interface between the user program and the operating system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"The wait() system call helps synchronize parent and child processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"Communication system calls do not include the send() and recv() functions.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"System calls allow user programs to execute privileged operations indirectly.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  ',13,10),(31,'2.3-OS Components','<div>\n    <h1>2.3 OS Components</h1>\n    <p>An Operating System (OS) is software that manages computer hardware and software resources. It provides services for computer programs and ensures that the system runs smoothly. The OS has several important components that work together to manage different aspects of the computer. Let’s explore them one by one in simple language with examples.</p>\n    \n    <h2>1. Process Management</h2>\n    <p>A process is a running program. The OS manages these processes to ensure they execute efficiently and without interfering with each other.</p>\n    <h3>Responsibilities:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Creating and deleting processes.</li>\n      <li>Allocating CPU time to processes.</li>\n      <li>Managing multitasking (running multiple processes at once).</li>\n      <li>Preventing deadlocks (where processes get stuck waiting for each other).</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Example:</h3>\n    <p>Imagine you are using a web browser, playing music, and downloading a file at the same time. The OS ensures that each task gets enough CPU time so that everything works smoothly without crashing.</p>\n    \n    <h2>2. Main Memory Management</h2>\n    <p>Main memory (RAM) is where data and programs are stored temporarily while they are being used. The OS manages this memory efficiently to avoid wastage and ensure that each program gets enough space to run properly.</p>\n    <h3>Responsibilities:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Allocating and deallocating memory.</li>\n      <li>Keeping track of which part of memory is free or occupied.</li>\n      <li>Managing virtual memory (using hard disk space as extra memory when RAM is full).</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Example:</h3>\n    <p>When you open multiple applications, such as a web browser and a game, the OS ensures that each program gets enough memory to function properly. If RAM is full, it temporarily moves some data to the hard drive (virtual memory) to free up space.</p>\n    \n    <h2>3. File Management</h2>\n    <p>A file is a collection of data stored on a computer. The OS manages all files on a system, ensuring they are stored, retrieved, and organized properly.</p>\n    <h3>Responsibilities:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Creating, deleting, reading, and writing files.</li>\n      <li>Managing file storage locations (folders/directories).</li>\n      <li>Controlling access permissions (who can read or edit a file).</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Example:</h3>\n    <p>When you save a Word document, the OS decides where to store it on the hard drive and keeps track of its location so you can find it later.</p>\n    \n    <h2>4. I/O System Management</h2>\n    <p>The Input/Output (I/O) system manages communication between the computer and external devices such as keyboards, mice, printers, and USB drives.</p>\n    <h3>Responsibilities:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Detecting and connecting input/output devices.</li>\n      <li>Managing data transfer between the OS and devices.</li>\n      <li>Handling device drivers (software that allows the OS to communicate with hardware).</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Example:</h3>\n    <p>When you plug in a USB drive, the OS detects it, assigns it a drive letter (e.g., \"D:\"), and allows you to access the files stored on it.</p>\n    \n    <h2>5. Secondary Storage Management</h2>\n    <p>Secondary storage refers to hard drives, SSDs, CDs, and external drives, where data is stored permanently (unlike RAM, which is temporary).</p>\n    <h3>Responsibilities:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Organizing data in storage devices.</li>\n      <li>Ensuring efficient file retrieval and storage.</li>\n      <li>Managing free space and disk partitions.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Example:</h3>\n    <p>When you install a new software application, the OS finds space on your hard drive and stores the necessary files in an organized way so the software can function correctly.</p>\n    \n    <h2>Conclusion</h2>\n    <p>These OS components work together to ensure that the computer runs smoothly, processes are managed efficiently, and users can store and retrieve files without issues. Without an OS, using a computer would be extremely difficult since we would have to manually manage hardware and software operations.</p>\n    <p>Understanding these components helps us appreciate how operating systems make our computing experience seamless and efficient.</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is the primary function of Process Management in an OS?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Managing user logins\",\n        \"Handling CPU scheduling and process execution\",\n        \"Managing file storage\",\n        \"Controlling hardware devices\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Which component of the OS is responsible for managing RAM?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Process Management\",\n        \"File Management\",\n        \"Main Memory Management\",\n        \"I/O System Management\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"What is the purpose of virtual memory in Main Memory Management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To store permanent files\",\n        \"To extend RAM using secondary storage\",\n        \"To increase CPU speed\",\n        \"To manage user accounts\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a responsibility of File Management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Creating, deleting, reading, and writing files\",\n        \"Managing CPU scheduling\",\n        \"Handling memory allocation\",\n        \"Managing user authentication\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"What does I/O System Management handle?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Managing hardware devices and drivers\",\n        \"Scheduling processes\",\n        \"Managing network connections\",\n        \"Handling login credentials\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is considered Secondary Storage?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"RAM\",\n        \"Cache Memory\",\n        \"Hard Drive\",\n        \"Registers\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"What role does Secondary Storage Management play in an OS?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Managing file storage and retrieval\",\n        \"Handling CPU scheduling\",\n        \"Allocating memory to running processes\",\n        \"Managing network communication\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"What is the purpose of CPU scheduling in Process Management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To determine which process gets CPU time\",\n        \"To delete unused files\",\n        \"To allocate hard disk space\",\n        \"To establish network connections\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Which OS component ensures smooth execution of multiple processes?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"File Management\",\n        \"Process Management\",\n        \"I/O System Management\",\n        \"Secondary Storage Management\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"What happens when RAM is full?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"The OS shuts down\",\n        \"The OS uses virtual memory to store temporary data\",\n        \"The system stops all processes\",\n        \"Files are deleted automatically\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"A process is a ________ program.\",\n      \"options\": [\"saved\", \"running\", \"deleted\", \"corrupted\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"The OS is responsible for ________ and deleting processes.\",\n      \"options\": [\"creating\", \"hiding\", \"renaming\", \"moving\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Process management ensures that processes execute efficiently and do not ________ with each other.\",\n      \"options\": [\"interrupt\", \"communicate\", \"interfere\", \"merge\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"The OS allocates ________ time to processes for execution.\",\n      \"options\": [\"CPU\", \"RAM\", \"Disk\", \"Cache\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Multitasking allows multiple ________ to run simultaneously.\",\n      \"options\": [\"files\", \"processes\", \"commands\", \"users\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Deadlocks occur when processes get stuck ________ for each other.\",\n      \"options\": [\"executing\", \"waiting\", \"loading\", \"deleting\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Main memory is also known as ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Cache\", \"Hard Disk\", \"RAM\", \"ROM\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"The OS uses ________ memory when RAM is full.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Virtual\", \"Primary\", \"Cloud\", \"Flash\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"File management is responsible for storing, retrieving, and ________ files.\",\n      \"options\": [\"deleting\", \"executing\", \"processing\", \"downloading\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"A file is a collection of ________ stored on a computer.\",\n      \"options\": [\"programs\", \"data\", \"applications\", \"commands\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"The OS manages files and stores them in ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"folders\", \"programs\", \"documents\", \"databases\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"I/O system management handles communication between the OS and ________ devices.\",\n      \"options\": [\"internal\", \"output\", \"hardware\", \"external\"],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Device drivers help the OS communicate with ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"software\", \"applications\", \"hardware\", \"users\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Secondary storage includes hard drives, SSDs, and ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"USBs\", \"RAM\", \"CPUs\", \"BIOS\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"The OS is responsible for organizing data in ________ storage.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Primary\", \"Secondary\", \"Temporary\", \"Volatile\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"When a file is saved, the OS determines its ________ on the disk.\",\n      \"options\": [\"format\", \"location\", \"permission\", \"speed\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"Without an OS, managing hardware and software would be extremely ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"easy\", \"simple\", \"difficult\", \"automatic\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Process management ensures that programs do not ________ system resources.\",\n      \"options\": [\"overuse\", \"waste\", \"interfere\", \"modify\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"The OS prevents ________ access to files through file permissions.\",\n      \"options\": [\"restricted\", \"authorized\", \"unauthorized\", \"limited\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"The OS assigns each running process a unique ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"memory\", \"address\", \"ID\", \"thread\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that an Operating System manages both hardware and software resources.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that an Operating System only manages hardware and has no role in software management.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Process management is responsible for creating and deleting processes in an OS.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that process management has no role in allocating CPU time to running programs.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"A deadlock occurs when processes get stuck waiting for each other indefinitely.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that process management is only responsible for handling files.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Main memory management ensures that programs get enough memory to run efficiently.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that main memory (RAM) stores data permanently.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Virtual memory is used when RAM is full, allowing the system to use part of the hard disk as additional memory.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that virtual memory completely replaces the need for RAM.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"File management in an OS is responsible for storing, retrieving, and organizing files.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that file management does not control file access permissions.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"A file is a collection of data stored on a computer.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the OS does not manage file storage locations.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"I/O system management handles communication between the computer and external devices.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the I/O system does not include handling device drivers.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"A device driver is software that allows an OS to communicate with a hardware device.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that an OS cannot detect new input/output devices like USB drives.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Secondary storage management is responsible for managing hard drives and external storage devices.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that secondary storage stores data temporarily like RAM.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"The OS ensures efficient file retrieval and storage in secondary storage.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the OS has no role in managing disk partitions.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"Process management ensures multitasking works efficiently.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that process management is not required for multitasking.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"The OS keeps track of which parts of memory are free or occupied.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that file management does not allow reading and writing files.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"The OS assigns a drive letter to a newly plugged-in USB device.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that I/O management does not include handling keyboards and mice.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"Secondary storage stores data permanently.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that RAM is a form of secondary storage.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"File permissions determine who can read, edit, or delete a file.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that secondary storage management does not handle external hard drives.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"The OS is responsible for preventing process deadlocks.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that an OS does not need to allocate memory to programs.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"The OS manages running programs using process management.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that secondary storage management deals with RAM allocation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"Virtual memory helps run large applications when RAM is full.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that virtual memory is stored in RAM.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"Device drivers are required for the OS to communicate with hardware devices.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that file management is only used for reading files and cannot create new ones.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"Process management ensures that multiple programs can run smoothly at the same time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that an OS does not control how data is stored on secondary storage devices.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"The OS ensures files are stored in an organized manner for easy retrieval.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that I/O system management does not manage printers.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"The OS plays a role in managing CPU scheduling for processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that file management does not include deleting files.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"The OS uses memory management to prevent memory wastage.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the OS cannot track which processes are currently running.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"File management ensures users can save and retrieve data efficiently.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that OS components do not work together to ensure a smooth computing experience.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  ',13,10),(32,'2.4-Use of Operating System Tools','<div>\n    <h1>2.4 Use of Operating System Tools</h1>\n    <p>The Operating System (OS) is like the manager of your computer. It helps control different things like users, security, devices, and performance. To make things easier, the OS provides built-in tools that help users manage their computers effectively.</p>\n    <p>In this topic, we will discuss five important OS tools:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>User Management</li>\n      <li>Security Policy</li>\n      <li>Device Management</li>\n      <li>Performance Monitor</li>\n      <li>Task Scheduler</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p>Each of these tools plays a key role in keeping the computer system running smoothly. Let\'s go through them one by one with simple explanations and examples.</p>\n  \n    <h2>1. User Management</h2>\n    <p>User Management is the process of creating, modifying, and deleting user accounts on a computer or network. This tool helps control who can access the system and what they can do.</p>\n    <h3>Why is User Management Important?</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Prevents unauthorized access to the system.</li>\n      <li>Helps in assigning different permissions to different users.</li>\n      <li>Allows multiple users to use the same computer with their own settings.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Examples of User Management:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>In Windows OS, you can go to Control Panel → User Accounts to manage users.</li>\n      <li>In Linux, you can use commands like:</li>\n      <ul>\n        <li><code>adduser username</code> → To create a new user.</li>\n        <li><code>deluser username</code> → To remove a user.</li>\n      </ul>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Real-Life Example:</h3>\n    <p>Imagine a school computer lab. The teacher has an admin account that can install software, but students have limited accounts that cannot change system settings. This ensures security and control over the system.</p>\n  \n    <h2>2. Security Policy</h2>\n    <p>A Security Policy in an OS defines rules and settings that protect the computer from threats like hacking, viruses, and unauthorized access.</p>\n    <h3>Why is Security Policy Important?</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Protects sensitive data from hackers and malware.</li>\n      <li>Prevents unauthorized users from accessing the system.</li>\n      <li>Helps in password management and account security.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Examples of Security Policy:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Password Policies:</li>\n      <ul>\n        <li>Enforcing strong passwords (at least 8 characters, including symbols).</li>\n        <li>Locking accounts after multiple wrong password attempts.</li>\n      </ul>\n      <li>Firewall Settings: Blocks harmful connections from the internet.</li>\n      <li>Antivirus & Windows Defender: Scans the system for viruses and malware.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Real-Life Example:</h3>\n    <p>When you try to log in to your email, and after 3 wrong attempts, your account gets locked for security reasons. This is an example of a security policy in action.</p>\n  \n    <h2>3. Device Management</h2>\n    <p>Device Management refers to the way the OS handles hardware devices like printers, keyboards, and USB drives.</p>\n    <h3>Why is Device Management Important?</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Helps in installing drivers so that devices work properly.</li>\n      <li>Ensures that devices communicate correctly with the OS.</li>\n      <li>Allows enabling or disabling devices when needed.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Examples of Device Management:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>In Windows, you can go to Device Manager (devmgmt.msc) to see all connected devices.</li>\n      <li>In Linux, commands like <code>lsusb</code> and <code>lspci</code> list connected devices.</li>\n      <li>If a printer is not working, you can update its driver through Device Manager.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Real-Life Example:</h3>\n    <p>When you connect a new printer to your computer, the OS automatically installs a driver so that you can print documents. If there’s an issue, you might need to update or reinstall the driver using Device Manager.</p>\n  \n    <h2>4. Performance Monitor</h2>\n    <p>A Performance Monitor is a tool that helps check how well your computer is working. It shows details about CPU usage, memory usage, disk activity, and network activity.</p>\n    <h3>Why is Performance Monitor Important?</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Helps in finding slow or malfunctioning applications.</li>\n      <li>Identifies high CPU or memory usage that may slow down the system.</li>\n      <li>Monitors network activity to detect potential security issues.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Examples of Performance Monitor:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Windows Task Manager (Ctrl + Shift + Esc): Shows CPU, RAM, and Disk usage in real-time.</li>\n      <li>Linux: Using <code>top</code> or <code>htop</code> commands: Displays CPU and memory usage in real-time.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Real-Life Example:</h3>\n    <p>If your laptop is running slow, you can open Task Manager and see if a particular program is using too much CPU or RAM. You can then close that program to speed up your system.</p>\n  \n    <h2>5. Task Scheduler</h2>\n    <p>Task Scheduler is a tool that helps automate tasks by scheduling them to run at a specific time.</p>\n    <h3>Why is Task Scheduler Important?</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Helps in automating system tasks (e.g., backups, updates).</li>\n      <li>Reduces the need for manual work.</li>\n      <li>Ensures that important tasks run even if the user forgets.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Examples of Task Scheduler:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Windows Task Scheduler (<code>taskschd.msc</code>): Automatically runs antivirus scans every night.</li>\n      <li>Linux Cron Jobs (<code>crontab -e</code>): Automates tasks like file backups or system updates.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Real-Life Example:</h3>\n    <p>Imagine you want your computer to back up files every night at 2 AM. Instead of doing it manually, you can use Task Scheduler to set up an automatic backup.</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is the main purpose of User Management in an OS?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To manage user accounts and permissions\",\n        \"To manage hardware devices\",\n        \"To speed up the computer\",\n        \"To monitor network performance\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Which OS tool helps enforce password policies and account security?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Task Scheduler\",\n        \"Security Policy\",\n        \"Performance Monitor\",\n        \"Device Manager\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Which command is used in Linux to add a new user?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"adduser\",\n        \"newuser\",\n        \"createuser\",\n        \"useradd\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Which OS tool is used to track CPU, memory, and disk usage?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Performance Monitor\",\n        \"Task Scheduler\",\n        \"User Management\",\n        \"Security Policy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Where can Windows users find device drivers and manage hardware devices?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Task Manager\",\n        \"Device Manager\",\n        \"Security Settings\",\n        \"Performance Monitor\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which tool in Windows helps automate tasks such as backups?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Task Scheduler\",\n        \"Performance Monitor\",\n        \"Device Manager\",\n        \"Security Policy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Which command in Linux is used to list connected USB devices?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"lsusb\",\n        \"listusb\",\n        \"usbinfo\",\n        \"devicelist\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"What is the purpose of a firewall in an OS security policy?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To block unauthorized network access\",\n        \"To clean up disk space\",\n        \"To monitor CPU performance\",\n        \"To schedule automatic tasks\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"What does the Windows Task Scheduler do?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Manages system performance\",\n        \"Automates scheduled tasks\",\n        \"Monitors security threats\",\n        \"Updates hardware drivers\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Which Linux tool is used to automate tasks at scheduled times?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"cron\",\n        \"taskmanager\",\n        \"taskrun\",\n        \"schedtask\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"________ is the OS tool used to create, modify, and delete user accounts.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"User Management\",\n        \"Security Policy\",\n        \"Task Scheduler\",\n        \"Performance Monitor\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"The tool responsible for protecting the system from unauthorized access is called ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Device Management\",\n        \"Security Policy\",\n        \"Performance Monitor\",\n        \"Task Scheduler\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"To check CPU and memory usage in real time, we use ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"User Management\",\n        \"Security Policy\",\n        \"Performance Monitor\",\n        \"Task Scheduler\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"The OS tool that automates tasks like backups and updates is called ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"User Management\",\n        \"Task Scheduler\",\n        \"Device Management\",\n        \"Security Policy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"The OS component that ensures devices like printers and USBs work correctly is called ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Performance Monitor\",\n        \"Device Management\",\n        \"Security Policy\",\n        \"Task Scheduler\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"A teacher having an admin account while students have restricted accounts is an example of ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Task Scheduler\",\n        \"User Management\",\n        \"Device Management\",\n        \"Performance Monitor\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"A security policy enforcing strong passwords ensures ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Easier login access\",\n        \"Protection against unauthorized users\",\n        \"Faster performance\",\n        \"Automatic updates\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"The command used in Linux to create a new user is ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"adduser\",\n        \"deluser\",\n        \"userconfig\",\n        \"newuser\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"To find out which application is using the most RAM, you would use ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Device Management\",\n        \"Task Scheduler\",\n        \"Performance Monitor\",\n        \"Security Policy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"In Windows, the tool used to schedule tasks like backups is called ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Task Scheduler\",\n        \"Performance Monitor\",\n        \"User Management\",\n        \"Security Policy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that User Management allows creating, modifying, and deleting user accounts.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the OS does not control what users can do on a system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"User Management helps prevent unauthorized access to a system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that in Windows, the Device Manager is used to manage user accounts.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"User Management allows multiple users to have personalized settings on the same system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that Security Policies help protect the system from threats like hacking and malware.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that security policies do not include enforcing password rules.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"A strong security policy helps prevent unauthorized users from accessing the system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that an account may get locked after multiple failed login attempts due to security policies.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that firewalls do not help in protecting a system from harmful network connections.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"Security policies help in password management and account security.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that a user with an admin account cannot install software on a system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Device Management is responsible for handling hardware devices connected to the system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that printers, USB drives, and keyboards are not part of device management.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"The OS installs and updates drivers to ensure proper communication between devices and the system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Device Management is only required for external hardware and not internal components.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"In Windows, Device Manager allows users to enable or disable devices.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that Linux users can use the \'lsusb\' command to list connected USB devices.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Performance Monitor helps in checking CPU, memory, and network usage.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Performance Monitor is not useful for identifying slow applications.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"Windows Task Manager can show real-time CPU and memory usage.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Linux has no tools like Task Manager to monitor system performance.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"The \'top\' command in Linux displays real-time CPU and memory usage.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that if a program is using too much RAM, it can slow down the system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that performance monitoring tools cannot be used to close unresponsive applications.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"Task Scheduler allows users to automate tasks such as system updates and backups.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Task Scheduler can only run tasks manually and not at a scheduled time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"Cron jobs in Linux are used for scheduling automated tasks.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Task Scheduler cannot be used to shut down a computer automatically.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that users can schedule antivirus scans using Task Scheduler.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that OS tools do not help in managing computer performance.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"A security policy may include firewall settings to block harmful connections.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that only administrators can change security policies.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"User Management helps in assigning different permissions to different users.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that a computer system can function well without device management.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"Performance monitoring tools help detect system slowdowns caused by high resource usage.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that Task Scheduler is only useful for businesses and not for individual users.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"Security policies may require users to change their passwords periodically.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that antivirus programs are not part of security policies.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"Device Management helps the OS recognize new hardware when connected.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that OS tools have no role in system maintenance.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"User Management allows setting restrictions on how users interact with the system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that performance monitoring tools cannot show disk activity.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"Task Scheduler helps ensure that important tasks run even if the user forgets.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that all OS tools must be manually operated every time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"Security policies can include rules for data encryption.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the OS does not need to manage user access levels.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"Performance Monitor helps identify potential security threats from suspicious programs.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that an OS can function without any security policies.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"Device Management includes managing both input and output devices.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  ',13,10),(33,'3.1-Process - Process States & Process Control Block (PCB)','<div>\n    <h2>3.1 Process - Process States & Process Control Block (PCB)</h2>\n    <p>In an operating system, a process is simply a running program. Every time you open an application (like a web browser or a music player), the operating system creates a process for it. The operating system manages multiple processes at the same time to ensure everything runs smoothly.</p>\n    \n    <h3>? Process States</h3>\n    <p>A process goes through different stages during its execution, just like a person’s life cycle (childhood, adulthood, old age). These stages are called Process States.</p>\n    \n    <h4>? Different Process States</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>New ?</strong> - The process has just been created and is waiting to be assigned resources.</li>\n      <li><strong>Ready ✅</strong> - The process is ready to run but waiting for the CPU to execute it.</li>\n      <li><strong>Running ?‍♂️</strong> - The process is currently being executed by the CPU.</li>\n      <li><strong>Blocked (Waiting) ⏳</strong> - The process is waiting for some resource (like user input, file access, or a network response).</li>\n      <li><strong>Terminated ❌</strong> - The process has finished execution or has been stopped by the user.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>? Process Control Block (PCB)</h3>\n    <p>To manage processes, the operating system keeps a record of important details about each process. This information is stored in a Process Control Block (PCB).</p>\n    \n    <h4>? What is PCB?</h4>\n    <p>PCB is like an identity card for a process, containing all necessary information the OS needs to manage that process.</p>\n    \n    <h4>? Information Stored in PCB</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Process ID (PID) ?</strong> - A unique number assigned to each process.</li>\n      <li><strong>Process State ?</strong> - Indicates whether the process is New, Ready, Running, Waiting, or Terminated.</li>\n      <li><strong>Program Counter (PC) ?️</strong> - Stores the memory address of the next instruction to be executed.</li>\n      <li><strong>CPU Registers ?</strong> - Stores temporary data like calculations, function calls, and variable values.</li>\n      <li><strong>Memory Management Information ?️</strong> - Contains details of memory usage.</li>\n      <li><strong>I/O Information ?</strong> - Stores input/output requests.</li>\n      <li><strong>Process Priority ⚡</strong> - Defines how important the process is compared to others.</li>\n      <li><strong>Parent Process ID ?‍?</strong> - Stores the parent’s ID if the process has a parent.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>? Real-Life Analogy</h3>\n    <p>Imagine a PCB as a school report card for each student (process). The report card stores details like:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Student ID (Process ID)</li>\n      <li>Current grade (Process State)</li>\n      <li>Next class to attend (Program Counter)</li>\n      <li>Subjects and marks (CPU Registers & Memory Info)</li>\n      <li>Extracurricular activities (I/O Requests)</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>? Example Scenario</h3>\n    <p>Let\'s say you are working on a Word document and playing music at the same time. Here’s how the OS manages the processes:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>You open Word → A new process is created and moves to the Ready state.</li>\n      <li>You start typing → The process moves to the Running state.</li>\n      <li>You switch to a music player → The Word process moves to the Waiting state while the music player moves to Running.</li>\n      <li>Music player loads a new song → It waits for the file to be accessed (moves to the Waiting state).</li>\n      <li>You close Word → The Word process moves to the Terminated state.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>? Conclusion</h3>\n    <p>A process is a running program in the operating system.</p>\n    <p>It moves through different process states (New, Ready, Running, Waiting, Terminated).</p>\n    <p>The Process Control Block (PCB) stores important details about each process.</p>\n    <p>The OS uses PCB to manage processes efficiently.</p>\n    <p>This helps the OS multitask effectively, allowing you to run multiple applications at the same time without issues.</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is a process in an operating system?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"A static program stored on disk\",\n        \"A running program in execution\",\n        \"A software application\",\n        \"A background service only\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is NOT a process state?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"New\",\n        \"Ready\",\n        \"Executing\",\n        \"Terminated\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"What happens in the \'New\' state of a process?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"The process is waiting for CPU time\",\n        \"The process is being created and initialized\",\n        \"The process is executing instructions\",\n        \"The process is waiting for an I/O operation\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Which process state means the process is actively executing on the CPU?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Waiting\",\n        \"Blocked\",\n        \"Running\",\n        \"Ready\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"When a process is waiting for input from a file, what state is it in?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Ready\",\n        \"Running\",\n        \"Waiting\",\n        \"Terminated\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which state does a process enter after completing its execution?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Running\",\n        \"Terminated\",\n        \"Blocked\",\n        \"New\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"What is stored in a Process Control Block (PCB)?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Only the process ID\",\n        \"Only memory information\",\n        \"All essential details needed to manage the process\",\n        \"Only the process state\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is NOT a part of a PCB?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Process ID\",\n        \"CPU Registers\",\n        \"User Login Information\",\n        \"Memory Management Information\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"What does the Program Counter (PC) store in a PCB?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"The memory address of the next instruction\",\n        \"The process priority level\",\n        \"The process creation time\",\n        \"The allocated CPU time\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Which process state is directly linked to the CPU?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"New\",\n        \"Ready\",\n        \"Running\",\n        \"Terminated\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"What happens if a process in the Running state needs to wait for a resource?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"It moves to the Ready state\",\n        \"It moves to the Waiting state\",\n        \"It is terminated immediately\",\n        \"It continues running but at a lower priority\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following best describes a process in the Ready state?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"It is waiting for an event to occur\",\n        \"It is waiting for the CPU to execute it\",\n        \"It is currently using the CPU\",\n        \"It has finished execution and exited\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"What determines the priority of a process?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Process ID\",\n        \"Process Control Block\",\n        \"Process Priority Field in PCB\",\n        \"Process Execution Time\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Why is PCB important in process management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"It stores information needed for the OS to manage a process\",\n        \"It determines the process execution speed\",\n        \"It decides which process should terminate\",\n        \"It contains only CPU usage statistics\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Which component of the OS is responsible for switching a process between states?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Memory Manager\",\n        \"CPU Scheduler\",\n        \"Device Manager\",\n        \"User Interface\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"A ________ is a running program managed by the operating system.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Thread\", \"Process\", \"Task\", \"Application\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"The OS assigns a unique identifier called ________ to each process.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Process Name\", \"Process ID\", \"Thread ID\", \"Execution Code\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"A process in the ________ state is waiting for CPU execution.\",\n      \"options\": [\"New\", \"Ready\", \"Blocked\", \"Terminated\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"When a process is currently being executed by the CPU, it is in the ________ state.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Ready\", \"Blocked\", \"Running\", \"Terminated\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"A process moves to the ________ state when it has completed execution.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Waiting\", \"Terminated\", \"Blocked\", \"Running\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"The Process Control Block (PCB) stores important information about a ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Thread\", \"Task\", \"Process\", \"File\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ stores the memory address of the next instruction to be executed.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Program Counter\", \"Stack Pointer\", \"Process ID\", \"Register\"],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"A process that is waiting for a resource moves to the ________ state.\",\n      \"options\": [\"New\", \"Ready\", \"Blocked\", \"Running\"],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"The OS manages multiple processes at the same time to ensure ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Slow execution\", \"Efficiency\", \"System failure\", \"Overheating\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Each PCB stores the ________ of the process, which determines its execution stage.\",\n      \"options\": [\"Name\", \"State\", \"Size\", \"Creation Time\"],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"A process is a running program in the operating system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"A process cannot exist in multiple states during its execution.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"The \'New\' state of a process means that it has just been created and is waiting for resources.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"A process in the \'Ready\' state is currently being executed by the CPU.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"The \'Running\' state means that the process is actively being executed by the CPU.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"A process in the \'Waiting\' state is waiting for some resource like user input or file access.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Once a process enters the \'Terminated\' state, it can move back to \'Running\' state.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"The operating system assigns a unique Process ID (PID) to each process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"A Process Control Block (PCB) stores important details about a process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"The PCB does not contain information about the process state.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"The program counter in the PCB stores the memory address of the next instruction to be executed.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"The CPU registers in the PCB store temporary data like calculations and function calls.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Memory management information in the PCB includes details about RAM usage by a process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"A PCB does not store information about input/output requests made by the process.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Every process has the same priority level in the operating system.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"The parent process ID in the PCB helps track child processes created by another process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"The operating system does not require a PCB to manage processes.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Multitasking is possible because the OS efficiently manages multiple processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"The \'Ready\' state means a process is waiting for the CPU to execute it.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"A process can move directly from \'Running\' to \'New\' state.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"A process in the \'Waiting\' state is waiting for CPU time to execute instructions.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"Once a process starts running, it cannot return to the \'Ready\' state.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"The PCB acts like an identity card for a process in the OS.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"The PCB does not store any security-related information.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"When you close an application, its process moves to the \'Terminated\' state.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"The operating system does not need to track process execution states.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"Processes in the \'Blocked\' state require CPU time to continue execution.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"The process priority helps the OS decide which process should be executed first.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"A single process can have multiple PCBs assigned to it.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"The PCB of a process is removed when the process enters the \'Terminated\' state.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"A process can remain in the \'New\' state indefinitely.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"The OS can create a new process without assigning it a Process ID.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"The \'Running\' state is the only state where a process can execute instructions.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"A process in the \'Ready\' state is waiting for memory allocation.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"The OS can schedule a process to move back and forth between \'Ready\' and \'Running\' states.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"The program counter in the PCB helps resume a paused process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"All processes in an operating system have the same execution time.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"Processes in the \'Blocked\' state are removed from memory.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"Process management ensures efficient execution of multiple processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"The PCB contains information about the process owner.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"A process can never move directly from \'Running\' to \'Waiting\'.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"Each process in the OS is isolated from other processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"The OS can kill a process before it finishes execution.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"The PCB does not contain information about allocated memory resources.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"Processes in the \'Ready\' state cannot return to the \'New\' state.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"The process scheduling algorithm decides which process gets CPU time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"Process priority is not considered in CPU scheduling.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"A terminated process can be restarted without re-creation.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"The OS can handle multiple processes simultaneously.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"Every process in an OS shares the same memory space.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    }\n]\n  ',13,11),(34,'3.2-Process Scheduling','<div>\n    <h1>3.2 Process Scheduling</h1>\n    <p>Process scheduling is the method by which the operating system (OS) manages the execution of multiple processes in a computer. Since the CPU can only execute one process at a time (in a single-core system), the OS ensures that all processes get a fair chance to execute by scheduling them efficiently.</p>\n    \n    <h2>To understand Process Scheduling, we will break it down into the following parts:</h2>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Scheduling Queues</li>\n      <li>Schedulers</li>\n      <li>Context Switch</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>1. Scheduling Queues</h2>\n    <p>A queue is like a waiting line where processes stand in order to get executed by the CPU. In an operating system, there are different types of queues to manage processes.</p>\n    \n    <h3>Types of Scheduling Queues</h3>\n    <h4>Job Queue</h4>\n    <p>This queue contains all processes that are ready to be executed.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> When you open multiple applications on your computer (such as a web browser, music player, and Word document), all these processes enter the job queue.</p>\n    \n    <h4>Ready Queue</h4>\n    <p>This queue contains all processes that are ready to run and are waiting for CPU time.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Suppose you have 5 apps running, but the CPU can only process one at a time. The remaining 4 processes wait in the ready queue.</p>\n    \n    <h4>Waiting Queue (I/O Queue)</h4>\n    <p>If a process needs to wait for some input/output (I/O) operation (e.g., reading a file, printing a document), it moves to the waiting queue.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> When you click Print in MS Word, the document is placed in a queue until the printer is available.</p>\n    \n    <h3>Example of Scheduling Queues in Real Life</h3>\n    <p>Imagine you are in a restaurant:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Job Queue</strong> → All customers who enter the restaurant and are waiting for a table.</li>\n      <li><strong>Ready Queue</strong> → Customers who got a table and are waiting for their food.</li>\n      <li><strong>Waiting Queue</strong> → Customers who ordered food and are waiting for the chef to prepare it.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>2. Schedulers</h2>\n    <p>Schedulers are responsible for managing processes and moving them between different queues.</p>\n    \n    <h3>Types of Schedulers</h3>\n    <h4>1. Long-Term Scheduler (Job Scheduler)</h4>\n    <p>Decides which processes should enter the ready queue from the job queue.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Imagine you are at an airport. Job Scheduler decides which passengers should go through security checks (entering the Ready Queue).</p>\n    \n    <h4>2. Short-Term Scheduler (CPU Scheduler)</h4>\n    <p>Decides which process gets CPU time next from the ready queue.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> A teacher asks students one by one to answer a question. The teacher decides who answers next (similar to how the short-term scheduler picks the next process).</p>\n    \n    <h4>3. Medium-Term Scheduler</h4>\n    <p>Removes processes from memory (called swapping out) and brings them back later (called swapping in).</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Imagine a restaurant with limited seats. If it’s too crowded, the manager may ask some people to wait outside until seats are available. This is similar to swapping out processes to free up memory.</p>\n    \n    <h2>3. Context Switch</h2>\n    <p>A context switch happens when the CPU switches from one process to another. It saves the state of the current process and loads the state of the new process.</p>\n    \n    <h3>How Context Switching Works</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Save the current process’s state (like remembering what a person was doing before taking a break).</li>\n      <li>Load the next process’s state (like picking up where another person left off).</li>\n      <li>Start executing the new process.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>Example of Context Switching in Real Life</h3>\n    <p>Imagine a teacher calls on Student A to answer a question. Suddenly, the teacher switches to Student B without letting Student A finish. The teacher must remember where Student A stopped before returning to them.</p>\n    \n    <h2>Final Summary</h2>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Scheduling Queues:</strong> Help manage processes waiting to be executed.</li>\n      <li><strong>Schedulers:</strong> Decide which processes get CPU time and when.</li>\n      <li><strong>Context Switch:</strong> Saves and switches processes when multitasking.</li>\n    </ul>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is process scheduling in an operating system?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Managing the execution of multiple processes\",\n        \"Executing only one process at a time\",\n        \"Deleting processes\",\n        \"Shutting down the system\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Which queue contains all processes that are ready to be executed?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Ready Queue\",\n        \"Job Queue\",\n        \"Waiting Queue\",\n        \"Execution Queue\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"What does the long-term scheduler do?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Selects which process gets CPU time next\",\n        \"Decides which process enters the ready queue\",\n        \"Swaps processes in and out of memory\",\n        \"Terminates processes\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"What is another name for the short-term scheduler?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Job Scheduler\",\n        \"CPU Scheduler\",\n        \"Memory Scheduler\",\n        \"Process Scheduler\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following runs most frequently?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Long-Term Scheduler\",\n        \"Short-Term Scheduler\",\n        \"Medium-Term Scheduler\",\n        \"Job Scheduler\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"What happens during a context switch?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"The OS shuts down\",\n        \"The CPU switches from one process to another\",\n        \"All processes are deleted\",\n        \"Processes merge into one\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Which queue contains processes that are waiting for I/O operations to complete?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Ready Queue\",\n        \"Job Queue\",\n        \"Waiting Queue\",\n        \"Execution Queue\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"What is the purpose of the medium-term scheduler?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Terminate processes\",\n        \"Move processes between RAM and disk\",\n        \"Assign CPU time\",\n        \"Handle I/O operations\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"In real life, what is an example of a ready queue?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"A customer waiting for food at a restaurant\",\n        \"Passengers waiting at airport security\",\n        \"A chef cooking food\",\n        \"A person sleeping\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Why is context switching necessary?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To allow multitasking\",\n        \"To increase CPU speed\",\n        \"To remove background processes\",\n        \"To shut down the system\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    }\n  ]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Process scheduling is used by the OS to manage the execution of multiple _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"devices\",\n        \"processes\",\n        \"files\",\n        \"networks\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"A queue that holds all processes waiting to be executed is called the _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Ready Queue\",\n        \"Job Queue\",\n        \"Waiting Queue\",\n        \"Execution Queue\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"The _______ Queue contains processes that are ready to run and waiting for CPU time.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Job\",\n        \"Ready\",\n        \"Waiting\",\n        \"Execution\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"A process that is waiting for an I/O operation moves to the _______ Queue.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Ready\",\n        \"Waiting\",\n        \"Job\",\n        \"Execution\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Which scheduler is responsible for deciding which processes should enter the ready queue?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Short-Term Scheduler\",\n        \"Long-Term Scheduler\",\n        \"Medium-Term Scheduler\",\n        \"I/O Scheduler\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"The _______ scheduler decides which process gets CPU time next from the ready queue.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Short-Term\",\n        \"Long-Term\",\n        \"Medium-Term\",\n        \"Task\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"The Medium-Term Scheduler performs a process known as _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Paging\",\n        \"Swapping\",\n        \"Scheduling\",\n        \"Buffering\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Context switching happens when the CPU switches from one _______ to another.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"thread\",\n        \"process\",\n        \"task\",\n        \"queue\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"During a context switch, the OS must save and restore the state of the _______.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"current process\",\n        \"job queue\",\n        \"hardware device\",\n        \"execution stack\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following scheduling queues contains processes that are waiting for an external event, such as input from a user?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Job Queue\",\n        \"Ready Queue\",\n        \"Waiting Queue\",\n        \"Execution Queue\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that process scheduling is responsible for managing the execution of multiple processes in a computer.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the CPU can execute multiple processes at the same time in a single-core system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that a job queue contains all processes that are ready to be executed.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that a ready queue contains processes that are currently running on the CPU.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that a waiting queue holds processes that are waiting for I/O operations to complete.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the long-term scheduler runs frequently to select the next process for execution.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the short-term scheduler runs frequently to select which process gets CPU time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the medium-term scheduler is responsible for swapping processes in and out of memory.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that context switching allows the CPU to switch from one process to another.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that context switching does not require saving the state of a process before switching.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the job queue includes all processes in the system, including those that are completed.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that a ready queue contains processes that are waiting for I/O operations to complete.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the short-term scheduler decides which process gets CPU time next.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the long-term scheduler runs more frequently than the short-term scheduler.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that a medium-term scheduler is responsible for swapping processes in and out of memory.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that process scheduling is unnecessary in modern operating systems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that a CPU scheduler is also known as a short-term scheduler.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the ready queue contains only one process at a time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that context switching can cause a slight delay in process execution.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the medium-term scheduler decides which process gets CPU time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that scheduling queues help manage processes waiting to be executed.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the short-term scheduler selects processes from the job queue.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that a context switch involves saving and loading process states.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that a process can move from the waiting queue directly to the running state.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that job scheduling occurs less frequently than CPU scheduling.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that every process in a system is always in a ready queue.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that context switching is necessary for multitasking in operating systems.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that scheduling queues are only used for long-term scheduling.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that process scheduling is essential for efficient CPU utilization.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that a process in the waiting queue does not require CPU time.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    }\n]\n  ',13,11),(35,'3.3-Inter-Process Communication (IPC)','<div>\n    <h2>3.3 Inter-Process Communication (IPC)</h2>\n    <h3>Introduction to IPC</h3>\n    <p>Inter-Process Communication (IPC) is a mechanism that allows multiple processes to communicate with each other. Processes are independent programs running on a computer, and sometimes they need to share information or coordinate tasks. IPC helps in achieving this by enabling data exchange between processes.</p>\n  \n    <h3>Why is IPC needed?</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>When multiple processes work on the same task, they may need to share data.</li>\n      <li>Some processes may need to send messages to others to coordinate their operations.</li>\n      <li>IPC helps in better resource utilization by allowing processes to work together efficiently.</li>\n      <li>It is essential in multi-core and distributed computing systems.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>Examples of IPC in Daily Life</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li><b>Chat Applications</b> – When you send a message on WhatsApp, your message (process 1) is sent to the server (process 2), which then delivers it to your friend (process 3).</li>\n      <li><b>Google Docs</b> – When multiple users edit a document, different processes share and update data simultaneously.</li>\n      <li><b>Banking Systems</b> – When you withdraw money from an ATM, the bank server process communicates with the ATM process to verify your balance and process the transaction.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>Shared Memory System</h3>\n    <p>In a shared memory system, multiple processes communicate by reading and writing data into a common memory space. This is like a shared whiteboard where multiple people can write and read information.</p>\n    \n    <h4>How Shared Memory Works?</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>One process creates a shared memory segment.</li>\n      <li>Other processes attach to the shared memory segment.</li>\n      <li>Processes read from and write to the shared memory to exchange information.</li>\n      <li>Once communication is done, processes detach from the shared memory.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>Example of Shared Memory</h4>\n    <p>Imagine two employees in an office using a whiteboard to exchange messages:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Employee A writes “Meeting at 3 PM” on the whiteboard.</li>\n      <li>Employee B reads it and notes the time. This is similar to how shared memory works in IPC.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>Advantages of Shared Memory</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Fast Communication – Since no extra data copying is required.</li>\n      <li>Efficient for large data – Useful when processes need to share a lot of information quickly.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>Disadvantages of Shared Memory</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Synchronization issues – If multiple processes modify data at the same time, conflicts may occur.</li>\n      <li>Security risks – One process can accidentally overwrite important data.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>Message Passing System</h3>\n    <p>In a message passing system, processes communicate by sending and receiving messages. Unlike shared memory, processes do not directly share data but instead exchange messages through predefined communication mechanisms.</p>\n  \n    <h4>How Message Passing Works?</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>One process sends a message to another process.</li>\n      <li>The receiving process gets the message and processes it.</li>\n      <li>The system ensures that messages are delivered in the correct order.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>Example of Message Passing</h4>\n    <p>Imagine two people talking over a walkie-talkie:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Person A presses a button and says, “Let’s meet at 3 PM.”</li>\n      <li>Person B listens and responds, “Okay, see you then.” Here, the voice messages are like IPC message passing.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>Types of Message Passing</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li><b>Synchronous Message Passing</b> – The sender waits for the receiver to acknowledge the message before continuing. <br> Example: A phone call where both people must be present to communicate.</li>\n      <li><b>Asynchronous Message Passing</b> – The sender sends the message and continues its work without waiting for the receiver. <br> Example: Sending an email where the receiver can read it later.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>Advantages of Message Passing</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>No direct memory sharing – This makes it safer and avoids data conflicts.</li>\n      <li>Better security – Each message is controlled and structured properly.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h4>Disadvantages of Message Passing</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Slower than shared memory – Messages need to be copied and processed.</li>\n      <li>Overhead in communication – Extra steps are needed to ensure message delivery and order.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>Comparison of Shared Memory and Message Passing</h3>\n    <table border=\"1\">\n      <tr>\n        <th>Feature</th>\n        <th>Shared Memory</th>\n        <th>Message Passing</th>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Speed</td>\n        <td>Faster</td>\n        <td>Slower</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Complexity</td>\n        <td>More complex (needs synchronization)</td>\n        <td>Simpler to implement</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Security</td>\n        <td>Less secure</td>\n        <td>More secure</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Data Transfer</td>\n        <td>Direct memory access</td>\n        <td>Needs message transmission</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Best for</td>\n        <td>Large data exchange</td>\n        <td>Simple and structured communication</td>\n      </tr>\n    </table>\n  \n    <h3>Conclusion</h3>\n    <p>Inter-Process Communication (IPC) is essential for processes to collaborate effectively. Shared memory provides fast communication but requires synchronization, whereas message passing is structured and secure but can be slower. Choosing the right IPC mechanism depends on the application’s requirements.</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is Inter-Process Communication (IPC)?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"A method for processes to execute independently\",\n        \"A mechanism that allows processes to communicate with each other\",\n        \"A technique for process scheduling\",\n        \"A system that prevents process execution\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Why is IPC needed?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To allow multiple processes to share data and coordinate tasks\",\n        \"To prevent processes from communicating\",\n        \"To slow down process execution\",\n        \"To limit the number of running processes\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an example of IPC in daily life?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Watching a movie on a single device\",\n        \"Two employees working on different tasks without communication\",\n        \"Chat applications where messages are exchanged between users\",\n        \"Writing a document without internet connectivity\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"What is a shared memory system?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"A communication method where processes share a common memory space\",\n        \"A technique where processes send messages to each other\",\n        \"A scheduling method for running processes\",\n        \"A way to prevent data exchange between processes\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Which step is NOT part of the shared memory communication process?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Creating a shared memory segment\",\n        \"Processes attach to the shared memory\",\n        \"Processes send messages over a network\",\n        \"Processes detach from shared memory after communication\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an example of shared memory IPC?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Two employees writing on a shared whiteboard\",\n        \"Two people talking over a phone call\",\n        \"Sending an email to a colleague\",\n        \"A teacher giving a lecture in a class\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"What is a disadvantage of shared memory communication?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Fast communication speed\",\n        \"Requires synchronization to avoid conflicts\",\n        \"More secure than message passing\",\n        \"Does not require memory allocation\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"What is a message passing system in IPC?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"A method where processes communicate by sending and receiving messages\",\n        \"A system where processes share memory directly\",\n        \"A way to block communication between processes\",\n        \"A technique to increase CPU execution speed\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is an example of message passing?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Two employees writing on a shared whiteboard\",\n        \"Sending an email to a colleague\",\n        \"Reading a book individually\",\n        \"Opening multiple applications on a computer\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"What is a disadvantage of message passing?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Slower than shared memory communication\",\n        \"Data conflicts occur frequently\",\n        \"Requires direct memory access\",\n        \"Processes need to use the same memory space\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Inter-Process Communication (IPC) allows multiple processes to ________ with each other.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"compete\",\n        \"communicate\",\n        \"terminate\",\n        \"execute\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"IPC is essential for processes to share ________ and coordinate tasks.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"data\",\n        \"memory\",\n        \"CPU\",\n        \"output\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"One of the main methods of IPC is ________, where multiple processes use a common memory space to communicate.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"message passing\",\n        \"shared memory\",\n        \"networking\",\n        \"threading\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Another IPC method is ________, where processes exchange messages instead of sharing memory.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"paging\",\n        \"message passing\",\n        \"buffering\",\n        \"synchronization\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Shared memory communication is ________ compared to message passing.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"slower\",\n        \"faster\",\n        \"more secure\",\n        \"less efficient\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Message passing ensures that messages are delivered in the correct ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"time\",\n        \"order\",\n        \"format\",\n        \"size\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"A ________ message passing system requires the sender to wait for the receiver to acknowledge before continuing.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"synchronous\",\n        \"asynchronous\",\n        \"buffered\",\n        \"non-blocking\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"An asynchronous message passing system allows the sender to send messages without waiting for ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"processing\",\n        \"response\",\n        \"execution\",\n        \"transmission\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Shared memory requires ________ to prevent data conflicts when multiple processes access it.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"virtualization\",\n        \"synchronization\",\n        \"paging\",\n        \"segmentation\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"A real-life example of message passing is a ________, where one person speaks and the other listens.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"whiteboard\",\n        \"walkie-talkie\",\n        \"file storage\",\n        \"RAM\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Inter-Process Communication (IPC) allows multiple processes to communicate with each other.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"IPC is not necessary for multi-core and distributed computing systems.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Shared memory IPC allows multiple processes to read and write data in a common memory space.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Message passing IPC involves direct memory sharing between processes.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Synchronization is a challenge in shared memory IPC because multiple processes can modify data simultaneously.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Message passing IPC is generally more secure than shared memory IPC.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Shared memory IPC is faster than message passing IPC.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"In synchronous message passing, the sender does not wait for an acknowledgment from the receiver.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Asynchronous message passing allows the sender to continue execution without waiting for the receiver to acknowledge the message.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Google Docs is an example of IPC where multiple users edit a document simultaneously.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"In shared memory IPC, one process creates a shared memory segment that others can attach to.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"Message passing IPC is less structured than shared memory IPC.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"An ATM transaction is an example of IPC where the ATM process communicates with the bank server process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Shared memory IPC is best suited for large data exchange.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Message passing IPC is preferred when processes need to exchange large amounts of data quickly.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"In message passing IPC, messages must always be delivered in order.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"Security risks in shared memory IPC arise because processes have direct access to shared data.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Message passing IPC has lower overhead than shared memory IPC.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Inter-process communication is only used in distributed systems.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"Processes using shared memory IPC need to synchronize access to prevent conflicts.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"Message passing IPC eliminates the need for synchronization mechanisms like semaphores.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"In shared memory IPC, processes communicate using a common file system instead of memory segments.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"IPC is required for processes to share resources and coordinate tasks.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"A walkie-talkie conversation is similar to message passing IPC.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"In shared memory IPC, a process cannot read memory written by another process.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"A chat application using a server to relay messages between users is an example of IPC.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"A process can both send and receive messages in message passing IPC.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"Message passing IPC is unsuitable for distributed systems.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"In shared memory IPC, the operating system automatically synchronizes access to memory.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"Message passing IPC requires more processing overhead compared to shared memory IPC.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"In IPC, message passing does not require a communication mechanism.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"Shared memory IPC is typically used when a large amount of data needs to be exchanged between processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"Message passing IPC is more complex to implement than shared memory IPC.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"Shared memory IPC does not require synchronization.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"Message passing IPC ensures better security because processes do not directly share memory.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"Inter-process communication is used only in real-time systems.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"Shared memory IPC can be used for communication between processes on different machines.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"Synchronization issues in shared memory IPC can be resolved using locks or semaphores.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"A phone call is an example of synchronous message passing IPC.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"An email is an example of synchronous message passing IPC.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    }\n]\n  ',13,11),(36,'3.4-Threads – Benefits, User and Kernel Threads, Multithreading Models','<div>\n    <h2>3.4 Threads – Benefits, User and Kernel Threads, Multithreading Models</h2>\n    \n    <h3>What is a Thread?</h3>\n    <p>A thread is a small unit of a process. Think of a process as a TV and a thread as a channel. The TV (process) remains the same, but you can switch between channels (threads) without changing the TV.</p>\n    <p>A process runs a program, and a thread is a smaller part of the program that runs separately but within the same process.</p>\n    \n    <h3>Benefits of Threads</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li><b>Faster Execution:</b> Threads execute tasks in parallel, meaning the CPU is used more efficiently.</li>\n      <li><b>Better Performance:</b> Different tasks happen at the same time, improving speed.</li>\n      <li><b>Less Memory Use:</b> Threads share memory with their process, so they don’t need separate memory space.</li>\n      <li><b>Efficient CPU Use:</b> A CPU can work on multiple threads at once, reducing idle time.</li>\n      <li><b>Quick Response Time:</b> Applications like web browsers use multiple threads to load different parts simultaneously.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>User Threads vs. Kernel Threads</h3>\n    <h4>User Threads (Managed by the Application, Not the OS)</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>The OS doesn’t know about user threads.</li>\n      <li>They are faster and easier to manage.</li>\n      <li>If one thread gets stuck, the entire process may stop working.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>Kernel Threads (Managed by the Operating System)</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>The OS knows about these threads and controls their execution.</li>\n      <li>They are slower but more powerful.</li>\n      <li>If one thread stops working, others can continue running.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>Multithreading Models</h3>\n    <h4>1. Many-to-One Model</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Multiple user threads → Mapped to ONE kernel thread.</li>\n      <li><b>Pros:</b> Simple and efficient, requires fewer system resources.</li>\n      <li><b>Cons:</b> If one thread blocks, all threads stop; can\'t use multiple CPUs.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>2. One-to-One Model</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>One user thread → Mapped to ONE kernel thread.</li>\n      <li><b>Pros:</b> If one thread stops, others keep running; allows parallel execution.</li>\n      <li><b>Cons:</b> Uses more system resources.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h4>3. Many-to-Many Model</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Multiple user threads → Mapped to Multiple kernel threads.</li>\n      <li><b>Pros:</b> Efficient resource use; supports parallel execution.</li>\n      <li><b>Cons:</b> More complex to manage.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>Comparison of Multithreading Models</h3>\n    <table border=\"1\">\n      <tr>\n        <th>Model</th>\n        <th>Pros</th>\n        <th>Cons</th>\n        <th>Example</th>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Many-to-One</td>\n        <td>Simple, low resource usage</td>\n        <td>One blocked thread stops all</td>\n        <td>Single-lane road</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>One-to-One</td>\n        <td>Parallel execution, more reliable</td>\n        <td>High resource usage</td>\n        <td>Multi-lane highway</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Many-to-Many</td>\n        <td>Efficient resource use, best performance</td>\n        <td>Complex implementation</td>\n        <td>Toll plaza with many booths</td>\n      </tr>\n    </table>\n    \n    <h3>Conclusion</h3>\n    <p>Threads allow programs to run faster by executing multiple tasks simultaneously. The way user threads map to kernel threads affects performance and efficiency. The Many-to-Many model provides the best balance, but the choice depends on the system requirements.</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is a thread in computing?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"A type of virus\",\n        \"A small unit of a process\",\n        \"A hardware component\",\n        \"A type of database\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is NOT a benefit of threads?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Faster execution\",\n        \"More memory usage\",\n        \"Better CPU utilization\",\n        \"Quick response time\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"How do threads improve performance?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"By executing tasks in parallel\",\n        \"By blocking all processes\",\n        \"By using more system memory\",\n        \"By slowing down CPU operations\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following best describes user threads?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Managed by the operating system\",\n        \"Managed by the application\",\n        \"Require more resources than kernel threads\",\n        \"Are always slower than kernel threads\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Kernel threads are managed by?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"User applications\",\n        \"Hardware\",\n        \"Operating system\",\n        \"BIOS\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following is a drawback of user threads?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"They are slower than kernel threads\",\n        \"If one thread blocks, all threads stop\",\n        \"They cannot be used for parallel execution\",\n        \"They use more memory than kernel threads\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Which threading model maps multiple user threads to one kernel thread?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"One-to-One\",\n        \"Many-to-One\",\n        \"Many-to-Many\",\n        \"None of the above\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"In which threading model does each user thread have its own kernel thread?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Many-to-One\",\n        \"One-to-One\",\n        \"Many-to-Many\",\n        \"None of the above\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"Which threading model is the most efficient in utilizing system resources?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Many-to-One\",\n        \"One-to-One\",\n        \"Many-to-Many\",\n        \"None of the above\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Which threading model suffers from the problem of one blocked thread stopping all others?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Many-to-One\",\n        \"One-to-One\",\n        \"Many-to-Many\",\n        \"None of the above\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"A thread is a smaller unit of a ________ that runs separately but within it.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"process\",\n        \"file\",\n        \"kernel\",\n        \"memory\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"One of the main benefits of threads is ________ execution, allowing tasks to run in parallel.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sequential\",\n        \"parallel\",\n        \"single-threaded\",\n        \"delayed\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Threads share ________ with their process, reducing memory usage compared to multiple processes.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"CPU time\",\n        \"memory\",\n        \"files\",\n        \"data structure\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"User threads are managed by the ________ instead of the operating system.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"hardware\",\n        \"application\",\n        \"kernel\",\n        \"scheduler\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Kernel threads are directly controlled by the ________.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"hardware\",\n        \"user\",\n        \"operating system\",\n        \"CPU\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"A major drawback of user threads is that if one thread blocks, ________ threads may also stop working.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"all other\",\n        \"kernel\",\n        \"hardware\",\n        \"OS-managed\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"Kernel threads are more powerful than user threads but have ________ overhead.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"lower\",\n        \"higher\",\n        \"no\",\n        \"minimal\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"In the Many-to-One model, multiple user threads are mapped to ________ kernel thread(s).\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"zero\",\n        \"one\",\n        \"many\",\n        \"two\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"The One-to-One model maps each user thread to ________ kernel thread(s).\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"zero\",\n        \"one\",\n        \"many\",\n        \"two\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"The Many-to-Many model allows multiple user threads to be mapped to ________ kernel threads.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"zero\",\n        \"one\",\n        \"many\",\n        \"two\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that a thread is a smaller unit of a process that runs separately within the same process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that threads require separate memory space like processes do.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that using multiple threads improves performance by allowing tasks to run in parallel.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that a single-threaded application is faster than a multi-threaded application.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that user threads are managed by the application, not the operating system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that kernel threads are managed by the application instead of the operating system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that user threads are faster than kernel threads since they do not involve the OS.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that kernel threads do not require system resources to function.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that if a user thread blocks, all other threads in the process may also stop.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that kernel threads are independent of the operating system’s control.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that multithreading allows multiple threads to execute simultaneously in a process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that threads do not share resources with other threads within the same process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that in a many-to-one model, multiple user threads are mapped to a single kernel thread.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that in a one-to-one model, multiple user threads share a single kernel thread.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that in a many-to-many model, multiple user threads are mapped to multiple kernel threads.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the many-to-one model allows true parallel execution across multiple CPUs.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the one-to-one model allows each user thread to be mapped to its own kernel thread.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that multithreading models do not affect the performance of an application.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the many-to-many model provides a good balance between efficiency and parallel execution.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that user threads require the operating system’s involvement for scheduling.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that kernel threads can continue executing even if one thread crashes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that user threads are slower than kernel threads because they need OS scheduling.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that multithreading makes better use of CPU resources by reducing idle time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that a process with multiple threads uses more memory than multiple single-threaded processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that multithreading allows quick response times in applications like web browsers.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that context switching between threads is slower than between processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the one-to-one model allows true parallel execution on multi-core processors.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that a kernel thread can be directly controlled by the user without OS involvement.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the many-to-one model is not suitable for multi-core processors.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that threads in the same process cannot communicate with each other.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that a web server can use threads to handle multiple client requests simultaneously.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that a thread must have its own memory space separate from other threads.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that user threads rely on user-level libraries for scheduling and execution.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that kernel threads are always faster than user threads in all scenarios.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that in the many-to-many model, the OS can schedule kernel threads efficiently.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the one-to-one model is the least resource-intensive multithreading model.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that threads within the same process share the same address space.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that threads in the same process cannot share data with each other.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that a multi-threaded program is more responsive than a single-threaded program.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that threads and processes are identical in how they execute tasks.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that context switching between threads is more efficient than between processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that multithreading is only useful for graphical applications.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the many-to-many model offers flexibility in thread scheduling.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  ',13,11),(37,'3.5- Understanding Process Commands in Linux ps, wait, sleep, exit, and kill','<div>\n    <h2>3.5 Understanding Process Commands in Linux: ps, wait, sleep, exit, and kill</h2>\n    <p>Processes are programs that are currently running on a computer. In Linux, we use different commands to manage these processes, such as viewing them, stopping them, or making them wait.</p>\n    <p>In this guide, we will explore five important process-related commands:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>ps</strong> – Shows the list of running processes.</li>\n      <li><strong>wait</strong> – Waits for a process to complete.</li>\n      <li><strong>sleep</strong> – Pauses execution for a specified time.</li>\n      <li><strong>exit</strong> – Ends a process.</li>\n      <li><strong>kill</strong> – Terminates a process forcefully.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>1. ps Command – View Running Processes</h3>\n    <p>The <code>ps</code> (process status) command is used to see which processes are currently running on the system.</p>\n    <p>Example 1: Display all processes for the current user</p>\n    <pre><code>ps</code></pre>\n    <p>Output:</p>\n    <pre><code>PID TTY          TIME CMD\n  1234 pts/0    00:00:00 bash\n  5678 pts/0    00:00:00 ps</code></pre>\n  \n    <h3>2. wait Command – Wait for a Process to Complete</h3>\n    <p>The <code>wait</code> command makes the script pause until a process finishes executing.</p>\n    <p>Example:</p>\n    <pre><code>#!/bin/bash\n  echo \"Starting process...\"\n  sleep 5 &   # Run sleep command in the background\n  pid=$!      # Capture process ID\n  echo \"Waiting for process $pid to complete...\"\n  wait $pid   # Wait for process to finish\n  echo \"Process $pid completed!\"</code></pre>\n  \n    <h3>3. sleep Command – Pause Execution for a Specified Time</h3>\n    <p>The <code>sleep</code> command delays execution for a given time.</p>\n    <p>Example:</p>\n    <pre><code>echo \"Waiting for 3 seconds...\"\n  sleep 3\n  echo \"Done!\"</code></pre>\n  \n    <h3>4. exit Command – End a Process</h3>\n    <p>The <code>exit</code> command is used to terminate a script or process.</p>\n    <p>Example:</p>\n    <pre><code>#!/bin/bash\n  echo \"This script will exit now.\"\n  exit 0</code></pre>\n  \n    <h3>5. kill Command – Terminate a Process</h3>\n    <p>The <code>kill</code> command stops a running process using its Process ID (PID).</p>\n    <p>Example:</p>\n    <pre><code>ps aux | grep firefox</code></pre>\n    <p>Output:</p>\n    <pre><code>user      3456  5.0  2.1 21580 12340 ?       S    12:15   0:30 firefox</code></pre>\n    <p>Now, we can kill the process using:</p>\n    <pre><code>kill 3456</code></pre>\n    <p>To force kill a process:</p>\n    <pre><code>kill -9 3456</code></pre>\n    <p>To kill all instances of a program:</p>\n    <pre><code>pkill firefox</code></pre>\n  \n    <h3>Summary of Commands</h3>\n    <table border=\"1\">\n      <tr>\n        <th>Command</th>\n        <th>Function</th>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>ps</td>\n        <td>Displays running processes</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>wait</td>\n        <td>Waits for a process to finish</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>sleep</td>\n        <td>Pauses execution for a specified time</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>exit</td>\n        <td>Ends a process or script</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>kill</td>\n        <td>Stops a process using its PID</td>\n      </tr>\n    </table>\n</div>\n  ','\n[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"Which command is used to view the list of running processes in Linux?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps\",\n        \"exit\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"wait\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"What does the ps command show in Linux?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"List of files\",\n        \"Running processes\",\n        \"List of users\",\n        \"System errors\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Which option with ps command displays all running processes on the system?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps aux\",\n        \"ps -e\",\n        \"ps -f\",\n        \"ps -l\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"What does the \'PID\' column in ps command output represent?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Process ID\",\n        \"Process Information\",\n        \"Program Instance\",\n        \"Process Initialization Date\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"What does the wait command do in a shell script?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Pauses execution for a specified time\",\n        \"Waits for a process to finish\",\n        \"Terminates a process\",\n        \"Exits the script\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Which command pauses the execution for a given number of seconds?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"wait\",\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"exit\",\n        \"ps\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"How long does the sleep command pause execution in the following example? \'sleep 5\'\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"5 minutes\",\n        \"5 seconds\",\n        \"5 hours\",\n        \"5 milliseconds\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Which command is used to exit a process or script in Linux?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps\",\n        \"exit\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"kill\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"What does the exit command return to indicate a successful process termination?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"1\",\n        \"0\",\n        \"exit\",\n        \"done\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"What is the purpose of the kill command in Linux?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Stops a process\",\n        \"Starts a process\",\n        \"Pauses a process\",\n        \"Renames a process\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"Which option is used with the kill command to forcefully stop a process?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"-9\",\n        \"-f\",\n        \"-x\",\n        \"-force\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"What does the command \'kill -9\' do?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Forcefully stops a process\",\n        \"Pauses a process\",\n        \"Starts a process\",\n        \"Waits for a process to finish\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"Which command finds and terminates all instances of a program by name?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"kill\",\n        \"pkill\",\n        \"killall\",\n        \"ps aux\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"Which command is used to display running processes along with their CPU and memory usage?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps aux\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"top\",\n        \"kill\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"What does the \'TTY\' column represent in the output of ps aux?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Time of process\",\n        \"Terminal associated with the process\",\n        \"User who started the process\",\n        \"Memory usage\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"What will the following script do? \'sleep 5 &\' followed by \'wait $pid\'\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Runs sleep in background and waits for it to complete\",\n        \"Runs the script indefinitely\",\n        \"Waits for 5 seconds and ends\",\n        \"Pauses the process indefinitely\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"What does the \'TIME\' column in ps output indicate?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"CPU time used by the process\",\n        \"Time the process started\",\n        \"Time the process was terminated\",\n        \"Time the process was created\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"Which command can be used to view only the processes related to Firefox?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps aux | grep firefox\",\n        \"ps aux | find firefox\",\n        \"ps aux | firefox\",\n        \"ps | grep firefox\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"How do you run a command in the background in Linux?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"command &\",\n        \"command > background\",\n        \"background command\",\n        \"command --bg\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following commands can terminate a process using its PID?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"kill\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"exit\",\n        \"wait\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"Which command will terminate the process with PID 5678?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"kill 5678\",\n        \"pkill 5678\",\n        \"ps kill 5678\",\n        \"killall 5678\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"What is the default exit code for a script that ends successfully?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"1\",\n        \"0\",\n        \"exit\",\n        \"done\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"Which of the following commands is used to forcefully terminate a non-responsive process?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"kill -9\",\n        \"kill -1\",\n        \"ps -9\",\n        \"exit -9\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"In the ps command output, what does the \'STAT\' column represent?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Process status\",\n        \"CPU usage\",\n        \"Memory usage\",\n        \"PID\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"What is the role of the sleep command in a script?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Pauses execution for a specified time\",\n        \"Terminates the script\",\n        \"Starts a process\",\n        \"Waits for a process\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"What is the primary function of the wait command in Linux?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Pauses the script indefinitely\",\n        \"Waits for a process to finish\",\n        \"Kills a process\",\n        \"Exits a script\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"How do you kill all instances of a program named \'firefox\'?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"pkill firefox\",\n        \"kill firefox\",\n        \"killall firefox\",\n        \"kill -9 firefox\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"Which command is used to display the processes in a more detailed view, including memory and CPU usage?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps aux\",\n        \"ps -l\",\n        \"ps -f\",\n        \"ps -e\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"Which command is useful for checking the status of a process before deciding to kill it?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps\",\n        \"top\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"wait\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"What is the function of the \'kill\' command?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Starts a process\",\n        \"Stops a running process\",\n        \"Pauses execution\",\n        \"Waits for process to finish\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"What does the command \'ps aux | grep firefox\' do?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Finds and lists processes related to Firefox\",\n        \"Kills all Firefox processes\",\n        \"Starts a Firefox process\",\n        \"Exits the Firefox process\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"Which command in Linux helps to display the process ID and terminal information of running processes?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"exit\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"How can you view the processes that are running in the background?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps aux\",\n        \"ps background\",\n        \"ps -b\",\n        \"ps -f\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"What does the command \'exit 1\' do in a script?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Exits with an error code\",\n        \"Exits successfully\",\n        \"Pauses the script\",\n        \"Kills the script\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"Which command is used to run a command in the background?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"command &\",\n        \"command > background\",\n        \"background command\",\n        \"command bg\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"What will happen if a process is terminated using the kill command?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"The process will be paused\",\n        \"The process will be stopped\",\n        \"The process will restart\",\n        \"The process will complete\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"Which command waits for a process to finish before continuing with the next task?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"wait\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"exit\",\n        \"sleep\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"Which command is useful for creating a delay between commands in a script?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"exit\",\n        \"kill\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"How can you see the status of multiple running processes at once?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps aux\",\n        \"ps -p\",\n        \"ps -a\",\n        \"ps -f\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"Which of these commands will forcefully terminate a non-responsive process in Linux?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"kill -9\",\n        \"kill -1\",\n        \"kill -x\",\n        \"kill -f\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"Which of these commands can be used to terminate a process using its PID?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"kill\",\n        \"exit\",\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"wait\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"What does the \'RSS\' column in ps aux output represent?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Resident Set Size (memory usage)\",\n        \"Process ID\",\n        \"CPU usage\",\n        \"Time of execution\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"What is the primary purpose of the sleep command?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Pauses execution for a set period\",\n        \"Waits for a process to finish\",\n        \"Exits a process\",\n        \"Kills a process\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"How can you exit a script immediately with an error?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"exit 1\",\n        \"exit 0\",\n        \"exit error\",\n        \"exit\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"Which command can be used to see the detailed list of processes in Linux?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps aux\",\n        \"ps -e\",\n        \"ps -a\",\n        \"ps -l\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"Which command is used to list processes and display CPU and memory usage?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps aux\",\n        \"ps -e\",\n        \"ps -s\",\n        \"ps -p\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"Which command allows you to pause a process for a specified amount of time?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"exit\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"What does the exit command do in a script?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Terminates the script or process\",\n        \"Pauses the process\",\n        \"Waits for a process to finish\",\n        \"Kills a process\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"Which command is used to terminate a specific process in Linux?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"kill\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"exit\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"Which of these commands shows all processes running in the system?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps aux\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"ps -e\",\n        \"ps -l\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    }\n]\n  \n','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is used to display the list of running processes in Linux.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"kill\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"The ps command displays information like Process ID (PID), terminal, and ________ usage.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"CPU\",\n        \"memory\",\n        \"disk\",\n        \"network\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command makes a script pause until a process finishes executing.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"wait\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"kill\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command delays execution for a given time (in seconds, minutes, or hours).\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"exit\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is used to terminate a script or process in Linux.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"exit\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"To forcefully terminate a process, you can use the ________ option with the kill command.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"-9\",\n        \"-f\",\n        \"-kill\",\n        \"-force\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is useful when you need to wait for a process to finish before starting another task.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps\",\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"exit\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command shows all running processes, including their CPU and memory usage.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps aux\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"exit\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command can be used to find the process ID (PID) of a program.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps aux\",\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"wait\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"To end a process in Linux, you use the ________ command.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"exit\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"ps\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is often used to pause execution for a specified time during a script.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"exit\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"The exit command returns a ________ code, which helps in error handling.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"status\",\n        \"process\",\n        \"timeout\",\n        \"file\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is used to pause execution for 3 seconds in a script.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sleep 3\",\n        \"sleep 5\",\n        \"sleep 2\",\n        \"wait 3\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command can be used to terminate all instances of a program.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"kill\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"exit\",\n        \"pkill\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command shows the process ID (PID), terminal, and CPU usage of running processes.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps\",\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"kill\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command ends a process or script without any error handling.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"exit 0\",\n        \"exit 1\",\n        \"kill 0\",\n        \"wait 0\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command can be used to kill a process by its PID in Linux.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"kill\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"sleep\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"You can use the ________ command to terminate a process forcefully by its PID.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"kill -9\",\n        \"ps aux\",\n        \"exit 1\",\n        \"sleep 3\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command will wait for the specified process ID to complete before continuing.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"wait\",\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"exit\",\n        \"ps\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is used to check if a process is running in the background.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"sleep\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is useful when you want to pause execution between iterations in a loop.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"kill\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command can be used to check if a specific file exists before terminating a process.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"exit\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"ps\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is used to check running processes with detailed information such as memory usage.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps aux\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"kill\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is helpful to stop an unresponsive process by using its PID.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"kill\",\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is useful when you want to delay the execution of the script for 5 seconds.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sleep 5\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"kill 5\",\n        \"exit 5\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command can be used to pause execution between each iteration of a loop.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"exit\",\n        \"ps\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command displays all the processes running under the root user.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps aux\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"kill\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is often used to pause the execution of a script during debugging.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"ps\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command can be used to stop a process by its name instead of the PID.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"pkill\",\n        \"ps aux\",\n        \"exit\",\n        \"kill\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command can be used in scripts to ensure that a background process completes before proceeding.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"wait\",\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"kill\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command provides the status of a process, such as CPU time and memory usage.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"kill\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command can be used to run a process in the background while continuing other tasks.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sleep &\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"kill\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command helps to stop a program or process that is taking too long to respond.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"kill\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"sleep\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is used to terminate a running process by its PID in Linux.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"kill\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"sleep\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is often used to add a pause in the execution of a script during automation.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"ps\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command helps to ensure that background tasks are completed before the next step is executed.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"wait\",\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"ps\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is used to monitor and manage processes in Linux.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"exit\",\n        \"wait\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is used to run a process in the background while the terminal remains free for other commands.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sleep &\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"exit\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command pauses a script for 2 seconds during execution.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sleep 2\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait 2\",\n        \"exit\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command can be used to send a kill signal to a process by its name.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"pkill\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"exit\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command helps to check the status of processes running on your system.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"sleep\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is often used when you want to wait for a process to finish before doing something else.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"wait\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"sleep\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command can be used to check the current processes running on your system.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"ps\",\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"exit\",\n        \"kill\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command helps to stop a process or program that has become unresponsive.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"kill\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"sleep\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command returns a success status code when a script ends normally.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"exit 0\",\n        \"exit 1\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"ps\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command pauses for 5 seconds before executing the next line of code in a script.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sleep 5\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait 5\",\n        \"exit\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command can be used to end a process by its name without specifying the PID.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"pkill\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"exit\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is used to forcefully stop a process that is not responding to a normal kill signal.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"kill -9\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"exit\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command pauses for 3 seconds before printing \'Done!\' in a script.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sleep 3\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"wait\",\n        \"kill\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"The ________ command is useful when you want to delay the script execution for debugging purposes.\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"sleep\",\n        \"ps\",\n        \"kill\",\n        \"wait\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    }\n]\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the ps command shows the list of running processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the ps command is used to stop running processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the wait command is used to pause execution until a process finishes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the wait command can terminate a process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the sleep command is used to pause execution for a specified time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the sleep command can be used to stop a process immediately.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the exit command ends a script or process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the exit command waits for a process to finish before ending.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the kill command stops a running process by its Process ID (PID).\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the kill command pauses a process for a specific time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the ps command shows the terminal associated with each process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the ps command provides a list of only system processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the ps aux command displays all running processes on the system.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the ps aux command only shows processes associated with the current user.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the $! variable stores the Process ID of the last background command.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the $! variable is used to store the status code of a process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the exit command can return a status code to indicate success or failure.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the exit command is only used to terminate background processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the kill command can be used to forcefully terminate a process with the -9 option.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the kill command only works for foreground processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the pkill command can terminate all instances of a program.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that pkill only terminates a single instance of a process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the wait command can be used in a script to pause until a process completes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the wait command can be used to terminate a process after waiting.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the sleep command can be used to pause execution for any amount of time.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the sleep command pauses execution indefinitely.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the ps command includes the CPU usage of each process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the ps command does not show the memory usage of processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the ps command displays the command that started each process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the ps command can only show processes related to the current terminal session.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the sleep command can be used inside a loop to delay each iteration.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the sleep command in a loop affects only the first iteration.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the ps aux command includes the user name associated with each process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the ps aux command shows the start time of each process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the kill -9 command forcefully stops a process even if it is unresponsive.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the kill -9 command gracefully terminates a process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the wait command can only be used with processes that run in the background.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the wait command is unnecessary when processes run in the foreground.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the ps command is commonly used to monitor system resource usage.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the ps command can change the priority of running processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the exit command can be used to end a script with a success code.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the exit command can only be used with error codes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the kill command can stop any process using its Process ID.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the kill command requires you to provide a specific user name for the process.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the kill command will stop processes based on their Process ID, regardless of user.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the kill command can stop a process without specifying a Process ID.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the sleep command can be used to delay execution between multiple commands.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the sleep command delays execution permanently until terminated.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the ps command can show processes running in the background.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"It is false that the ps command can only show foreground processes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    }\n]\n  ',13,11),(38,'1.1-Definitions of Management, Role, and Importance of Management','<div>\n    <h1>1.1 Definitions of Management, Role, and Importance of Management</h1>\n    <h2>Introduction</h2>\n    <p>Management is an essential aspect of any organization, whether a business, school, hospital, or government body. It helps in organizing resources, setting goals, and ensuring that everything runs smoothly. In simple terms, management is like a captain steering a ship toward its destination.</p>\n  \n    <h2>Definition of Management</h2>\n    <p>Management is the process of planning, organizing, leading, and controlling resources (people, money, materials, etc.) to achieve a specific goal efficiently and effectively.</p>\n    <h3>Popular Definitions of Management:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Henry Fayol</strong> – \"To manage is to forecast, plan, organize, command, coordinate, and control.\"</li>\n      <li><strong>Peter Drucker</strong> – \"Management is doing things right; leadership is doing the right things.\"</li>\n      <li><strong>Harold Koontz</strong> – \"Management is the art of getting things done through and with people in formally organized groups.\"</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Simple Explanation with Example:</h3>\n    <p>Think of a restaurant manager. They ensure that customers are happy, food is prepared on time, staff members are working efficiently, and expenses are controlled.</p>\n    <p>A school principal manages teachers, students, and staff to ensure smooth education delivery.</p>\n  \n    <h2>Role of Management</h2>\n    <p>Management plays several important roles in an organization. These roles can be categorized into three main types:</p>\n  \n    <h3>1. Interpersonal Roles (People-Oriented Roles)</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Leader</strong> – Motivates employees and guides them to perform well.<br>Example: A sales manager encouraging the sales team to meet monthly targets.</li>\n      <li><strong>Figurehead</strong> – Represents the organization at formal events.<br>Example: A company CEO attending a business conference.</li>\n      <li><strong>Liaison</strong> – Builds relationships with people inside and outside the company.<br>Example: A hospital director coordinating with government health departments.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>2. Informational Roles (Data-Oriented Roles)</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Monitor</strong> – Collects important information for decision-making.<br>Example: A marketing manager analyzing customer feedback to improve a product.</li>\n      <li><strong>Disseminator</strong> – Shares information with employees.<br>Example: An HR manager informing employees about new company policies.</li>\n      <li><strong>Spokesperson</strong> – Represents the company and communicates with the public.<br>Example: A company spokesperson announcing a new product launch.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h3>3. Decisional Roles (Decision-Making Roles)</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Entrepreneur</strong> – Comes up with new ideas and innovations.<br>Example: A business owner launching an eco-friendly product.</li>\n      <li><strong>Disturbance Handler</strong> – Solves unexpected problems.<br>Example: A hotel manager handling a guest complaint about room service.</li>\n      <li><strong>Resource Allocator</strong> – Decides how to distribute resources like money, staff, and materials.<br>Example: A hospital administrator allocating a budget for medical equipment.</li>\n      <li><strong>Negotiator</strong> – Handles negotiations with employees, suppliers, or clients.<br>Example: A company CEO negotiating a business deal with a supplier.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h2>Importance of Management</h2>\n    <p>Management is essential for organizations to run effectively and achieve their goals. Below are some key reasons why management is important:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Achieves Goals Efficiently</strong> – Management ensures that resources (people, money, time) are used in the best possible way to achieve goals.<br>Example: A factory manager improving production processes to reduce waste and increase output.</li>\n      <li><strong>Improves Productivity</strong> – Good management helps employees perform better, increasing overall productivity.<br>Example: A software company’s project manager ensuring developers meet deadlines efficiently.</li>\n      <li><strong>Reduces Wastage of Resources</strong> – Management helps in using resources wisely, preventing wastage.<br>Example: A restaurant owner planning ingredients carefully to minimize food waste.</li>\n      <li><strong>Ensures Stability and Growth</strong> – A well-managed business remains stable even during economic challenges and continues to grow.<br>Example: A small startup expanding into a larger company due to proper financial and operational management.</li>\n      <li><strong>Enhances Teamwork and Motivation</strong> – Good management creates a positive work environment where employees work together effectively.<br>Example: A football coach managing players to work as a team and win games.</li>\n      <li><strong>Encourages Innovation</strong> – Management encourages creativity and new ideas, helping businesses stay competitive.<br>Example: A mobile phone company introducing new technology to stay ahead in the market.</li>\n      <li><strong>Helps in Decision Making</strong> – Managers analyze situations, collect data, and make the best decisions for the organization’s success.<br>Example: A retail store manager deciding which products to stock based on customer demand.</li>\n      <li><strong>Ensures Customer Satisfaction</strong> – By managing customer service, production, and quality, management helps keep customers happy.<br>Example: A hotel manager ensuring clean rooms and friendly service to keep guests satisfied.</li>\n    </ul>\n  \n    <h2>Conclusion</h2>\n    <p>Management is a critical function in any organization. It involves planning, organizing, leading, and controlling resources to achieve goals efficiently. Managers play various roles in handling people, information, and decision-making. Without effective management, businesses and organizations would struggle to operate smoothly and achieve success. Whether it’s a small business, a hospital, or a multinational corporation, management is the backbone of any successful operation.</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is the definition of management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"The process of planning, organizing, leading, and controlling resources to achieve specific goals\",\n        \"Only planning and organizing resources\",\n        \"Only leading and controlling resources\",\n        \"Only managing people\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"What are the main roles of management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Interpersonal, informational, and decisional roles\",\n        \"Only interpersonal roles\",\n        \"Only informational roles\",\n        \"Only decisional roles\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"What is the importance of management in organizations?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"It ensures efficiency, productivity, and stability\",\n        \"It only improves productivity\",\n        \"It only ensures stability\",\n        \"It only enhances teamwork\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"Can management improve innovation in an organization?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Yes\",\n        \"No\",\n        \"Only with specific methods\",\n        \"Only with specific functions\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"What is the role of a leader in management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To motivate employees and guide them to perform well\",\n        \"To only gather information\",\n        \"To only make decisions\",\n        \"To only control resources\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"Can management enhance customer satisfaction?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Yes\",\n        \"No\",\n        \"Only with specific methods\",\n        \"Only with specific functions\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"What is the benefit of effective management in decision-making?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"It helps in analyzing situations and making informed decisions\",\n        \"It does nothing\",\n        \"It only involves planning\",\n        \"It only involves controlling\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"Can management reduce wastage of resources?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Yes\",\n        \"No\",\n        \"Only with specific methods\",\n        \"Only with specific functions\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"What is the effect of good management on organizational stability and growth?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"It ensures stability and growth\",\n        \"It reduces stability and growth\",\n        \"It does nothing\",\n        \"It throws an error\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"Can management improve teamwork and motivation?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Yes\",\n        \"No\",\n        \"Only with specific methods\",\n        \"Only with specific functions\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"What is the role of a figurehead in management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To represent the organization at formal events\",\n        \"To only make decisions\",\n        \"To only gather information\",\n        \"To only control resources\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"Can management encourage innovation?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Yes\",\n        \"No\",\n        \"Only with specific methods\",\n        \"Only with specific functions\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"What is the role of a monitor in management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To collect important information for decision-making\",\n        \"To only make decisions\",\n        \"To only control resources\",\n        \"To only motivate employees\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"What is the benefit of management in ensuring customer satisfaction?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"It ensures quality and service to keep customers happy\",\n        \"It reduces customer satisfaction\",\n        \"It does nothing\",\n        \"It throws an error\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"Can management help in decision-making by analyzing data?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Yes\",\n        \"No\",\n        \"Only with specific methods\",\n        \"Only with specific functions\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"What is the effect of effective management on resource allocation?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"It optimizes resource use\",\n        \"It reduces resource efficiency\",\n        \"It does nothing\",\n        \"It throws an error\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"Can management improve organizational stability?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Yes\",\n        \"No\",\n        \"Only with specific methods\",\n        \"Only with specific functions\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"What is the role of a negotiator in management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To handle negotiations with employees, suppliers, or clients\",\n        \"To only make decisions\",\n        \"To only gather information\",\n        \"To only control resources\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"Can management enhance teamwork?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Yes\",\n        \"No\",\n        \"Only with specific methods\",\n        \"Only with specific functions\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"What is the benefit of management in achieving organizational goals?\",\n      \"