ess.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that management is essential for converting disorganized resources into a useful enterprise.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that management is not essential for converting disorganized resources into a useful enterprise.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that management involves maximizing efficiency through effective resource utilization.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that management does not involve maximizing efficiency through effective resource utilization.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that management is a comprehensive function that includes planning, organizing, leading, and controlling.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that management does not include planning, organizing, leading, and controlling.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that management provides benefits to both the organization and society.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that management does not provide benefits to both the organization and society.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that management involves strategic planning to set long-term goals.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that management does not involve strategic planning to set long-term goals.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that management requires skills like leadership, decision-making, and communication.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that management does not require skills like leadership, decision-making, and communication.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    }\n]\n  ',14,12),(39,'1.2-Management Characteristics and Principles, Levels of Management, and Their Functions','<div>\n    <h1>1.2 Management Characteristics and Principles, Levels of Management, and Their Functions</h1>\n    \n    <h2>1. What is Management?</h2>\n    <p>Management is the process of planning, organizing, leading, and controlling resources (people, money, materials, etc.) to achieve specific goals effectively and efficiently.</p>\n    <p>Imagine you are organizing a birthday party. You need to:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Decide the date, venue, and guest list (Planning)</li>\n      <li>Arrange decorations, food, and music (Organizing)</li>\n      <li>Guide and instruct people to do their tasks (Leading)</li>\n      <li>Ensure everything is happening as planned (Controlling)</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p>This is how management works in businesses, schools, hospitals, and every organization.</p>\n    \n    <h2>2. Characteristics of Management</h2>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Goal-Oriented</strong> – The main purpose of management is to achieve a goal.</li>\n      <li><strong>Continuous Process</strong> – Management is ongoing and never stops.</li>\n      <li><strong>Universal</strong> – Management is required in all types of organizations.</li>\n      <li><strong>Multidisciplinary</strong> – It includes different fields like finance, marketing, and human resources.</li>\n      <li><strong>Dynamic</strong> – Management must adapt to changes in the business environment.</li>\n      <li><strong>Group Activity</strong> – It involves teamwork and cooperation.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>3. Principles of Management</h2>\n    <p>Management principles are guidelines that help managers run an organization efficiently. Henri Fayol introduced 14 principles of management:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Division of Work</strong> – Work should be divided among employees to increase efficiency.</li>\n      <li><strong>Authority and Responsibility</strong> – A manager should have the right to give orders but must also take responsibility.</li>\n      <li><strong>Discipline</strong> – Employees should follow company rules and respect authority.</li>\n      <li><strong>Unity of Command</strong> – An employee should receive orders from only one boss.</li>\n      <li><strong>Unity of Direction</strong> – A team should work towards a common goal under one plan.</li>\n      <li><strong>Remuneration</strong> – Employees should be paid fairly for their work.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>4. Levels of Management and Their Functions</h2>\n    <h3>1. Top-Level Management (Strategic Level)</h3>\n    <p>These are the highest-ranking managers responsible for major decisions.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Who are they? CEOs, Managing Directors, Board of Directors.</li>\n      <li>Functions: Make long-term decisions, set company goals, represent the company to outsiders.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>2. Middle-Level Management (Tactical Level)</h3>\n    <p>These managers act as a link between top and lower levels.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Who are they? Department Managers, Branch Managers.</li>\n      <li>Functions: Implement policies, supervise lower-level managers, ensure team coordination.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h3>3. Lower-Level Management (Operational Level)</h3>\n    <p>They directly handle workers and daily activities.</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Who are they? Supervisors, Team Leaders, Foremen.</li>\n      <li>Functions: Assign tasks, ensure work quality, solve workers’ problems.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>5. Management vs. Administration vs. Organization</h2>\n    <table border=\"1\">\n      <tr>\n        <th>Feature</th>\n        <th>Management</th>\n        <th>Administration</th>\n        <th>Organization</th>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Definition</td>\n        <td>Execution of plans</td>\n        <td>Setting policies</td>\n        <td>A structured setup</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Main Role</td>\n        <td>Implementing goals</td>\n        <td>Deciding goals</td>\n        <td>Coordinating activities</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Hierarchy Level</td>\n        <td>Middle & lower-level managers</td>\n        <td>Top-level executives</td>\n        <td>All levels</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>Example</td>\n        <td>School principal managing teachers</td>\n        <td>Education board setting syllabus</td>\n        <td>School structure (teachers, students, staff)</td>\n      </tr>\n    </table>\n    \n    <h2>6. Relationship Between Management and Administration</h2>\n    <p>Management and administration work together to ensure smooth operations.</p>\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>A hospital’s administration decides to introduce a 24-hour emergency service.</li>\n      <li>The management hires doctors, arranges medical supplies, and sets up shifts.</li>\n      <li>The organization provides doctors, nurses, and infrastructure to run the service.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>Conclusion</h2>\n    <p>Management ensures an organization runs efficiently by planning, organizing, leading, and controlling.</p>\n    <p>It has three levels: top, middle, and lower, each with specific roles.</p>\n    <p>Principles like division of work, unity of command, and discipline help in better management.</p>\n    <p>Management, administration, and organization are interconnected, ensuring an organization functions smoothly.</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is the definition of management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"The process of planning, organizing, leading, and controlling resources\",\n        \"Only planning and organizing resources\",\n        \"Only leading and controlling resources\",\n        \"Only managing people\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"What are the main characteristics of management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Goal-oriented, pervasive, multidimensional, continuous, dynamic, and intangible\",\n        \"Only goal-oriented and pervasive\",\n        \"Only multidimensional and continuous\",\n        \"Only dynamic and intangible\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"What are the levels of management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Top, middle, and lower levels\",\n        \"Only top and middle levels\",\n        \"Only middle and lower levels\",\n        \"Only top level\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"What is the role of top-level management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To make major decisions and set company goals\",\n        \"To implement policies from top management\",\n        \"To assign tasks to workers\",\n        \"To solve workers’ problems\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"What is the role of middle-level management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To implement policies from top management and supervise lower-level managers\",\n        \"To make major decisions and set company goals\",\n        \"To assign tasks to workers\",\n        \"To solve workers’ problems\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"What is the role of lower-level management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To assign tasks to workers and ensure quality of work\",\n        \"To make major decisions and set company goals\",\n        \"To implement policies from top management\",\n        \"To solve workers’ problems\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"What is the relationship between managemen