 expert advice.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that line and staff structures do not use both line authority and expert advice.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that project structures are temporary and flexible.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that project structures are permanent and rigid.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that matrix structures can lead to confusion about reporting lines.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that matrix structures do not lead to confusion about reporting lines.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that organizing is a key management function that helps achieve goals efficiently.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that organizing is not a key management function.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that different organizational structures suit different business needs and sizes.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that different organizational structures do not suit different business needs and sizes.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that network structures focus on outsourcing and partnerships.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that network structures do not focus on outsourcing and partnerships.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    }\n]\n  ',14,12),(43,'1.6-Functional Areas of Management – Detailed Explanation with Examples','<div>\n    <h1>1.6 Functional Areas of Management – Detailed Explanation with Examples</h1>\n    <p>Management is essential for any organization, whether it is a business, hospital, school, or government office. It helps in achieving goals efficiently by organizing resources and ensuring smooth operations. The different aspects of management are divided into functional areas to make work more structured and effective.</p>\n    \n    <h2>What are Functional Areas of Management?</h2>\n    <p>Functional areas of management refer to different key divisions or departments within an organization that focus on specific tasks to achieve overall success. These areas help in the smooth operation of a business by distributing responsibilities among specialized teams.</p>\n    \n    <h2>Major Functional Areas of Management</h2>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Production Management</li>\n      <li>Marketing Management</li>\n      <li>Financial Management</li>\n      <li>Human Resource Management (HRM)</li>\n      <li>Material Management</li>\n      <li>Research and Development (R&D) Management</li>\n      <li>Office Management</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>1. Production Management</h2>\n    <p>Production management deals with the process of producing goods and services. It ensures that products are manufactured efficiently, maintaining quality and cost-effectiveness.</p>\n    <h3>Key Functions:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Planning the production process</li>\n      <li>Managing raw materials and resources</li>\n      <li>Ensuring product quality</li>\n      <li>Reducing production costs</li>\n      <li>Maintaining production schedules</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Example:</h3>\n    <p>A car manufacturing company needs to produce 500 cars per month. The production manager ensures that:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Raw materials (steel, tires, seats, etc.) are available.</li>\n      <li>Workers assemble cars efficiently.</li>\n      <li>Quality checks are conducted to avoid defects.</li>\n      <li>The production process runs smoothly without delays.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>2. Marketing Management</h2>\n    <p>Marketing management focuses on promoting and selling products or services. It helps in identifying customer needs and creating strategies to attract them.</p>\n    <h3>Key Functions:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Market research to understand customer needs</li>\n      <li>Advertising and promotion of products</li>\n      <li>Setting prices and sales strategies</li>\n      <li>Distributing products through different channels</li>\n      <li>Managing customer relationships</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Example:</h3>\n    <p>A mobile phone company launches a new smartphone. The marketing manager:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Conducts a survey to understand what customers want (better camera, battery life, etc.).</li>\n      <li>Sets an attractive price based on market competition.</li>\n      <li>Runs advertisements on TV and social media to promote the phone.</li>\n      <li>Ensures phones are available in stores and online platforms.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>3. Financial Management</h2>\n    <p>Financial management involves handling money, investments, and budgeting. It ensures that the organization has enough funds to operate smoothly.</p>\n    <h3>Key Functions:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Managing income and expenses</li>\n      <li>Budgeting and financial planning</li>\n      <li>Controlling costs and reducing waste</li>\n      <li>Investing in business growth</li>\n      <li>Ensuring profitability</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Example:</h3>\n    <p>A supermarket chain wants to open 10 new stores. The finance manager:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Calculates how much money is needed.</li>\n      <li>Arranges loans or investments.</li>\n      <li>Allocates funds to buy land, shelves, and products.</li>\n      <li>Ensures stores operate profitably by controlling costs.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>4. Human Resource Management (HRM)</h2>\n    <p>HRM is responsible for managing employees, their hiring, training, and overall well-being.</p>\n    <h3>Key Functions:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Recruiting and selecting employees</li>\n      <li>Training and development programs</li>\n      <li>Employee motivation and performance evaluation</li>\n      <li>Salary and benefits management</li>\n      <li>Ensuring a healthy work environment</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Example:</h3>\n    <p>A hotel chain hires 100 new employees. The HR manager:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Conducts interviews and selects skilled workers.</li>\n      <li>Trains them on customer service and hotel operations.</li>\n      <li>Ensures fair salaries and promotions based on performance.</li>\n      <li>Resolves conflicts between employees.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>5. Material Management</h2>\n    <p>Material management ensures that the right materials are available at the right time and place to support production and operations.</p>\n    <h3>Key Functions:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Purchasing raw materials</li>\n      <li>Storing and handling materials efficiently</li>\n      <li>Reducing waste and managing inventory</li>\n      <li>Ensuring timely delivery of materials</li>\n    </ul>\n    <h3>Example:</h3>\n    <p>A construction company building 100 houses needs cement, bricks, and steel. The material manager:</p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Orders the correct quantity of materials.</li>\n      <li>Stores them safely to avoid damage.</li>\n      <li>Ensures materials are available on time to avoid delays.</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>6. Research and Development (R&D) Management</h2>\n    <p>R&D focuses on innovation, improving products, and finding new ways to stay ahead of competitors.</p>\n    <h3>Key Functions:</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Researching new technologies</li>\n      <li>Developing better products</li>\n      <li>Improving manufacturing processes</li>\n      <li>Testing and launching new products</li>\n    </ul>\n    \n    <h2>7. Office Management</h2>\n    <p>Office management ensures that daily operations in an office run smoothly. It includes managing paperwork, communication, and office resources.</p>\n    \n    <h2>Conclusion</h2>\n    <p>Each functional area of management is essential for an organization’s success.</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is the primary function of production management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To manage the production process\",\n        \"To handle financial operations\",\n        \"To manage human resources\",\n        \"To handle marketing\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"What is the purpose of marketing management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To promote and sell products\",\n        \"To manage financial operations\",\n        \"To manage human resources\",\n        \"To handle production\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Can management improve organizational efficiency?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Yes\",\n        \"No\",\n        \"Only with specific methods\",\n        \"Only with specific functions\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"What is the benefit of financial management?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"It helps in budgeting and financial planning\",\n        \"It reduces efficiency\",\n        \"It does nothing\",\n        \"It throws an error\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"Can management enhance employee motivation?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Yes\",\n        \"No\",\n        \"Only with specific methods\",\n        \"Only with specific functions\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"What is the role of a manager in leading employees?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To guide and motivate employees\",\n        \"To only set goals\",\n        \"To only organize