e\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the pass statement is used to avoid syntax errors in incomplete code.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the pass statement is not used to avoid syntax errors in incomplete code.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the else clause in loops is used to handle cases where the loop completes normally without break.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the else clause in loops is not used to handle normal loop completion.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that loop manipulation statements like break and continue are crucial for efficient loop management.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that loop manipulation statements like break and continue are not crucial for efficient loop management.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the break statement is essential for stopping loops based on specific conditions.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the break statement is not essential for stopping loops based on specific conditions.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the continue statement helps in skipping unnecessary iterations in loops.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the continue statement does not help in skipping unnecessary iterations in loops.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    }\n]\n  ',15,16),(67,'3.1-Lists in Python','<div>\n    <h2>3.1 Lists in Python</h2>\n    <h3>Introduction to Lists</h3>\n    <p>A list in Python is a collection of multiple values stored together in a single variable. Lists allow us to store different types of data such as numbers, strings, or even other lists. They are ordered, mutable (changeable), and allow duplicate values.</p>\n    \n    <h3>a) Defining Lists, Accessing Values, Deleting Values, and Updating Lists</h3>\n    <h4>Defining a List</h4>\n    <p>A list is created by enclosing values inside square brackets [ ], separated by commas.</p>\n    \n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        # List of numbers\n        numbers = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50]\n        \n        # List of strings\n        fruits = [\"Apple\", \"Banana\", \"Cherry\"]\n        \n        # Mixed data types\n        mixed = [25, \"Hello\", 3.14, True]\n        \n        # Empty List\n        empty_list = []\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    \n    <h4>Accessing Values in a List</h4>\n    <p>Each item in a list has an index (position number) that starts from 0.</p>\n    \n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        fruits = [\"Apple\", \"Banana\", \"Cherry\"]\n        \n        print(fruits[0])  # Output: Apple\n        print(fruits[1])  # Output: Banana\n        print(fruits[2])  # Output: Cherry\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    \n    <h4>Updating a List</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        numbers = [10, 20, 30, 40]\n        numbers[1] = 99  # Changing value at index 1\n        print(numbers)   # Output: [10, 99, 30, 40]\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    \n    <h4>Deleting Values from a List</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        fruits = [\"Apple\", \"Banana\", \"Cherry\"]\n        del fruits[1]  # Deletes \"Banana\"\n        print(fruits)   # Output: [\"Apple\", \"Cherry\"]\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    \n    <h3>b) Basic List Operations</h3>\n    <h4>Concatenation (Joining Lists)</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        list1 = [1, 2, 3]\n        list2 = [4, 5, 6]\n        combined = list1 + list2\n        print(combined)  # Output: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    \n    <h4>Finding the Length of a List</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        numbers = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50]\n        print(len(numbers))  # Output: 5\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    \n    <h3>c) Built-in List Functions</h3>\n    <h4>Appending an Item</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        fruits = [\"Apple\", \"Banana\"]\n        fruits.append(\"Mango\")\n        print(fruits)  # Output: [\'Apple\', \'Banana\', \'Mango\']\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    \n    <h4>Sorting a List</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        numbers = [5, 2, 9, 1, 7]\n        numbers.sort()\n        print(numbers)  # Output: [1, 2, 5, 7, 9]\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    \n    <h4>Conclusion</h4>\n    <p>Python lists are powerful, flexible, and easy to use. You can store multiple values, modify them, and perform various operations with built-in functions. Lists are widely used in programming for managing data efficiently.</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"How are lists defined in Python?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using parentheses ()\",\n        \"Using square brackets []\",\n        \"Using curly brackets {}\",\n        \"Using angle brackets <>\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"What types of data can be stored in a Python list?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Only numbers\",\n        \"Only strings\",\n        \"Different types including numbers, strings, and lists\",\n        \"Only booleans\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"How do you access the first element of a list in Python?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"list_name[1]\",\n        \"list_name[0]\",\n        \"list_name[-1]\",\n        \"list_name[2]\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"What is the purpose of negative indexing in Python lists?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To access elements from the start of the list\",\n        \"To access elements from the end of the list\",\n        \"To skip elements\",\n        \"To restart the list\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"How do you update an element in a Python list?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"By using the append() method\",\n        \"By assigning a new value to a specific index\",\n        \"By using the insert() method\",\n        \"By using the sort() method\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"What is the effect of using del on a list?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"It removes all elements\",\n        \"It removes a specific element by index\",\n        \"It removes a specific element by value\",\n        \"It does nothing\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"How do you remove an element by value from a list?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using del\",\n        \"Using remove()\",\n        \"Using pop()\",\n        \"Using clear()\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"What does the clear() method do to a list?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Removes the first element\",\n        \"Removes the last element\",\n        \"Removes all elements\",\n        \"Does nothing\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"How do you concatenate two lists in Python?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using the + operator\",\n        \"Using the * operator\",\n        \"Using the append() method\",\n        \"Using the insert() method\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"What is the purpose of the * operator with lists?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To concatenate lists\",\n        \"To repeat a list\",\n        \"To remove elements\",\n        \"To sort elements\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n    