n\": \"It is true that lists in Python are mutable, allowing changes after creation.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that lists in Python are immutable and cannot be changed after creation.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the del statement can be used to delete items from a list.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the del statement cannot be used to delete items from a list.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the remove() method removes an item by value from a list.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the remove() method removes an item by index from a list.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the pop() method removes an item by index and returns its value.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the pop() method removes an item by value and returns its index.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the clear() method removes all elements from a list.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the clear() method does not remove all elements from a list.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that lists can be concatenated using the + operator.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that lists cannot be concatenated using the + operator.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that lists can be repeated using the * operator.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that lists cannot be repeated using the * operator.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the in operator checks if an item exists in a list.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the in operator does not check if an item exists in a list.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the len() function returns the number of elements in a list.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the len() function does not return the number of elements in a list.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that slicing allows extracting a portion of a list.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that slicing does not allow extracting a portion of a list.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the append() method adds an item to the end of a list.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the append() method adds an item to the beginning of a list.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the insert() method inserts an item at a specific position in a list.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the insert() method does not insert an item at a specific position in a list.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the sort() method sorts a list in ascending order.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the sort() method does not sort a list in ascending order.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the reverse() method reverses the order of a list.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the reverse() method does not reverse the order of a list.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the count() method counts the occurrences of a value in a list.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the count() method does not count the occurrences of a value in a list.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the index() method finds the position of an item in a list.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the index() method does not find the position of an item in a list.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the copy() method creates a copy of a list.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the copy() method does not create a copy of a list.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that lists are widely used in programming for managing data efficiently.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that lists are not widely used in programming for managing data efficiently.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    }\n]\n  ',15,17),(68,'3.2-Tuples in Python','<div>\n    <h2>3.2 Tuples in Python</h2>\n    <p>A tuple is a data structure in Python that allows you to store multiple values in a single variable. Tuples are similar to lists but have one key difference: tuples are immutable, meaning that their values cannot be changed after creation.</p>\n    \n    <h3>Example of a Tuple:</h3>\n    <pre><code>fruits = (\"apple\", \"banana\", \"cherry\")\n  print(fruits)  \n  # Output: (\'apple\', \'banana\', \'cherry\')</code></pre>\n    \n    <p>Here, fruits is a tuple containing three elements.</p>\n  \n    <h3>(a) Accessing, Deleting, and Updating Tuples</h3>\n    <h4>1. Accessing Values in Tuples</h4>\n    <p>You can access elements in a tuple using indexing, just like lists. Indexing starts from 0 (zero-based indexing).</p>\n    <pre><code>colors = (\"red\", \"green\", \"blue\", \"yellow\")\n  print(colors[0])  # Output: red\n  print(colors[2])  # Output: blue\n  print(colors[-1]) # Output: yellow</code></pre>\n  \n    <h4>Accessing a Range of Elements (Slicing):</h4>\n    <pre><code>numbers = (10, 20, 30, 40, 50)\n  print(numbers[1:4])  # Output: (20, 30, 40)</code></pre>\n  \n    <h4>2. Deleting Values in Tuples</h4>\n    <p>Since tuples are immutable, you cannot delete individual elements. However, you can delete the entire tuple.</p>\n    <pre><code>fruits = (\"apple\", \"banana\", \"cherry\")\n  del fruits</code></pre>\n  \n    <h4>3. Updating Tuples</h4>\n    <p>Since tuples cannot be changed, you must create a new tuple by concatenating existing tuples.</p>\n    <pre><code>tuple1 = (1, 2, 3)\n  tuple2 = (4, 5, 6)\n  new_tuple = tuple1 + tuple2\n  print(new_tuple)  # Output: (1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6)</code></pre>\n  \n    <h3>(b) Basic Tuple Operations</h3>\n    <h4>1. Concatenation (Joining Tuples)</h4>\n    <pre><code>tuple1 = (1, 2, 3)\n  tuple2 = (4, 5, 6)\n  result = tuple1 + tuple2\n  print(result)  # Output: (1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6)</code></pre>\n  \n    <h4>2. Repetition (Multiplying Tuples)</h4>\n    <pre><code>numbers = (7, 8)\n  result = numbers * 3\n  print(result)  # Output: (7, 8, 7, 8, 7, 8)</code></pre>\n  \n    <h4>3. Checking Membership</h4>\n    <pre><code>fruits = (\"apple\", \"banana\", \"cherry\")\n  print(\"banana\" in fruits)  # Output: True</code></pre>\n  \n    <h4>4. Finding the Length of a Tuple</h4>\n    <pre><code>colors = (\"red\", \"green\", \"blue\")\n  print(len(colors))  # Output: 3</code></pre>\n  \n    <h3>(c) Built-in Tuple Functions</h3>\n    <h4>1. len() – Returns the Length of a Tuple</h4>\n    <pre><code>numbers = (10, 20, 30, 40)\n  print(len(numbers))  # Output: 4</code></pre>\n  \n    <h4>2. max() – Returns the Maximum Value</h4>\n    <pre><code>values = (5, 10, 15, 20)\n  print(max(values))  # Output: 20</code></pre>\n  \n    <h4>3. min() – Returns the Minimum Value</h4>\n    <pre><code>values = (5, 10, 15, 20)\n  print(min(values))  # Output: 5</code></pre>\n  \n    <h4>4. sum() – Returns the Sum of Elements</h4>\n    <pre><code>numbers = (1, 2, 3, 4)\n  print(sum(numbers))  # Output: 10</code></pre>\n  \n    <h4>5. tuple() – Converts a List into a Tuple</h4>\n    <pre><code>my_list = [1, 2, 3]\n  my_tuple = tuple(my_list)\n  print(my_tuple)  # Output: (1, 2, 3)</code></pre>\n  \n    <h4>6. count() – Counts the Occurrences of an Element</h4>\n    <pre><code>numbers = (1, 2, 2, 3, 4, 2)\n  print(numbers.count(2))  # Output: 3</code></pre>\n  \n    <h4>7. index() – Returns the Index of an Element</h4>\n    <pre><code>fruits = (\"apple\", \"banana\", \"cherry\", \"banana\")\n  print(fruits.index(\"banana\"))  # Output: 1</code></pre>\n  \n    <h3>Conclusion</h3>\n    <ul>\n      <li>✔ Tuples are immutable, meaning values cannot be changed after creation.</li>\n      <li>✔ You can access elements using indexing and slicing.</li>\n      <li>✔ Tuples cannot be updated or deleted, but you can create a new tuple.</li>\n      <li>✔ Python provides various tuple operations like concatenation, repetition, and membership checking.</li>\n      <li>✔ There are several built-in functions like len(), max(), min(), sum(), count(), and index() to perform operations on tuples.</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p>Tuples are widely used when you need unchangeable collections of data, such as coordinates, database records, or 