    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that tuples can be repeated using the * operator.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that tuples cannot be repeated using the * operator.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that you can check if an element exists in a tuple using the in keyword.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 28,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that you cannot check if an element exists in a tuple using the in keyword.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 29,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the len() function returns the number of elements in a tuple.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 30,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the len() function does not return the number of elements in a tuple.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 31,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the max() function returns the maximum value in a tuple.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 32,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the max() function does not return the maximum value in a tuple.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 33,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the min() function returns the minimum value in a tuple.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 34,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the min() function does not return the minimum value in a tuple.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 35,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the sum() function returns the sum of elements in a tuple.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 36,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the sum() function does not return the sum of elements in a tuple.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 37,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the tuple() function converts a list into a tuple.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 38,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the tuple() function does not convert a list into a tuple.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 39,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the count() method counts the occurrences of an element in a tuple.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 40,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the count() method does not count the occurrences of an element in a tuple.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 41,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the index() method returns the index of an element in a tuple.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the index() method does not return the index of an element in a tuple.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that tuples are widely used when you need unchangeable collections of data.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that tuples are not widely used when you need unchangeable collections of data.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that tuples support various operations like concatenation and repetition.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that tuples do not support operations like concatenation and repetition.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that tuples can be used for storing constant values or database records.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that tuples cannot be used for storing constant values or database records.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that tuples are similar to lists but have different properties due to immutability.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that tuples are identical to lists in all properties.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    }\n]\n  ',15,17),(69,'3.3-Sets in Python','<div>\n    <h2>3.3 Sets in Python</h2>\n    <p>A set in Python is an unordered collection of unique items. This means that no element can appear more than once, and the items do not have a specific order. Sets are commonly used when you need to store unique values and perform mathematical set operations like union, intersection, and difference.</p>\n    <h3>a) Accessing Values in a Set, Deleting Values, and Updating Sets</h3>\n    <h4>Creating a Set</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        # Creating a set\n        my_set = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}\n        print(my_set)  # Output: {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}\n  \n        # Using set() function\n        another_set = set([10, 20, 30])\n        print(another_set)  # Output: {10, 20, 30}\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h4>Accessing Values in a Set</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        my_set = {\"apple\", \"banana\", \"cherry\"}\n        for item in my_set:\n            print(item)\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h4>Adding Items to a Set</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        fruits = {\"apple\", \"banana\"}\n        fruits.add(\"cherry\")\n        fruits.update([\"orange\", \"grape\"])\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h4>Deleting Values from a Set</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        my_set = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50}\n        my_set.remove(20)\n        my_set.discard(100)\n        popped_item = my_set.pop()\n        my_set.clear()\n        del my_set\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h3>b) Basic Set Operations</h3>\n    <h4>Union</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        set_a = {1, 2, 3}\n        set_b = {3, 4, 5}\n        print(set_a | set_b)  # Output: {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h4>Intersection</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        print(set_a & set_b)  # Output: {3}\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h4>Difference</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        print(set_a - set_b)  # Output: {1, 2}\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h4>Symmetric Difference</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        print(set_a ^ set_b)  # Output: {1, 2, 4, 5}\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h3>c) Built-in Set Functions</h3>\n    <h4>len(), max(), min(), sum()</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        numbers = {10, 25, 35, 5, 15}\n        print(len(numbers))\n        print(max(numbers))\n        print(min(numbers))\n        print(sum(numbers))\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h4>sorted(), any(), all()</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        my_set = {3, 1, 4, 5, 2}\n        print(sorted(my_set))  # Output: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h4>copy()</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n        original_set = {1, 2, 3}\n        copied_set = original_set.copy()\n        print(copied_set)  # Output: {1, 2, 3}\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h3>✨ Conclusion</h3>\n    <p>Sets in Python are perfect for storing unique items, performing mathematical operations, and writing efficient code. They are easy to use, flexible, and come with many built-in functions that simplify common tasks.</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is a key characteristic of sets in Python?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Ordered collection of unique items\",\n        \"Unordered collection of unique items\",\n        \"Ordered collection of duplicate items\",\n        \"Unordered collection of duplicate items\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"How do you create a set in Python?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using square brackets []\",\n        \"Using curly braces {}\",\n        \"Using parentheses ()\",\n        \"Using angle brackets <>\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"Can sets in Python contain duplicate values?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Yes\",\n        \"No\",\n        \"Only if they are numbers\",\n        \"Only if they are strings\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"How do you access elements in a set?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using indexing\",\n        \"Using a for loop\",\n        \"Using the in keyword\",\n        \"All of the above except indexing\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"What is the purpose of the add() method in sets?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To add multiple items\",\n        \"To add a single item\",\n        \"To remove an item\",\n        \"To clear the set\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"How do you add multiple items to a set?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using add()\",\n        \"Using update()\",\n        \"Using insert()\",\n        \"Using append()\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"What does the remove() method do in a set?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Removes a specific item; throws an error if the item doesn\'t exist\",\n        \"Removes a specific item; does nothing if the item doesn\'t exist\",\n        \"Removes all items\",\n        \"Removes a random item\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"What is the difference between remove() and discard() in sets?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"remove() does nothing if the item doesn\'t exist, discard() throws an error\",\n        \"remove() throws an error if the item doesn\'t exist, discard() does nothing\",\n        \"remove() removes all items, discard() removes a specific item\",\n        \"remove() removes a random item, discard() removes all items\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"What does the pop() method do in a set?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Removes a specific item\",\n        \"Removes a random item\",\n        \"Removes all items\",\n        \"Does nothing\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"How do you delete an entire set?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using del statement\",\n        \"Using remove() method\",\n        \"Using pop() method\",\n        \"Using clear() method\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"question\": \"What is the union operation in sets?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Combines all unique items from both sets\",\n        \"Finds common items between both sets\",\n        \"Finds items present in one set but not the other\",\n        \"Finds items not common to both sets\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"question\": \"How do you perform a union operation in Python?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using the & operator\",\n        \"Using the | operator\",\n        \"Using the union() method\",\n        \"All of the above except & operator\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"question\": \"What is the intersection operation in sets?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Finds common items between both sets\",\n        \"Finds items present in one set but not the other\",\n        \"Finds items not common to both sets\",\n        \"Combines all unique items from both sets\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"question\": \"How do you perform an intersection operation in Python?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using the | operator\",\n        \"Using the & operator\",\n        \"Using the intersection() method\",\n        \"All of the above except | operator\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"question\": \"What is the difference operation in sets?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Finds items present in one set but not the other\",\n        \"Finds common items between both sets\",\n        \"Finds items not common to both sets\",\n        \"Combines all unique items from both sets\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"question\": \"How do you perform a difference operation in Python?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using the - operator\",\n        \"Using the difference() method\",\n        \"Using the union() method\",\n        \"Using the intersection() method\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"question\": \"What is the symmetric difference operation in sets?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Finds items not common to both sets\",\n        \"Finds common items between both sets\",\n        \"Finds items present in one set but not the other\",\n        \"Combines all unique items from both sets\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 18,\n      \"question\": \"How do you perform a symmetric difference operation in Python?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using the ^ operator\",\n        \"Using the symmetric_difference() method\",\n        \"Using the union() method\",\n        \"Using the intersection() method\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 19,\n      \"question\": \"What does the len() function return for a set?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"The first element\",\n        \"The last element\",\n        \"The number of elements\",\n        \"The type of elements\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 20,\n      \"question\": \"How do you find the maximum value in a set?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using max()\",\n        \"Using min()\",\n        \"Using sum()\",\n        \"Using len()\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 21,\n      \"question\": \"What does the sum() function do for a set?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Returns the sum of all elements\",\n        \"Returns the maximum value\",\n        \"Returns the minimum value\",\n        \"Returns the number of elements\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 22,\n      \"question\": \"How do you sort the elements of a set?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using sorted()\",\n        \"Using sort()\",\n        \"Using max()\",\n        \"Using min()\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 23,\n      \"question\": \"What does the any() function do for a set?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Returns True if all items are truthy\",\n        \"Returns True if at least one item is truthy\",\n        \"Returns False if all items are truthy\",\n        \"Returns False if at least one item is truthy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 24,\n      \"question\": \"What does the all() function do for a set?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Returns True if at least one item is truthy\",\n        \"Returns True if all items are truthy\",\n        \"Returns False if at least one item is truthy\",\n        \"Returns False if all items are truthy\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 25,\n      \"question\": \"How do you create a copy of a set?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using copy()\",\n        \"Using add()\",\n        \"Using update()\",\n        \"Using remove()\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 26,\n      \"question\": \"Can you use indexing to access elements in a set?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Yes\",\n        \"No\",\n        \"Only with specific methods\",\n        \"Only with specific functions\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 27,\n      \"question\": \"What is the purpose of the update() method in sets?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To add a single item\",\n        \"To add multiple items\",\n        \