ue\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 42,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the all() function does not return True if all items in a set are truthy.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 43,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the copy() method returns a shallow copy of a set.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 44,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that the copy() method does not return a shallow copy of a set.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 45,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that sets in Python are commonly used for storing unique values and performing mathematical operations.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 46,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that sets in Python are not commonly used for storing unique values or performing mathematical operations.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 47,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that sets in Python are mutable, allowing items to be added or removed.\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 48,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that sets in Python are immutable, not allowing items to be added or removed.\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 49,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that sets in Python support various built-in functions like len(), max(), min(), and sum().\",\n      \"answer\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 50,\n      \"question\": \"It is true that sets in Python do not support built-in functions like len(), max(), min(), and sum().\",\n      \"answer\": false\n    }\n]\n  ',15,17),(70,'3.4-Dictionaries in Python','<div>\n    <h2>3.4 Dictionaries in Python</h2>\n    <p>A dictionary in Python is a collection of key-value pairs. It is used to store data in an organized way, where each key has a corresponding value.</p>\n    <h3>What is a Dictionary?</h3>\n    <p>A dictionary is written using curly brackets {}, and the key-value pairs are separated by colons :</p>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n  # Creating a dictionary\n  student = {\n      \"name\": \"John\",\n      \"age\": 20,\n      \"grade\": \"A\"\n  }\n  print(student)\n  # Output: {\'name\': \'John\', \'age\': 20, \'grade\': \'A\'}\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h3>(a) Accessing, Deleting, and Updating Dictionary Values</h3>\n    <h4>1. Accessing Values in a Dictionary</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n  print(student[\"name\"])  # Output: John\n  print(student[\"age\"])   # Output: 20\n  print(student.get(\"grade\"))  # Output: A\n  print(student.get(\"city\", \"Not Found\"))  # Output: Not Found\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h4>2. Updating a Dictionary</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n  student[\"age\"] = 21\n  student[\"city\"] = \"New York\"\n  print(student)\n  # Output: {\'name\': \'John\', \'age\': 21, \'grade\': \'A\', \'city\': \'New York\'}\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h4>3. Deleting Values from a Dictionary</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n  del student[\"city\"]\n  print(student)\n  # Output: {\'name\': \'John\', \'age\': 21, \'grade\': \'A\'}\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h3>(b) Basic Dictionary Operations</h3>\n    <h4>1. Finding the Length of a Dictionary</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n  print(len(student))  # Output: 3\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h4>2. Checking if a Key Exists</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n  if \"age\" in student:\n      print(\"Key exists!\")  # Output: Key exists!\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h4>3. Looping Through a Dictionary</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n  for key, value in student.items():\n      print(f\"{key}: {value}\")\n  # Output:\n  # name: John\n  # age: 21\n  # grade: A\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h3>(c) Built-in Dictionary Functions</h3>\n    <h4>1. keys() - Get All Keys</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n  print(student.keys())  # Output: dict_keys([\'name\', \'age\', \'grade\'])\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h4>2. values() - Get All Values</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n  print(student.values())  # Output: dict_values([\'John\', 21, \'A\'])\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h4>3. items() - Get All Key-Value Pairs</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n  print(student.items())  # Output: dict_items([(\'name\', \'John\'), (\'age\', 21), (\'grade\', \'A\')])\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h4>4. update() - Merge Dictionaries</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n  new_info = {\"city\": \"New York\", \"phone\": \"1234567890\"}\n  student.update(new_info)\n  print(student)\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h4>5. copy() - Copy a Dictionary</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n  copy_dict = student.copy()\n  print(copy_dict)\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h4>6. popitem() - Remove the Last Item</h4>\n    <pre>\n      <code>\n  student.popitem()\n  print(student)\n      </code>\n    </pre>\n    <h3>Conclusion</h3>\n    <p>Dictionaries are an essential part of Python and provide a fast, flexible way to store and retrieve data. You can use them for various tasks such as storing user details, keeping track of products in a store, and more.</p>\n</div>\n  ','[\n    {\n      \"id\": 1,\n      \"question\": \"What is a dictionary in Python?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"A collection of key-value pairs\",\n        \"A collection of unique values\",\n        \"A collection of ordered items\",\n        \"A collection of unordered items\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 2,\n      \"question\": \"How do you define a dictionary in Python?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using square brackets []\",\n        \"Using curly brackets {}\",\n        \"Using parentheses ()\",\n        \"Using angle brackets <>\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"question\": \"What is the purpose of keys in a dictionary?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"To store values\",\n        \"To access values\",\n        \"To store keys\",\n        \"To access keys\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"question\": \"How do you access a value in a dictionary?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using numerical indexes\",\n        \"Using keys\",\n        \"Using the in keyword\",\n        \"Using the get() method\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"question\": \"What does the get() method do in a dictionary?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Returns a value if the key exists, otherwise throws an error\",\n        \"Returns a value if the key exists, otherwise returns a default value\",\n        \"Adds a new key-value pair\",\n        \"Removes a key-value pair\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 2\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"question\": \"How do you update a value in a dictionary?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using the update() method\",\n        \"Using the add() method\",\n        \"By assigning a new value to a key\",\n        \"Using the append() method\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"question\": \"How do you add a new key-value pair to a dictionary?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using the update() method\",\n        \"Using the add() method\",\n        \"By assigning a value to a new key\",\n        \"Using the append() method\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"question\": \"What does the del statement do to a dictionary?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Removes a specific key-value pair\",\n        \"Removes all key-value pairs\",\n        \"Deletes the entire dictionary\",\n        \"Does nothing\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"question\": \"How do you remove a key-value pair using a method?\",\n      \"options\": [\n        \"Using pop()\",\n        \"Using remove()\",\n        \"Using delete()\",\n        \"Using clear()\"\n      ],\n      \"answer\": 1\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"question\": \"What does the clear() method do to a dictionary?\",\n      \"opti